<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Korea-USFirebombing     11-17 0377</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea-US Firebombing,0392</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Attackers Raid U.S. Housing Area, Wound Two</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Forty youths wielding iron pipes and
clubs hurled firebombs on Thursday at a housing complex for families
of U.S. troops, U.S. authorities said. Two servicemen were wounded.
   The assailants, believed to be radical students, escaped after
damaging or destroying nine military vehicles and passenger cars,
the officials said.
   Attackers yelled ``Yankee go home!'' during the evening assault
about one mile from the U.S. 8th Army headquarters near central
Seoul, authorities said.
   Ten firebombs exploded and caused at least $15,000 in damage,
said a military spokesman.
   Gen. Louis C. Menetrey, who commands U.S. forces in Korea, issued
a statement Friday calling the attackers ``cowardly criminals.''
U.S. officials said security was increased at the housing complex.
   A U.S. Army spokesman said the youths attacked the back gate of
the Hannam Village complex, which houses about 2,500 military
dependents. At least 15 youths got inside, he said, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   The spokesman said the back gate is used for road traffic and was
open, with two guards on duty. He said additional help was called,
but the attackers fled.
   An Army news release said a U.S. military policeman was hurt when
the youths hit him with iron pipes. A U.S. officer was injured when
a pipe was thrown through the windshield of his car.
   The soldiers' identities were withheld.
   Hannam Village is leased from the Korean National Housing Corp.
for use by U.S. military dependents. It faces Dankook University.
Radical students attacked the housing area front gate twice in
October with no reports of injury.
   In central Seoul on Thursday, riot police battled thousands of
farmers chanting ``Drive out the Yankees!'' and trying to march on
the U.S. Embassy to protest American farm imports.
   About 2,000 riot police blocked an estimated 7,000 farmers and
other protesters.
   Hundreds of protesters hurled rocks and bricks at police and
attacked troopers with clubs after the march was blocked a few
hundred yards from the embassy. Students joined the march and threw
a few firebombs at police.
   The United States has been pressuring South Korea to open its
markets to American imports, especially agricultural products, to
help ease Washington's $10 billion annual trade deficit with Seoul.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
