<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Smith-Execution 3rdLd-Writethru a0788 11-17 0551</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Smith-Execution, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0788,0561</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Smith's Fate Again Up to 8th Circuit</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEDES with 4 grafs to UPDATE with Supreme Court's action;
picks up 4th graf pvs, `Smith, 30...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KAREN BALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JEFFERSON CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Supreme Court refused late
Thursday to lift a stay of execution for man who killed an inmate in
a dispute over a diamond ring, marking the second time the man's
execution has been blocked against his wishes.
   In a ruling handed down shortly after 9 p.m. CST, the Supreme
Court denied the state's motion to vacate a stay that had been
issued to Gerald Smith earlier Thursday by the 8th U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals in St. Louis.
   In a 7-3 ruling handed down about 5 p.m. in St. Louis, the court
said it needed more time to review Smith's case, including the issue
of whether he is competent to abandon his appeals. Smith had been
scheduled to die at 12:01 a.m. Friday.
   The execution would have been the first in Missouri since 1965,
the first under the state's 11-year-old reinstated capital
punishment law and the first use of lethal injection, a change from
the former gas chamber.
   Smith, 30, has said he wants to die now rather than spend years
on death row awaiting ``the inevitable.''
   Smith's wife, Lynn, filed a petition with the court earlier
Thursday, seeking to stop the execution, contending Smith is not
competent to abandon his appeals. The Missouri Public Defenders
Commission had asked the U.S. Supreme Court for a stay.
   Smith was sentenced to die for the 1985 stabbing death of inmate
Robert Baker. He also had been scheduled to die Oct. 4 for the 1980
beating death of Karen Roberts, a former girlfriend, but the 8th
Circuit stayed that execution, saying it needed more time to
determine if Smith was competent to abandon his appeals.
   Authorities said Baker was killed in a dispute over a diamond
ring, although Smith said he committed the murder so he could be
executed. Smith has said he killed Ms. Roberts because she gave him
a venereal disease and caused him to lose his fiancee.
   Last month, Mrs. Smith stood by her husband in his decision to
abandon his appeals, but recently decided to challenge his
competency and try to get the latest execution halted. Mrs. Smith, a
registered nurse from California, got to know Smith through letters
and married him last year in the prison.
   ``Gerald Smith is a very sick and emotionally disturbed young man
who is not competent to decide whether to abandon his appeals and
acquiesce in his execution,'' said Mrs. Smith's motion for a stay.
   The state's response contended Smith's competency has already
been established and criticized Mrs. Smith for her ``eleventh hour''
request for a stay.
   In a telephone interview from the prison Wednesday, Smith said
his wife had joined forces with those trying to save him because she
had been ``brainwashed.''
   ``Apparently they told her it would come off and she is their
only chance to stop it,'' Smith said. ``They told her that with her
there is a 90 percent chance of stopping it.''
   Smith has vowed to start a hunger strike and threatened to commit
violence against others if his execution is halted by the courts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
