<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Dollar-Markets 1stLd-Writethru a0793 11-17 0359</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0793,0364</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Strong Central Bank Intervention Stabilizes Dollar</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 1 graf to UPDATE with early Friday dollar trading in
Japan; longer version moved on financial wires.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Fed-Dollar</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Major central banks came to the dollar's rescue
Thursday in a united buying spree that stabilized the weakening
currency. But analysts warned the recovery might be short-lived
because of continued concerns about the U.S. trade and budget
deficits.
   The coordinated worldwide buying of dollars by central banks
appeared to be the heaviest since the spring, and it lent some
support to the slumping stock market, which has been keeping a keen
eye on dollar activity.
   On Wall Street, the Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks
closed up 13.87 points at 2,052.45. But the rebound still left the
market's best known measure down about 75 points over seven sessions.
   Bond prices slipped, pushing interest rates higher. The yield on
the Treasury's bellwether 30-year bond rose to 9.15 percent from
9.11 percent, although some analysts blamed the decline on the
Treasury's auction of long-term bonds Thursday rather than the
action in the currency markets.
   Investors in the financial markets worry that a weak dollar could
drive up interest rates and spark higher inflation, since it would
raise prices of imports and some domestic commodities.
   Currency traders said the central-bank intervention began without
much success in Tokyo, as heavy buying of the dollar by the Bank of
Japan did not keep the U.S. currency from dropping to a near 40-year
low of 121.5 yen.
   The Federal Reserve Bank began selling yen for dollars in New
York, and the West German Bundesbank also bought up dollars to
reduce the supply of the U.S. currency on the market, traders said.
The central banks of Britain, Switzerland, France, Italy, Austria
and other nations then joined in.
   The dollar rebounded to about 122.6 yen in Europe before slipping
to 122.2 in New York. The dollar gained ground against all other
major currencies.
   On Friday morning in Japan, the dollar opened at 122.15 yen, and
by midmorning was trading at about 122.23 yen.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
