<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Thatcher 1stLd-Writethru a0691 11-17 0619</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Thatcher, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0691,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mrs. Thatcher: Palestinian Declaration Offers `Signs of Hope'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf pvs bgng, `Speaking to,' with 2 grafs and SUBS
12th graf pvs bgng, `Mrs. Thatcher reaffirmed,' with 4 grafs to
UPDATE with comments on Cold War</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher said
Thursday the recent Palestine Liberation Organization policy
statement offers ``signs of hope'' that should be explored through a
revived Middle East peace effort.
   At a news conference, Mrs. Thatcher said acceptance by the PLO
parliament in exile of two key United Nations resolutions on the
Middle East represents a ``modest step forward'' on which progress
toward peace could be made.
   And in a separate interview with reporters and editors of The
Washington Post and Newsweek magazine, the prime minister declared
that the policies of Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev have ended
the Cold War between the East and the West.
   At a news conference shortly before ending her two-day visit
here, Mrs. Thatcher offered a slightly more upbeat appraisal of the
declaration by the Palestine National Council than the Reagan
administration.
   The State Department said Wednesday ``more movement on key
issues'' will be required by the PLO before the United States
regards it as ready to participate in the Middle East peace process.
   But Mrs. Thatcher said the indications of PLO flexibility should
be encouraged, otherwise ``you won't get further moves.''
   She called for a ``strenuous effort,'' including heavy pressure
on both Israel and the Arabs, to get peace negotiations started.
   On the specifics of the declaration, Mrs. Thatcher indicated that
she shares the administration's views.
   While offering restrained praise for the PNC stand on U.N.
Security Council resolutions 242 and 338, Mrs. Thatcher said she
opposes the PNC proclamation establishing an independent state and
added the declaration did not go far enough in repudiating terrorism.
   ``Obviously there are a lot of things in it that none of us
like,'' she said.
   The two U.N. resolutions call for Israeli withdrawal from
occupied territories and asserts the right of all countries in the
area to live within secure borders.
   The administration has said the PLO declaration on the
resolutions was ``an advance'' compared with previous statements.
But it said the council declaration as a whole falls short of U.S.
requirements for opening a dialogue with the PLO.
   During the hour-long interview with The Washington Post and
Newsweek, Mrs. Thatcher said, ``We're not in a Cold War now'' but in
a ``new relationship much wider than the Cold War ever was,''
according to a story in the Post's Friday editions.
   Gorbachev's policies have affected East-West relations
profoundly, Mrs. Thatcher said, adding that the previous ``minimal
relationship'' with Moscow that focused on arms control has expanded
to include trade, culture and other major issues.
   ``I expect Mr. Gorbachev to do everything he can to continue his
reforms,'' she said. ``We will support it.''
   At the news conference, Mrs. Thatcher reaffirmed her high regard
for President-elect George Bush, citing his extensive experience in
government as a major asset.
   ``You will have a president who doesn't have to be briefed,'' she
said.
   She said Bush has carried out his many missions to Europe as vice
president ``superbly,'' including his effort to ensure U.S.
intermediate-range missiles were installed in allied countries on
time in 1983.
   Before a breakfast meeting with Bush on Thursday, Mrs. Thatcher
said she had ``not the slightest shadow of a doubt'' that Bush will
deal responsibly with the budget deficit.
   She offered similar expressions of confidence in Bush and the
U.S. economy in network television interviews she had at her
temporary residence in the Blair House, across the street from the
White House.
</TEXT>
