<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Scarfo-Racketeering     11-17 0516</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Scarfo-Racketeering,0534</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Final Arguments Made in Scarfo Racketeering Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE LINDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prosecutor told jurors Wednesday that
reputed mob boss Nicodemo ``Little Nicky'' Scarfo and 16 associates
should be convicted of racketeering based on their own recorded
words.
   Defense lawyers, in their final arguments, said the government
relied on liars and hearsay to form its case.
   ``According to the defendants, all the witnesses lied. And the
defendants tell you that the Mafia is a figment of the imagination
of (informants) DelGiorna and Caramandi,'' Assistant U.S. Attorney
Arnold Gordon said. ``Now that is not true. There is a mob. The
evidence has proven it.''
   Gordon's statements came after the jury heard from the last of
the defense lawyers, Robert Simone, who represents Scarfo.
   The 59-year-old Scarfo, who authorities say heads the Mafia in
the Philadelphia-southern New Jersey area, and his 16 associates are
standing trial on federal racketeering charges, which include
allegations of nine murders, extortion and loan sharking.
   The jurors, sequestered since the two-month trial began, are
scheduled to receive instructions from U.S. District Judge Franklin
VanAntwerpen Thursday morning before beginning deliberations.
   Simone suggested the government was trying to prove his client
guilty through newspaper stories identifying Scarfo as a mob boss,
not by evidence.
   ``That's how they want to prove the Mafia exists and that's how
they want to prove his guilt,'' Simone said.
   Simone, like the other defense lawyers, hammered hard at the two
star government witnesses, Thomas DelGiorno and Nicholas Caramandi.
Both accepted government plea bargains and are under government
protection.
   ``Is it possible for you to remove from your notes or remove from
your minds the testimony of Caramandi and DelGiorno and other
government witnesses?'' Simone asked. ``If you do, you will find
that the government case will collapse like a house of cards.''
   But Gordon noted that, besides the testimony, the government
presented 15 to 20 hours of secretly recorded conversations.
   ``You heard Scarfo on the tape, and what he was talking about
with others,'' Gordon said. ``They were talking about the Mafia.
Their words.
   ``It is on the basis of those words that the government wants you
to find these defendants guilty, not on newspaper articles.''
   Gordon acknowledged that a good deal of the evidence came from
the two informants.
   ``The defense would like you to believe that DelGiorno and
Caramandi told you lies, and that there is no case, but that is not
true,`` Gordon said.
   Gordon acknowledged that the two witnesses were criminals, but
said they were government witnesses ``because that's how you
prosecute mob members.''
   ``(Law-abiding citizens) don't associate with the kind of people
the evidence shows these defendants are. The only people who can
tell you about the mob and how it works are people inside the mob.
   ``People like Caramandi and DelGiorno are not found among honest
citizens. They are found in the sewers of the underworld.''
   On the basis of testimony from DelGiorno and Caramandi a year
ago, Scarfo and former City Councilman Leland Beloff were convicted
of trying to extort $1 million from a developer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
