<1ST_LINE>r i PM-FrugalFuneral     11-17 0227</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Frugal Funeral,0235</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Plans $180 Funeral, `No Rip Off' Epitaph</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EXETER, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Teddy Corbett-Winder has organized his own
funeral to avoid bothering anyone with a mortician's bill.
   The 72-year-old retired businessman is ready to meet his maker
for a bargain price of less than $180.
   A carpenter made a chipboard box coffin for less than $125, and a
friend will take him to his final resting place in a station wagon.
   Corbett-Winder keeps dirty laundry in the coffin under his bed at
his home in Exeter, southwest England, until it is needed.
   ``All they will have to do is roll me out of my bed and straight
into the box,'' he said.
   He has also written his epitaph: ``Edmund Frederick
Corbett-Winder, 1916-? No Rip Off.''
   ``I'm deadly serious. Funerals can cost more than 1,000 pounds
($1,800) and I'm not leaving any cash to the funeral directors,'' he
said. ``Once I've slipped a few quid (pounds) to my mates to carry
the coffin and paid the cremation fee it will be very cheap.''
   He has already had a trial run for his cremation. ``It was
beautiful, but a bit hard on the backside. I'll have to put in a
cushion and pillow,'' he said.
   Corbett-Winder, a grandfather, said he will leave all his money
to the Exeter Hospice, where he works as a volunteer.
</TEXT>
