<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-88 0049EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SouthernBaptistRdp     11-17 0607</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Southern Baptist Rdp,0621</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Old Arguments Pop Up In State Southern Baptist Conventions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Southern Baptists convening in 11 states decided Wednesday to
give a little less to charity, interpret the Bible for themselves
and work seriously toward uniting moderate and conservative factions
in the nation's largest Protestant denomination.
   Southern Baptists from Alabama, Florida, Georgia, Kentucky,
Louisiana, Mississippi, North Carolina, Oklahoma, South Carolina,
Tennessee and Virginia have been meeting most of this week to elect
new officers and define bylaws tht govern the Southern Baptist
Convention.
   Always present during the proceedings is a power struggle between
moderate Baptists, who believe the Bible is authoritative but open
to scholarly interpretation, and fundamentalists, who take a literal
interpretation of the Bible and have controlled the 14.7
million-member denomination for the past decade.
   In Florida, Southern Baptists voted to cut back the
denomination's donation to national and international causes.
   Some 2,200 Baptists, gathered at 127th annual Florida State
Baptist Convention in Lakeland, Tuesday approved giving to charity
47.65 percent, or $10.3 million of their $21.6 million budget next
year, down from 50 percent.
   The Rev. Jack Snell, chairman of the budget-allocations
committee, said budget requests are up $500,000 from last year, most
of it due to debt payments, salary adjustments, program increases
and such expenses as insurance.
   Florida Baptists elected as their president the Rev. Bill
Billingsley, a 54-year-old pastor from Hollywood. Al Townsend Jr., a
layman from Niceville, was elected first vice president.
   In Georgia, Baptists closed their three-day convention with a
vote that reaffirmed Baptists' right to interpret the Bible as they
see it. During Wednesday's final session, a resolution that says
pastors can encourage members to ``exercise the traditional
privileges and rights of believers as priests'' passed on a 791-629
vote.
   The moderate-backed resolution challenged a measure passed by the
national convention that gave pastors more authority for running
their churches and interpreting scriptures for their congregations.
   Convention delegates also voted on six resolutions that could
affect policies at more than 3,000 affiliated churches. Among the
resolutions were official statements opposing pornography, abortion
and legalized gambling. The gambling resolution warned Baptists that
the state legislature will soon consider establishing a lottery.
   The Alabama Baptist State Convention ended Wednesday with a new
president being selected by acclamation for the first time in
decades.
   The Rev. Charles Carter, a conservative Birmingham pastor, was
the only candidate nominated to succeed layman Steve Tondera, who
served the customary two years as convention president.
   ``I would describe my posture as bridge building or centrist,''
Carter said. ``By concentrating on that on which we agree, we can
continue to defuse that on which we disagree. I put that as a
priority.''
   Tennessee Baptists agreed Wednesday to open several group homes
for retarded adults in Tennessee, approved a $25.8 million budget,
selected Calvin Metcalf of Knoxville as the group's president and
decided to support a three-year missions partnership with the
Philippines.
   The Mississippi Baptist Convention on Wednesday denounced
criticism leveled at slain civil rights leader Martin Luther King
Jr. by a state denomination leader earlier this year. The convention
adopted a resolution condemning remarks made by Curtis Caine of
Jackson that praised South African apartheid and labeled King as a
fraud.
   The convention's 1,961 delegates also voted unanimously to elect
the Rev. Jim Futral, pastor of a Jackson church, to a second
one-year term as president.
   In Virginia, Baptists said they may reconsider their funding of
convention ministries. About 2,500 messengers, or delegates, from
congregations across the state approved moderate-backed statements
saying they would do so unless the convention provides ``more direct
communication, accountability and flexibility regarding matters of
conscience.''
</TEXT>
