<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Cincinnati-Handguns     11-17 0192</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cincinnati-Handguns,0197</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cincinnati Approves Handgun Law</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The City Council on Wednesday overrode intense
opposition by the National Rifle Association and enacted a law
requiring prospective handgun owners to wait 15 days before picking
up their weapons.
   The ordinance, approved 7-2, takes effect Dec. 16.
   Mayor Charles J. Luken, a council member who proposed the
ordinance, praised the council for passing the law over the NRA's
pressure. The pressure included a deluge of letters and telephone
calls to council members, and booing and heckling to drown out
people who spoke in favor of the proposal at the council's public
hearing Tuesday.
   Richard Gardiner, an NRA assistant general counsel in Washington,
said Cincinnati's law appears to be broader than that of some other
cities in that it applies to handgun sales by individuals as well as
dealers. Gardiner said that without seeing a copy of Cincinnati's
law, he could not say whether the NRA would try to challenge it in
the courts.
   Some other cities and states, including California, also require
waiting periods before allowing purchase of handguns.
   The U.S. House on Sept. 15 rejected a proposed seven-day waiting
period.
</TEXT>
