<1ST_LINE>r i PM-NIreland-Weapons     11-17 0286</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-NIreland-Weapons,0295</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arms Could Have Been Used Against Republic, King Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities arrested 10 people
and seized a rocket-powered grenade launcher, rifles, warheads and
other weapons believed to belong to Protestant loyalist guerrillas.
   Northern Ireland Secretary Tom King said the huge arms cache
found in British-ruled Northern Ireland on Wednesday could have been
used against targets in the Irish Republic.
   The Royal Ulster Constabulary, the province's police force, said
it arrested 10 people after seizing the arms in a predominantly
Protestant public housing project 30 miles southwest of Belfast.
   It said the weapons included a rocket-propelled grenade launcher
and five warheads, rifles, hand grenades, more than 12,000 rounds of
ammunition and inoperative scrap parts for a missile launcher.
   ``Here we have an apprehension by the police of what appear to be
loyalist weapons which, no doubt, could have been used against
targets in the republic,'' King told reporters at Stormont Castle,
the seat of government in Northern Ireland.
   ``I think it clearly indicates the importance and the effect of
increased cooperation on security,'' he said.
   Loyalist is the term used for the province's Protestant majority,
who want to remain under the British flag as part of the United
Kingdom and not merge with the overwhelmingly Roman Catholic Irish
Republic.
   Northern Ireland police said earlier that so far this year they
recovered from Catholic and Protestant guerrilla groups 438 guns,
90,000 rounds of ammunition, 9,600 pounds of explosives, 111 rockets
and mortars and 200 pounds of plastic explosive.
   Another 8,300 pounds of explosive was recovered from defused
bombs.
   The mainly Catholic and outlawed Irish Republican Army is
fighting to end British rule in Northern Ireland and unite it with
the republic.
</TEXT>
