<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Bush     11-17 0301</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush's Role In Gorbachev Meeting Will Be As VP</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush's role in next month's meeting
between President Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev will
be as vice president, and any discussions about Bush's future
dealings with the Kremlin leader will be ``fairly brief,'' a
spokesman said.
   Bush, the president-elect, will be attending the talks in New
York with Reagan when the Soviet leader is in town to address the
United Nations.
   ``It should not be expected that the meeting is being designed as
a summit or designed with a set of objectives in mind that would be
the kinds of things that we would hope for in a future meeting,''
Craig Fuller, a co-director of Bush's transition team, said
Wednesday.
   He said Bush would be prepared to take stock of U.S.-Soviet
developments over the past eight years.
   ``He will particpate in the meeting as vice president,'' Fuller
said.
   ``We're not certain exactly what the scenario is going to be for
those discussions but any discussion they have about the future I
think will be fairly brief and will be designed merely to set the
stage for each other's approach with regard to meetings in the
months ahead,'' Fuller added.
   Fuller commented at a news conference where the Bush team also
announced that all people involved in his transition are being asked
to sign a code of conduct pledging they will not leak any news about
assignments in the new administration and will avoid any conflict of
interest.
   After talks today with British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher
and a separate meeting with Reagan, Bush returns to the job of
assembling a Cabinet.
   Robert Teeter, another transition co-director, said Bush would
review candidates today for two or three Cabinet posts, which he did
not identify.
</TEXT>
