<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Brazil     11-17 0629</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Brazil,0649</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Surge For Leftist Mayors Indicates Displeasure With President's
Party</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE HANDLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Brazilians expressed frustration
with President Jose Sarney's center-right government, economic chaos
and corruption by giving massive support to leftists in muncipal
elections around the nation.
   ``At least now the voters can't blame us for everything that goes
wrong with Brazil,'' said Gov. Pedro Simon of Rio Grande do Sul
state, a member of Sarney's Brazilian Democratic Movement Party.
   Early returns from Tuesday's balloting showed that the dominant
party since 1964 was taking a beating from both the right and the
left, but that leftists were surging ahead for control of major
cities.
   Final results were not expected until Sunday.
   Analysts said voters were dissatisfied with a record 1,000
percent annual inflation rate, the falling value of the cruzado,
political corruption and nearly constant strikes.
   ``The voters didn't send us just a message. A message is short.
This was a telex,'' said Gov. Wellington Moreira Franco of Rio de
Janeiro state, a member of Sarney's party.
   In the biggest upset, Luiza Erundina, a 53-year-old social worker
and a Marxist from the Workers Party, was expected to win as mayor
of Sao Paulo, the country's largest city.
   With 15 percent of the city's more than 5 million votes counted,
Ms. Erundina led Paulo Maluf, a wealthy industrialist and former
military-backed presidential candidate, by 4 percent.
   Ms. Erundina told reporters she would concentrate municipal
funding on public health, transportation and abandoned children,
areas in which ``hardly anything ever was invested before.''
   In Rio, the No. 2 city, the winner was Marcello Alencar, a
63-year-old lawyer from the leftist Democratic Labor Party. He is a
close ally of Leonel Brizola, the expected candidate of the left in
next year's presidential elections.
   With 28 percent of the ballots counted, Alencar had one-third
more votes than his closest opponent.
   The projected winner in Belo Horizonte, the third-largest city,
was Joao Pimenta da Veiga Filho, 41, of the left-center Brazilian
Social Democracy Party. This group recently broke away from Sarney's
party.
   The Democratic Movement, which swept mayoral elections in 1985
and captured 22 of 23 state governorships in 1986, appeared headed
for mayoralty wins in just four capitals.
   Leftists seemed assured of victory in at least seven important
state capitals. Candidates from various groups to the right of
Sarney's were headed toward wins in seven other capitals.
   The biggest prize for the rightists was the large northeastern
city of Recife, where Joaquim Francisco Cavalcanti, 40, of the
Liberal Front Party, was far ahead. He resigned this year from
Sarney's Cabinet.
   Races in the remaining capitals were too close to call or the
results were not yet in because of the cities' remoteness.
   The Democratic Movement and Sarney have controlled Brazilian
politics since the nation of 144 million returned in 1985 to
civilian rule after a 21-year military dictatorship.
   Brazil is in the throes of its worst strike by petroleum workers.
The state-owned oil monopoly Petrobras said Wednesday that Brazil
has nearly run out of diesel oil and cooking gas because of the
six-day nationwide strike.
   Twenty-nine parties participated in the election for mayors and
city councils of more than 4,000 cities and towns.
   The races were based largely on local issues, but analysts said
they indicate general feelings about presidential elections
scheduled for Nov. 15, 1989. It will be the first presidential
election in Brazil in 29 years.
   The 58-year-old Sarney is a civilian, but he gained office
indirectly through an electoral college system imposed by the
departing military regime. He was the vice presidential candidate on
a ticket headed by Tancredo Neves, a popular centrist political
figure. Neves died before he could assume office, and Sarney moved
into the top spot.
</TEXT>
