<1ST_LINE>r w PM-SeawayCoal     11-17 0242</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Seaway Coal,270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Coal Exports Through St. Lawrence Seaway Increase</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Problems among foreign coal producers and the
lower dollar abroad contributed to a 247 percent increase in the
amount of U.S. coal shipped through the St. Lawrence Seaway,
officials say.
   The increase, to 569,000 metric tons, was recorded during the
period from April to October, as compared to the same period last
year.
   Spurring the demand for American-mined coal were the lower value
of the dollar; competitive worldwide ocean freight rates; a tight
supply due to a series of industrial disputes last summer in
Australia; sanctions against using South African coal; and
production problems and rising production costs in Poland.
   U.S. coal exports through the seaway in April-October of 1987
totaled 234,000 metric tons. In 1985 and 1986, the biggest coal
years since 1982, coal exports just exceeded 600,000 tons each year.
   James L. Emery, administrator of the Saint Lawrence Seaway
Development Corp., which operates the U.S. portion of the
American-Canadian channel, said the majority of U.S. export coal
through the system so far this year has been transported to Denmark
for power production.
   Nationally, 1988 U.S. coal exports as of Aug. 31 totaled 52.2
million metric tons, up 15 percent from the same period last year,
according to the National Coal Association.
   The seaway begins at the mouth of the St. Lawrence River and runs
through the Great Lakes, ending 2,342 miles later at Duluth, Minn.
</TEXT>
