<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Intelligence-Bush     11-17 0235</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Intelligence-Bush,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Conservatives Urge More US Covert Actions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A conservative group contends that
President-elect George Bush should make covert action a routine
technique in the American spy arsenal.
   A study sponsored by the National Strategic Information Center
says covert action _ unacknowledged financial, political or military
action to influence events in foreign countries _ should be restored
as a common tool of U.S. foreign policy.
   ``American intelligence, as it is presently constituted, will not
be up to the challenges of the '90s,'' said Roy Godson of Georgetown
University, who edited the study. The report was released Wednesday
at a news conference.
   The report says covert action tactics have been tainted in the
eyes of the U.S. public by the Iran-Contra scandal.
   While covert actions have proliferated under the Reagan
administration, they still are viewed by the public and many within
the CIA as stepchildren, the study concluded.
   It also said U.S. intelligence analysts should do more to spot
the vulnerabilities of foreign governments and leaders and point out
opportunities for U.S. leverage and influence.
   The report said ``there will be major opportunities for the
United States to advance its interests in the 1990s through a broad
array of (covert action) techniques.''
   Kenneth E. deGraffenreid, former intelligence director at the
Reagan administration's National Security Council, said covert
action ``should be perceived as a useful, limited adjunct, and a
normal one, to statecraft.''
</TEXT>
