<DOCNO> AP881117-0027 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-88 0136EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-DeficitCommission     11-17 0717</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Deficit Commission,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Advisory Panel Told Quick Action Needed To Cut Budget Gap</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A parade of witnesses before a
deficit-reduction commission agreed the nation is spending too much
and saving too little, but panel members said they were far from
reaching a consensus on how to resolve the problem.
   The National Economic Commission members listened to almost eight
hours of testimony Wednesday from a variety of experts, many of whom
warned of dire consequences for the United States if quick action is
not taken to cut the federal budget deficit.
   ``Simply put, we are spending too much, investing too little and
saving virtually nothing,'' said former Labor Secretary William
Brock. ``This country is imperiled and it is going to take a whole
lot of guts to face this fact and deal with it.''
   Later, commission members said they were still watching for the
first signal from President-elect George Bush on what his intentions
are for using the panel, which was created to advise President
Reagan's successor on a deficit solution.
   Both Republican Drew Lewis and Democrat Robert Strauss, who serve
as co-chairmen of the panel, said they hoped the president-elect
would soon name his two appointees to the commission so the panel
could begin serious deliberations.
   The commission already has set aside its earlier hopes of having
a deficit-cutting blueprint finished by Dec. 21. Strauss said he was
not sure the panel would be able to meet a March 1 deadline and
might have to delay the report even further.
   ``The key to the commission's role is going to be up to the
president-elect,'' said Rep. Bill Gray, D-Pa., a member of the panel
and chairman of the House Budget Committee. ``Who does he appoint,
how credible are they, do they have his ear and what are his
instructions to them.''
   Gray said the financial markets might force Bush's hand,
especially if markets continue falling because of investor concerns
over whether the president-elect and Congress will be able to come
up with a credible budget solution.
   The stock market on Wednesday tumbled to a 2{-month low in a
broad-based decline that analysts said was linked to fresh declines
in the value of the dollar. The dollar's recent slide has led stock
market investors to worry that U.S. policymakers might force up
interest rates _ threatening a further slowdown in the economy _ to
make the American currency more attractive to foreigners.
   Economists testifying before the National Economic Commission
said the $700 billion in new foreign investment which has flowed
into the country since 1982 means that the U.S. economy is more
vulnerable to foreigners' economic decisions.
   ``The rest of the world may well give up on the dollar if it
foresees four more years of towering twin (budget and trade)
deficits,'' said C. Fred Bergsten, head of the Institute for
International Economics.
   Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan told the panel that it
should not listen to those who say that bduget deficits don't matter
since the economy has managed to survive for six years without an
economic downturn in the midst of high deficits.
   ``The deficit already has begun to eat away at the foundations of
our economic strength,'' he said. ``And the need to deal with it is
becoming ever more urgent.''
   Alice Rivlin, former head of the Congressional Budget Office,
told the commission that it was facing no easy choices.
   ``The budget cannot be cut in sufficient amounts to eliminate the
deficit, except by reducing programs and benefits that some people
feel they want and need _ or by raising revenues,'' she said. ``It
is not possible to eliminate the deficit if defense, Social Security
and taxes are all ruled out simultaneously.''
   Comments of this kind were not often heard during the
presidential campaign, when both candidates sidestepped questions
concerning the deficit because they did not want to offer detailed
solutions.
   But since winning the election, Bush has been forced to address
the budget situation, pledging to work with Congress early on to
come up with a solution.
   But Bush has not indicated any willingness to abandon his
``flexible freeze'' proposal by which overall spending increases,
excluding Social Security and interest on the national debt, would
be held to the rise of inflation each year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
