<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Iran-Contra     11-17 0709</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Contra,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prosecutors Say North Trying To Intimidate Justice Department</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran-Contra prosecutors say Oliver L. North
wants to scare the Justice Department into dropping charges against
him by seeking disclosure of ``some of our nation's most valuable
secrets.''
   Independent counsel Lawrence E. Walsh is seeking a court order to
bar North from revealing any classified information during his
defense of charges he illegally conspired to divert U.S.-Iran
arms-sale proceeds to the Nicaraguan Contra rebels.
   North showed his intention of trying to subvert the case ``by not
presenting a good-faith listing of the classified documents that he
reasonably deems necessary to defend against the indictment,'' Walsh
said in court papers filed Wednesday.
   The list of 40,000 pages of secret documents North proposed as
defense exhibits includes items that ``are simple efforts at
graymail and have no conceivable bearing on the charges in the
indictment,'' Walsh said.
   It includes documents ``which are far afield from any logical
defense,'' including ``large swatches of CIA cables concerning
Nicaragua that bear only the most tangential relation to the subject
matter in the case,'' Walsh said of the defense list filed under
court seal.
   The independent counsel asked U.S. District Judge Gerhard A.
Gesell to issue an order under the Classified Information Procedures
Act (CIPA) barring North from disclosing any government secrets
during his trial.
   ``Otherwise, North will have exposed this prosecution to
precisely the type of outcome that the drafters of CIPA worked to
avoid: a decision by the attorney general _ based purely on fear
that the price, in terms of threat to national security, is too high
_ that compels the court not to proceed with the criminal case,''
Walsh said.
   North's ``filing demonstrates once against his expectation that
intransigence will encumber the processes of law, threaten some of
our nation's most valuable secrets and provoke dismissal of the
case,'' Walsh said.
   The attorney general _ not Walsh _ has the final say about
whether to drop the charges if disclosure of secrets would threaten
national security.
   The so-called ``graymail statute'' enacted in 1980 by Congress
set up procedures to regulate the use of classified information in
court proceedings.
   Walsh argued the law is ``a critical, time-tested shield of the
government's necessary secrets and, at the same time, a device that
prevents high officeholders from escaping criminal prosecution'' by
threatening indiscriminate disclosure of secrets.
   But North ``from the outset of this litigation, has been
determined to force a failure of CIPA's procedures,'' Walsh said.
``The present notice is so grossly overblown that it invites
dismissal for lack of good faith.''
   Under CIPA,, the defense is required to submit a notice listing
the classified documents it proposes to disclose at trial. The judge
then convenes secret proceedings to determine if the documents are
relevant to the case and if they can be presented in public form.
   Walsh described the notice as ``calculated to overwhelm the
court's and the government's abilities to conduct proceedings''
under the law.
   Gesell rejected North's first list _ filed Aug. 1 _ as ``wholly
insufficient,'' later saying it ``blatantly lacked any attempt at
particularization.''
   The judge denied a similar request by Walsh to bar defense
disclosure of any secrets and gave North until Nov. 14 to file his
notice.
   On Wednesday, Walsh said the defense should be barred from using
any classified documents because ``North arrogantly disregarded the
court's repeated orders defining his obligations under CIPA.''
   North's attorneys, who have a policy of not commenting on the
case, did not return a reporter's telephone call.
   But in court papers made public Wednesday, the defense rejected
Gesell's criticism of their Aug. 1 filings as unjustified. The
lawyers disputed Gesell's holding that they were required to show
how the documents were relevant to the case.
   North, a former National Security Council aide and retired Marine
lieutenant colonel, is charged with conspiring to defraud the
government by illegally diverting to the Contras more than $12
million in profits from the arms-for-hostage sales to Iran.
   No date has been set for North's trial.
   His three co-defendants, former national security adviser John M.
Poindexter and arms dealers Albert Hakim and retired Air Force Maj.
Gen. Richard V. Secord, each have been granted separate trials.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881117-0034 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-88 0158EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Sakharov-Teller     11-17 0638</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sakharov-Teller,640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Fathers' of Soviet, American A-Bombs Disagree on Star Wars</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An unprecedented joint appearance by two men
frequently described as the respective ``fathers'' of the Soviet and
American hydrogen bombs featured sharp disagreement on whether
space-based defenses would bring world harmony or nuclear war.
   Andrei Sakharov, the Soviet scientist who has become his nation's
foremost human rights activist, said deploying such a defense system
would ``destabilize the world'' and could trigger nuclear war
between the superpowers.
   Edward Teller, one of the principal American advocates of
deploying the Star Wars defense system, said it could lead to a
``world neighborhood'' of cooperation and peace.
   The two scientists aired their views Wednesday evening at a
banquet honoring Teller as a pioneer in the field of nuclear physics
and for his advocacy of the Strategic Defense Initiative, SDI. It
was sponsored by the Ethics and Public Policy Center, a conservative
research group.
   Sakharov, 67, winner of the Nobel and Albert Einstein peace
prizes, attended the dinner as part of his first trip outside his
native land. He and Teller held a private 20-minute conversation,
the first time the two had met.
   In a speech at the beginning of the banquet, Sakharov praised
Teller as a man of principle and conviction but said deploying the
Strategic Defense Initiative, as the Star Wars plan is formally
known, would be ``a great error.''
   ``I feel it would destabilize the world,'' Sakharov said.
   He cited the ``enormous cost'' involved in paying for the
deployment of a defense system by the United States and for the
Soviet Union to field new offensive weapons to defeat it.
   ``If such systems are deployed ... there would be a temptation to
destroy them'' before they were armed, Sakharov said. ``And this in
itself could trigger a nuclear war.''
   Short of actual war, Sakharov said, SDI is an obstacle to better
relations between the two superpowers.
   ``SDI is one of the problems that stands in the way of achieving
really deep and profound arms control,'' he said.
   Soviet objections to SDI have been a central obstacle to
superpower negotiations in Geneva on cutting long-range nuclear arms
by up to 50 percent.
   Teller, responding at the banquet's end and after Sakharov had
departed, called Sakharov ``a great man'' who shares with the world
a desire for peace.
   ``Andrei Sakharov argued for the rights of individuals, argued
for freedom in an incredibly courageous manner, and he won,'' Teller
said of Sakharov's long human rights battle against the Soviet
system.
   But he said that as a physicist, Sakharov is out of touch with
the technological advances of recent decades, including advances in
the Soviet Union which Teller said is closer to deploying a
space-based defense system than is the United States.
   ``My argument has been that we must know what can be known, we
must find out'' whether a defense system will work, he said,
including ``lasers that move with the speed of light.''
   ``I have enjoyed the possibility to work on all these things,''
he said. ``Andrei Sakharov has not.''
   ``Technology has made out of the world a small neighborhood,'' he
said. ``Self defense is of interest to everybody.''
   Both men noted that their early careers in nuclear physics had
followed parallel paths.
   Sakharov said that at the time he was working on the Soviet
hydrogen bomb he and his colleagues believed that it was ``necessary
for the peace of the world to do such terrible things.''
   ``The world has now entered a new era and I am convinced a new
approach is necessary,'' he said.
   While he and Teller disagree, Sakharov said that through such
dialogues their countries ``will at least understand each other's
point of view and be able to talk instead of creating a situation of
confrontation.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
