<1ST_LINE>r w PM-TransitionAt-a-Glance     11-17 0351</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Transition At-a-Glance,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With PM-Transition-Cabinet Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, are the main developments in
President-elect George Bush's preparations for taking over as chief
executive:
   _A team of 13 people, mostly campaign workers with experience in
the Reagan adminstration, has been assembled to direct Bush's
transition office. The task at hand is to chose people for about
5,000 political jobs open in 1989 as well as developing policies for
Bush. The team is co-directed by Craig Fuller and Robert Teeter, who
were appointed by Bush the day after his election Nov. 8.
   _Teeter said the president-elect would review candidates today
for two or three Cabinet positions. He did not say which ones and
would not discuss any names.
   _Bush meets British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher today over
breakfast. The two held private talks on Wednesday, and Bush also
met with Soviet dissident Andrei Sakharov.
   _The president-elect said ``no final decision'' had been made on
chosing a White House chief of staff, but sources close to Bush said
he had picked retiring New Hampshire Gov. John Sununu. At a news
conference in Concord, Sununu said he had discussed the job with
Bush but would not confirm his selection.
   _The New York office of the Anti-Defamation League of B'nai
B'rith said it was concerned about Sununu getting the White House
job because he was the only governor who refused to endorse a
proclamation attacking a 1975 U.N. resolution that equated zionism
with racism.
   Sununu, who is Arab-American, told reporters he did not endorse
the proclamation because it would have been ``inappropriate for a
governor to try to issue something that would have as its focus an
attempt to influence foreign policy.''
   _All of the staff and volunteers involved in Bush's takeover of
power were asked to sign a ``standards of conduct'' document that
applies both during the transition and a Bush presidency. At the top
of the list was a no-leak promise. It also forbids aides from using
information for private gain and says they must disqualify
themselves from any matter which may involve a financial conflict of
interest.
</TEXT>
