<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SDXHonorees 1stLd-Writethru a0782 11-17 0432</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SDX Honorees, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0782,0436</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Honored by Journalism Society</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs first 2 grafs to CORRECT that three were nominated, sted
elected; picks up 3rd graf, The recognition...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A committee of The Society of Professional
Journalists, Sigma Delta Chi's national convention on Wednesday
nominated three distinguished journalists as fellows of the society
_ its highest form of recognition.
   Delegates to the national convention were to vote Thursday on
approving the nominees: John Quinn, senior vice president-news for
Gannett Co. Inc. and editor-in-chief of the company's USA Today
national newspaper; Ellen Goodman, columnist and associate editor of
The Boston Globe, and Louis D. Boccardi, president and general
manager of The Associated Press.
   The recognition is given for professional performance and for
contributions to public understanding of major social and political
issues.
   Quinn, also a director of Gannett, is responsible for working
with editors and publishers of Gannett's 90 daily newspapers and
with executives of its eight television and 16 radio stations to
develop news talent, resources and enterprise necessary for
comprehensive news coverage.
   Quinn's leadership positions in the news industry include service
as president of the Associated Press Managing Editors in 1972-73 and
as president of the American Society of Newspaper Editors in
1982-83. He has also been a Pulitzer Prize juror and is a past
president of the New England chapter of SPJ,SDX.
   Ms. Goodman has been with The Boston Globe since 1967. Her
syndicated column, for which she won a Pulitzer Prize in 1980,
appears in more than 400 newspapers. The column first appeared in
1971 in the Globe's Living section and was syndicated by the
Washington Post Writers Group in 1976.
   In May, Ms. Goodman was awarded the Hubert H. Humphrey Civil
Rights Award by the Leadership Conference on Civil Rights for
dedication to the cause of equality. She became associate editor of
the Globe in 1987.
   Boccardi was honored for playing a leading role in the journalism
industry's efforts to deal with First Amendment issues and problems
of readership and credibility. He has been with the AP since 1967,
after eight years of service on New York City newspapers, and became
chief executive of the worldwide news cooperative in 1985.
   Boccardi has served twice as a Pulitzer Prize juror and as a
member of the readership project and research and marketing
committee of the American Newspaper Publishers Association. He is a
member of advisory boards of the Media and Society seminars, the
Gannett Center for Media Studies, the Center for International
Journalism at the University of Southern California and the Center
for Communications.
</TEXT>
