<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0803,0226</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Plummets, Stocks Surge To Record High</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with closing. Pick up 5th pvs,
`The dollar's...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar plunged against the yen Thursday, and
share prices rose on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   Despited the reported dollar-buying intervention by the Bank of
Japan, the dollar closed lower at 121.52 yen, down 2.02 yen from
Wednesday's close of 123.54 yen. Opening at 122.40 yen, the currency
kept declining while moving in a range of 121.30-122.40 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which gained
166.71 points the previous day, gained 80.69 more points, or 0.28
percent, to finish at 29,076.81, a record high.
   The dollar's bearishness is due partly to insufficient monetary
action by the U.S. Federal Reserve Board to back the currency, said
Sumitomo Bank's Sumio Fukushima. He said the dollar fell sharply
when speculative investors began selling dollars all at once.
   Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa said Thursday morning that the
dollar should recover because the U.S. trade deficit for September
narrowed. He also called for joint action by monetary authorities to
prop up the sagging dollar, a Finance Ministry official said on
condition of anonymity.
   On Wednesday, U.S. Commerce Department reported the nation's
trade deficit for September dropped to $10.5 billion from the
previous month's $12.3 billion.
</TEXT>
