<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington in Brief,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kerry: Military Aid Needed To Help Latin America Fight Drugs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Warning that Latin American drug lords pose a
more ``immediate and effective'' national security threat than
communism, the head of a Senate narcotics panel says the Bush
administration must make military aid available to drug-fighting
nations.
   Sen. John F. Kerry, D-Mass., also recommended sweeping economic
aid to help Latin countries, similar to the Marshall Plan used to
help Western Europe following World War II.
   ```Just Say No' is just not enough. It just hasn't worked.''
Kerry said Wednesday night. ``The drug cartels do represent a
national security threat to the United States and our friends and
allies abroad. The sooner we understand this fact of life, the
sooner we can begin waging a serious war on drugs,''
   Kerry, chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations subcommittee on
narcotics, terrorism and international operations, said the new
administration must focus its national security initiatives on the
narcotics trade.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Rejection of Unfair Auto Trade Petition Called Distorting to</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Economy
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration's refusal to protect
U.S. auto parts makers from ``unfair and illegal'' Canadian trading
policies will skew that economic sector to Canada's benefit,
Michigan Gov. James Blanchard says.
   U.S. Trade Representative Clayton Yeutter on Wednesday rejected
the Michigan governor's petition to declare a Canadian duty-rebate
program to be an unfair trading practice.
   Blanchard said that decision will allow ``illegal practices to
fully develop, distorting employment, trade and investment to the
benefit of Canada.''
   Canada gives duty rebates on autos to foreign manufacturers in
return for the use of Canadian parts in their cars, which Yeutter
said is permitted in a massive free-trade agreement between Canada
and the U.S. that has already been approved by the Congress.
</TEXT>
