<DOCNO> AP881117-0047 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-88 0335EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-WomenLeaders     11-17 0622</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Women Leaders,0642</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Family Ties Key To Women's Political Power In Subcontinent</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Pakistan-Election, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Benazir Bhutto of Pakistan is following
the traditional route to power by women politicians in the Asian
subcontinent.
   She capitalized on family ties and played on the emotions of
crowds who remembered her executed father, Prime Minister Zulfikar
Ali Bhutto.
   But an iron will behind the tears served her well in her foray
into the male-dominated political arena in a region where most women
have yet to achieve economic, educational and professional parity.
   Like the daughters and widows of fallen leaders in India,
Bangladesh and Sri Lanka, she is a savvy, charismatic, intelligent
student of politics who graduated into leadership ranks in her own
right.
   The most famous _ and the one who left the deepest mark on her
own nation and on the world _ was Indira Gandhi of India.
   Mrs. Gandhi was considered a pliable young lady and the ideal
compromise candidate when the squabbling cronies of her late father,
Prime Minister Jawaharlal Nehru, had to anoint a new leader of
India's dominant Congress Party.
   She proved to be anything but pliable.
   Mrs. Gandhi governed India as prime minister from 1966 to 1977,
turning a country where bullock carts and bicycles are major means
of transportation into a nuclear power and a mighty military force.
   Her increasingly authoritarian measures handed her a crushing
election defeat after her first 11 years in power, but she bounced
back into office in 1980 with a resounding comeback victory.
   She governed another four years until she was assassinated by her
Sikh bodyguards in revenge for the army raid she had ordered to
flush out gunmen holed up the Sikh faith's holiest shrine, the
Golden Temple in Amritsar.
   The first woman political leader in the Asian subcontinent was
Sirimavo Bandaranaike of Sri Lanka. Her husband, Prime Minister
S.W.R.D. Bandaranaike, was assassinated by a Buddhist monk in 1959.
   The following year, with his Sri Lanka Freedom Party in a
shambles, the male politicians turned to his widow as the person
most capable of restoring unity.
   Mrs. Bandaranaike governed from 1960 to 1965 and again from 1970
to 1977, when voters rebelled against her stringent economic
controls. But she has rebounded again and is now the leading
opposition candidate in the presidential election set for Dec. 19.
   In Bangladesh, women have not captured the top office. But the
two strongest opposition leaders are women: Sheik Hasina of the
Awami League and Khaleda Zia of the Bangladesh Nationalist Party.
   Hasina is the daughter of Sheik Mujibur Rahman, the prime
minister who was assassinated in a coup in 1975. Mrs. Zia is the
widow of another assassinated prime minister, Ziaur Rahman, who died
in a 1981 coup.
   All the women leaders have invoked the memories and the
popularity, as they perceive it, of their fathers and husbands. But
none has done it as eloquently as Benazir Bhutto.
   In the opening chapter of her recently published autobiography,
``Daughter of the East,'' she recounts the moment of her father's
execution, which was sanctioned by the man who overthrew him,
Mohammed Zia ul-Haq:
   ``They killed my father in the early morning hours of April 4,
1979, inside Rawalpindi Central Jail. Imprisoned with my mother a
few miles away in a deserted police training camp at Sihala, I felt
the moment of my father's death.
   ``I suddenly sat bolt-upright in bed at 2 a.m. `No!' the scream
burst through the knots in my throat. `No!' I couldn't breathe,
didn't want to breathe. `Papa, Papa!' I felt so cold.''
   And then she resolved to avenge his death, in her oft-repeated
campaign words, by ``restoring democracy in Pakistan.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881117-0048 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-88 0352EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BhuttoProfile     11-17 0667</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bhutto Profile,0687</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bhutto: Crowd-Pleasing Charisma</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Pakistan-Election, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BIERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Benazir Bhutto once recalled a day
nearly a decade ago when she visited her father in jail as he
awaited execution by the military regime that had toppled his
civilian government.
   ``I told him on my oath in his death cell, I would carry on his
work,'' Ms. Bhutto said.
   Her father, former Prime Minister Zulfikar Ali Bhutto, was hanged
in a Rawalpindi prison in 1979, two years after being convicted in a
murder conspiracy. Gen. Mohammad Zia ul-Haq, who led the coup that
unseated Bhutto, turned down international pleas for sparing him.
   Today, three months after Zia died in a plane crash, Ms. Bhutto
claimed victory in national elections and is likely to become the
first woman prime minister of a modern Moslem nation.
   She is the undisputed star of Pakistani politics as head of the
populist Pakistan People's Party founded by her father.
   The charismatic 35-year-old Ms. Bhutto inherited the grass-roots
following that brought her father to power in the 1970s. In speech
after speech to adoring crowds, she has promised a better life to
the poor rural masses that form the core of this Islamic nation.
   Ms. Bhutto was groomed for politics, studying by the side of her
father, then focusing on politics and government while at Harvard
and Oxford.
   Her first taste of political success came at the British
university, where she was elected president of the Oxford Union
Society in 1976.
   Ms. Bhutto returned to Pakistan in early 1977 to take up a job in
the foreign office. The job was short-lived, however, as Zia toppled
Bhutto's government a few months later.
   Her father was accused of conspiring to murder a political
opponent and was sentenced to death. Ms. Bhutto turned to denouncing
Zia after her struggle to have her father reprieved failed. She
wound up in jail or under house arrest for five years.
   Not until a serious ear infection required treatment did Zia
allow her release in 1984 to go to England in self-exile.
   Ms. Bhutto returned triumphantly to Pakistan in April 1986, four
months after Zia announced an end to eight years of military rule.
She drew huge crowds as she toured the nation demanding democracy.
   Ecstatic crowds numbering in the hundreds of thousands would
chant her name and wait for hours for a glimpse of her.
   The stunning comeback led to inevitable comparisons with Corazon
Aquino of the Philippines, who became president after a popular and
military uprising against Ferdinand Marcos.
   But Zia steadfastly refused to allow elections contested by
political parties. In the meantime, Ms. Bhutto surprised many
observers by agreeing to an arranged marriage last December with
Karachi businessman Asif Ali Zardari that followed strict Islamic
tradition.
   Six months later, Zia fired his civilian government. In July, he
set Nov. 16 as the date for new elections.
   There was considerable speculation that Zia, who died in an Aug.
17 plane crash, chose the date because he knew Ms. Bhutto was
pregnant with her first child and hoped to keep her off the campaign
trail.
   But the elections came two months after Ms. Bhutto gave birth to
a son, Bilawal, giving her time to make whirlwind campaign tours
throughout the country after a brief bout with a kidney infection.
   In public, Ms. Bhutto is mindful of local custom and Islamic
morality, appearing with her head covered and wearing the baggy
Shalwar Kameez favored by most Pakistani women. But she is clearly
Westernized and is as comfortable speaking English as Urdu.
   Poised and articulate, she has captivated massive crowds almost
everywhere she travels in Pakistan. In early November, she mounted a
38-hour, 31-stop railway tour aboard the green-and-yellow ``Khyber
Mail'' train that wound its way 1,000 miles through the country's
hinterland.
   Her voice deteriorated into a barely audible rasp as she preached
the Bhutto message handed down by her late father: democracy and
prosperity to the poor masses.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
