<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Sudan-Rebels     11-17 0340</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sudan-Rebels,0352</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sudanese Rebels and Khartoum Political Party Sign Agreement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sudanese rebels and a political
party in the country's coalition government have signed an agreement
calling for a constitutional conference next month to end the civil
war in Sudan's south.
   The agreement, signed Wednesday night in Addis Ababa, also calls
for a cease-fire in the 5{-year conflict, cancellation of Sudan's
defense pacts with other countries, suspension of harsh Islamic laws
and lifting the state of emergency.
   ``It is time for reason to prevail, high time to end the
fratricidal war,'' said Mohammed Osman El-Mirghani,
secretary-general of the Democratic Unionist Party, the second
largest in Prime Minister Sadiq el-Mahdi's coalition government.
   He said the agreement was backed by el-Mahdi and his Umma party,
Sudan's biggest. ``The Prime Minister telephoned last night and
fully expressed his support to the meeting,'' El-Mirghani said.
   But the National Islamic Party, the third coalition partner, has
expressed reservations, especially to suspending Islamic law and
lifting the state of emergency.
   The rebels took up arms against the Moslem-dominated Khartoum
government in 1983 to press for autonomy and social reform in the
predominantly Christian and animist south. The rebels claim to
control 95 percent of the southern countryside and small towns.
   Because of the war, a third of southern Sudan's 6 million
civilians have fled in search of a haven in northern Sudan and
neighboring Ethiopia.
   EL-Mirghani and John Garang, leader of the rebel Sudan People's
Liberation Army, spoke to reporters after three days' talks led to
Wednesday's agreement.
   Garang said that El-Mirghani's party and his movement ``have
broken the ice and the next step should be taken by the government.''
   In a joint communique, the two parties in Addis Ababa also urged
the international commmunity to provide relief to the war-torn
southern Sudan.
   Garang denied the SPLA has stopped relief organizations sending
humanitarian aid to the south. He said the rebels only insist that
relief officials work with the rebels' relief organization to ensure
no arms were disguised as humanitarian aid.
</TEXT>
