<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-88 0540EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WebsterSpeech     11-17 0508</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Webster Speech,0522</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CIA Director Says Glasnost Doesn't Reduce Soviet Threat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mikhail Gorbachev's efforts to reform his
country have not fundamentally altered the relationship between the
Soviet Union and the United States, which is likely to remain
``essentially adversarial,'' says CIA director William H. Webster.
   But Gorbachev's policy of glasnost, or openness, has presented
the intelligence community with some very formidable challenges,
Webster told the Yale Political Union on Wednesday.
   While the CIA chief said the information explosion in the Soviet
Union is ``very welcome and very healthy,'' it also requires the
agency to determine ``what is real versus what Moscow wants us to
hear.''
   The Soviet Union's ``military capability, its efforts to increase
global influence and its aggressive intelligence activities are
still serious threats to United States interests. Gorbachev's
efforts to reform his country have not fundamentally altered these
truths,'' Webster said, adding that they arguably may make the
Soviets an even greater threat.
   Webster fielded questions from students after his speech and held
a news conference _ rare for a CIA chief.
   When asked by reporters if Soviet spying had decreased as a
result of Gorbachev's policy of openness, Webster answered, ``No.''
When asked if Soviet spying had increased, he responded,
``Possibly,'' adding that there is ``very intensive intelligence
work.'' He did not elaborate.
   Whatever arms control agreements the United States reaches with
the Soviet Union, he said in his speech, ``I believe that our
relationship is likely to remain essentially adversarial.''
   Webster said that while Gorbachev is an impressive leader, ``when
we watch the leadership, we also have to see what actual reforms are
being made in terms of military activity, aggressive intelligence
against the United States, improvements in civil rights and all the
things that are important to us. Here we are still waiting for
progress.''
   On the subject of the war on drugs, Webster said the role of
intelligence gathering in the battle has not been well-defined, but
that President-elect Bush is expected to change that.
   He said he believes drug interdiction is the most expensive and
least effective way to deal with the problem. The only real
solution, he said, lies in ``reduced demand coupled with a real
reduction in supply.''
   Asked by a student about his future as CIA chief under the Bush
administration, Webster said he had not yet been contacted by the
president-elect's transition team.
   Webster said the president-elect, a former chief of the agency,
had asked that he receive daily briefings from the CIA.
   Defending the use of covert action in furthering U.S. foreign
policy, Webster said that as an an alternative to military action,
``I think it is very important.''
   Covert action went awry in the Iran-Contra affair because trading
arms for hostages was not consistent with the country's overt
policy, Webster said.
   The CIA was not seen to be institutionally involved in the
Iran-Contra affair, Webster said, adding that the individuals who
violated agency rules were carrying out instructions from the
National Security Council.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881117-0055 </DOCNO>
