<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Mexico     11-17 0259</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mexico,0267</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposition Party Recognizes Salinas Presidency</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANITA SNOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The conservative National Action Party says it
has ended efforts to annul results of the July 6 election and will
now adopt the role of responsible democratic opposition to
President-elect Carlos Salinas de Gortari.
   The party said Wednesday that it still maintains Salinas, of the
governing Institutional Revolutionary Party, won in a fraudulent
election.
   Abel Vicencio Tovar, National Action's secretary general, called
on Salinas to begin his term Dec. 1 with ``a transition to a real
democracy.''
   In a statement, he said Salinas could ``legitimize himself'' by
``respecting the popular mandate of democratization, pluralism,
social justice and national sovereignty.''
   It was the first public acceptance of Salinas' victory by a major
Mexican opposition party.
   Manuel J. Clouthier, National Action's presidential candidate,
previously had called upon President Miguel de la Madrid to annul
the election results and appoint an interim president until a new
ballot could be held.
   Salinas won with slightly more than 50 percent of the vote, the
slimmest margin of victory in the governing party's 59-year history.
The party has not lost a presidential election since its founding in
1929.
   Cuauhtemoc Cardenas of the leftist National Democratic Front
coalition came in second with 31 percent and Clouthier finished
third with 17 percent, according to the Federal Election Commission.
   The National Action statement said the party had adopted a
position as ``a responsible democratic opposition.'' The statement
also called for a revision of Mexico's election code to ensure
fraud-free elections.
</TEXT>
