<HEAD>Storm Dumps Snow, Rain in the Northwest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Snow and rain fell across the Pacific Northwest to the Rockies,
dropping up to a foot of snow on mountain peaks in Washington and
Oregon. High winds accompanying the storm knocked over trees in some
areas.
   In the East, there was also stormy weather, with showers and a
few thunderstorms scattered along a cold front from the Appalachians
to the Atlantic coast. Light snow was reported in the Dakotas and
upper Michigan.
   Winter storm warnings or snow advisories were posted for a wide
area of the West: the mountains of Washington and Oregon, where snow
fell heavily overnight; northeast California and the Sierra Nevadas
along with northwest and west-central Nevada; Sun Valley and the
southern mountains of Idaho, where up to 6 inches of snow was
expected; southwest and south-central Montana; western Wyoming; and
parts of Utah and Colorado.
   As of late Wednesday, a foot of snow had fallen at Crater Lake,
Ore.
   Strong winds accompanying the storm gusted between 60 and 80 mph
in the Reno-Carson City, Nev., area. Wind measuring up to 75 mph at
Verdi, Nev., blew down a poplar tree, and wind advisories were in
effect for southern Nevada and the mountains and deserts of southern
California.
   But there was no reported recurrence of tornadoes that struck
five Midwestern states Tuesday, killing seven people and damaging
scores of homes, cars and businesses.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. EST ranged from one
below zero at Glasgow, Mont., to 79 degrees at Key West, Fla.
   Today's forecast called for widespread rain, turning to snow at
higher elevations, for much of California, the northern Pacific
coast and the northern and central parts of the inland West. In the
East, rain was expected in eastern New York and New England, while
in the Midwest, snowshowers were forecast for upper Michigan.
   High temperatures were forecast in the 30s and 40s over the Ohio
Valley, the Great Lakes, the northern Mississippi Valley, the
northern half of the Plains, the upper Missouri valley and the
Rockies to the northern Pacific coast. Florida expected highs in the
80s, with temperatures in the 70s across the Georgia and South
Carolina coasts, the central Gulf coast and the desert Southwest.
Other areas expected highs in the 50s and 60s.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 53 cloudy; Boston 60 foggy; Buffalo 43 windy;
Charleston, S.C., 73 cloudy; Cincinnati 33 cloudy; Cleveland 38
cloudy; Detroit 36 windy; Miami 77 fair; New York 55 foggy;
Philadelphia 63 cloudy; Pittsburgh 39 cloudy; Portland, Maine, 51
drizzle; Washington 60 thunderstorm.
   _Central: Bismarck 22 snow; Chicago 33 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth 35
fair; Denver 27 fair; Des Moines 30 fair; Indianapolis 32 fair;
Kansas City 26 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 21 partly cloudy;
Nashville 41 fair; New Orleans 58 partly cloudy; St. Louis 31 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 33 fair; Anchorage 21 cloudy; Las Vegas 57
fair; Los Angeles 56 fair; Phoenix 54 fair; Salt Lake City 43 windy;
San Diego 54 foggy; Seattle 44 rain.
   _Canada: Montreal 54 showery; Toronto 37 windy.
</TEXT>
