<1ST_LINE>r i PM-MilesDavis     11-17 0251</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Miles Davis,0258</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jazz Trumpeter Cancels Tour After Illness</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. jazz trumpeter Miles Davis canceled six
concerts in Italy and the rest of his European tour after collapsing
at the end of a concert in Madrid, a newspaper reported today.
   Spain's leading daily El Pais quoted concert promoter Tito
Ramoneda as saying the 62-year-old Davis fainted and fell offstage
after his Tuesday performance at the Madrid Jazz Festival.
   A doctor who examined him in the Madrid sports palace said the
noted composer and bandleader suffered from arrhythmia, or irregular
heartbeat, the paper said.
   Davis, who has diabetes, received an injection of insulin and was
ordered to remain in bed in his hotel room in the Spanish capital,
the paper said.
   On Wednesday, Davis canceled a concert in Barcelona and a
six-date tour in Italy that was to begin in Reggio Emilia today, the
paper said.
   Romaneda told the paper Davis had told his promoters that he
wanted to end his months of almost daily concerts in different
European cities and return to the United States.
   Davis has been a major influence in jazz since the late 1940s.
The bands he led have been credited with developing the West Coast
``cool'' style of the 1950s, the modal approaches of the 1960s and
the jazz-rock fusion of the 1970s.
   His better known recordings include ``Birth of the Cool'' (1949),
``Kind of Blue'' (1959) and ``Bitches Brew'' (1969).
   In recent years, his records have been influenced by pop music.
</TEXT>
