<HEAD>Judge Orders Fan To Stay Away From Actress Sharon Gless</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A psychiatric patient who threatened to shoot
herself in front of actress Sharon Gless was ordered by a judge to
stay away from the co-star of the ``Cagney and Lacey'' television
series.
   Superior Court Judge Kurt Lewin issued a permanent restraining
order Wednesday that said Joni Leigh Penn must remain 200 yards away
from Miss Gless' family members and stay 1,000 yards away from the
actress' home and residences of her family members, said her
attorney and brother, Michael Gless.
   ``She's being treated for fan obsession,'' he said of Ms. Penn.
``Before, all the police could do was ask her not to trespass. Now
they can arrest her for violation of a court order.''
   Neither Miss Gless or Ms. Penn appeared in court.
   Miss Gless, who won two Emmy awards for her portrayal of
dedicated police officer Christine Cagney on the now-canceled CBS-TV
series, has received 20 letters from Ms. Penn, a self-described fan,
since Jan. 19.
   Ms. Penn threatened to shoot herself in front of the actress,
according to a letter submitted to the court by Ms. Penn's
psychiatrist, Hubert Nestor.
   Gless said Ms. Penn was a frequent fixture near the ``Cagney and
Lacey'' set, hovering outside studio doors at dawn to await Miss
Gless' arrival, then following the sound truck to the filming
location.
   On Oct. 25, Ms. Penn went to Miss Gless' home and told her
secretary she had a gun, attorneys said. Police were called, but Ms.
Penn left before they arrived.
   She later underwent psychiatric observation at an Orange County
facility, Gless said.
</TEXT>
