<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     11-17 0488</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0505</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If you're a Scrooge about Christmas you might want
to head for Denver, where it seems there's a Santa shortage.
   Ken Galey, director of the non-profit Rent-A-Santa program, says
that for the first time in the program's six-year history it is
short on recruits for the ho-ho-ho role.
   ``We have 10 and need 40,'' he said.
   The recruits undergo a week-long training program for duty
beginning right after Thanksgiving, Galey said. The program is part
of the the Mile High Child Care unit of United Way.
   The job pays $10 the first hour and $5 per hour after that, he
said. Costumes are supplied.
   ``Last year we did 375 assignments between Thanksgiving and
Christmas Eve and that was with about 28 Santas. This year we need
40 already,'' Galey said.
   ``I'm just thinking off the top of my head that because our
economy has been a bit in the doldrums, people aren't looking
forward to the Christmas holidays as early this year as they have in
past years,'' he said to explain the shortage of Santas in training.
   The program's Santas, which have ranged from truck drivers to
attorneys, see duty at private parties in homes, office parties,
shopping centers, day care centers and anywhere else that Christmas
parties are held for children.
   ``They are generally people who look forward to the holidays and
love playing the part of Santa and have a good time doing it. It
wouldn't be Christmas for them if they didn't have a chance to play
Santa Claus,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BRUNSWICK, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A name game has the residents of a Virginia
county and this Georgia city all in a stew.
   Both Brunswick County, Va., and Brunswick, Ga., claim to be the
home of Brunswick stew, a tasty concoction of smoked meat, chicken,
corn, baby lima beans, tomatoes, onions, secret ingredients and
assorted seasonings.
   Georgian's traditionally cook their Brunswick stew in black iron
wash pots over an open fire, which gives the stew a distinctive,
smoky flavor.
   Virginians cook theirs in large stainless-steel kettles similar
to those used in military mess kitchens.
   In February, the Georgia Legislature and Virginia's House of
Representatives each passed resolutions declaring its state the
stew's ``official'' birthplace. On Saturday, there will be a second
attempt to settle the issue with a cook-off, this time in Georgia.
   Virginians won a similar competition in Virginia last year that
featured judges from that state, according to Phyllis Taunton, one
of the sponsors. She said Georgians will claim the title this year,
which is being judged by locals.
   ``Naturally, Georgia lost that competition,'' Mrs. Taunton said.
``But I'm confident we'll regain the national Brunswick stew title
this Saturday at high noon, when the judges announce their
decision.''
   Nonetheless, more than 50 Virginians are expected. They say they
are bringing a new, $5,000 stainless-steel stew kettle to compete in
the contest.
</TEXT>
