<DOCNO> AP881117-0064 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-88 0659EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Cocaine-Valium     11-17 0558</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cocaine-Valium,0575</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Study Shows Cocaine Users Now Abusing Tranquilizers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER McNULTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A dramatic increase in tranquilizer use by
cocaine abusers is worrying counselors nationwide, who fear the
double dangers of dual addictions.
   Tranquilizers like Valium, used to ease the ``crash'' of a
cocaine high by calming nerves and relieving paranoia, are becoming
a second drug of choice among cocaine users, according to a study
released Wednesday by the city's Haight Ashbury Free Clinic.
   But cocaine users, particularly those who smoke the potent form
known as crack, take tranquilizers in such quantity that the effects
are reversed and users often become more agitated, unpredictable and
violent, said David Smith, the clinic's founder and medical director.
   The ``dual-drug'' phenomenon parallels the ``speedballing''
habits of heroin addicts 20 years ago, who supplemented their
barbiturates with amphetamines, he said.
   Valium and the tranquilizer Xanax, which overtook Valium last
year as the most-prescribed benzodiazepine tranquilizer in the
country, are long-acting drugs that can produce seizures when taken
at high doses. They also can lead to severe addictions that are hard
to kick, Smith said.
   ``We believe we have identified a valid trend nationwide, and
other independent sources support it,'' said Smith.
   The study surveyed 3,000 workers in 339 chemical dependency
treatment programs across the nation on a variety of questions. It
found that many reported a growing dual-drug problem.
   Data on hospital emergency room drug overdoses, addiction
treatment admissions and law enforcement seizure statistics support
the study results, Smith said. In San Francisco, emergency room
overdoses have increased 77 percent this year compared to 1987.
   ``The emergency room data suggest not only were we correct, but
it's worse than we thought,'' said Smith. ``It's clearly a trend and
we've not peaked out yet.''
   Smith said the widespread dual-drug phenomenon warrants expanded
treatment centers, supply-reduction efforts and education programs
for drug users and physicians.
   Although cocaine users also use alcohol to take the edge off,
Smith said researchers are particularly fearful of the
cocaine-tranquilizer combination.
   ``When you combine two drugs ... it multiplies. Instead of one
plus one equalling two, it's three, four, five or six,'' said Hal
Linebarger, a chemical dependency therapist at a center south of San
Francisco. ``They cancel each other out, but it ends up being much
more poisonous to the system.''
   Tranquilizers can ease the emotional and physical depression that
follows a cocaine ``high,'' Linebarger explained.
   A secondary dependence on tranquilizers can go unnoticed by a
cocaine addict, Smith said. Physicians may prescribe tranquilizers
for patients who complain of feeling anxious and paranoid, not
realizing the symptoms are a result of cocaine use, he said.
   Prescription tranquilizers also are available on the street
through wholesale diversions and international smuggling, he said.
   Although the cocaine epidemic appeared to be leveling off in
1983, the introduction of crack cocaine in 1984 produced record
levels of dual-drug dependence, Smith said.
   ``Any time you see an increase in an upper, you'll see an
increase in downers, and any time you see an increase in downers,
you'll see an increase in uppers,'' he said. ``Smokable forms of
cocaine are really the fuel for this.''
   The study was conducted by the Training and Education Section of
the Haight Ashbury Free Clinic in conjunction with the Research
Division of the Merritt-Peralta Chemical Dependency Recovery
Hospital in Oakland.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881117-0065 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-88 0701EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0454 11-17 0715</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0454,0736</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with new clashes. No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli troops shot and wounded 10 Palestinians
in clashes in the occupied lands today, and the army eased a six-day
curfew aimed at blocking violence fueled by the Palestinian
declaration of independence.
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin dismissed the declaration of a
Palestinian state in the Israeli-occupied territories as a ``PLO
deception attempt,'' and Israel launched a diplomatic offensive on
Wednesday to counter it.
   Hospital officials said 10 Palestinians were shot and wounded
when soldiers opened fire on rioting youths near Nablus in the West
Bank and several areas of the Gaza Strip. Among the wounded were a
15-year-old girl shot in the back and a 34-year-old woman hit in the
left thigh, they said.
   The army said it was checking the reports.
   In Arab east Jersualem today, two Israeli policemen were injured
by rocks at an Arab boys' school, police spokesman Rafi Levy said.
He said riot police then entered Rashadiye School and arrested eight
students.
   A teacher said trouble started when police arrived to quiet
students singing Palestinian patriotic songs in the school's
courtyard. The teacher would not give his name.
   The army lifted curfews from several towns in the Gaza Strip,
home to 650,000 Palestinians, but kept curfews in effect for the
250,000 who live in refugee camps. A curfew also was maintained on
the Nur Shams refugee camp near Tulkarem in the West Bank.
   Telephone lines remained cut off to homes and businesses for a
seventh day in the West Bank cities of Hebron, Nablus, Ramallah and
Jenin, but the army said they would be restored during the day.
   The lines were severed to prevent Palestinians from coordinating
anti-Israeli activities during the meeting in Algiers of the PLO's
parliament-in-exile, which ended Tuesday with the declaration of
independence.
   The government, meanwhile, confirmed that Defense Minister
Yitzhak Rabin ordered Israel Television not to show scenes of
jubilation at the Palestine National Council meeting in order not to
incite Palestinians in the territories.
   Rabin, who has been defense minister in charge of quelling
violence during the 11-month Palestinian uprising, told Israel
television Wednesday night that quiet could be restored in three to
six months.
   ``I believe that the events of the last several days can become a
turning point leading to a significant decrease in violence,'' he
said.
   He expressed hope that many Palestinians would be content with
``achieving their aim and allowing the political process'' but said
Israel ``should continue to supress violence and block the PLO
deception attempt by political action.''
   In Jerusalem on Wednesday, Foreign Ministry officials announced a
diplomatic campaign against the Palestine Liberation Organization's
drive for recognition of its self-proclaimed state.
   The effort will focus on the PLO's failure to renounce terrorism,
to accept U.N. Resolution 242 unconditionally or to clearly
recognize Israel, one official said. He said Israel will argue that
the resolution, which implicitly recognizes the the Jewish state's
right to exist, cannot be amended.
   The PLO said it was accepting the resolution on condition the
Palestinian right to self-determination is also recognized.
   Palestinian hardliners said they opposed the declaration, and the
fundamentalist Moslem Hamas (Zeal) movement called a three-day
general strike to protest the declaration's implicit recognition of
Israel.
   Foreign Minister Shimon Peres complained that recognition of the
would-be Palestinian state would interfere with any peace process.
   He told reporters that recognition, now by more than 20 mostly
Arab countries, ``further complicates the situation by supporting
something that shouldn't be supported.''
   On Wednesday, Palestinians kept up their nightly revelry
celebrating the Algiers independence statement. Youths danced in the
streets in the West Bank city of Bethlehem, and firecrackers rounded
through Gaza City.
   A 25-year-old man wounded in the head three days ago in the Gaza
Strip town of Rafah died Wednesday, raising to 313 the number of
Palestinians killed in the nearly year-long uprising against 21
years of Israeli occupation. Eleven Israelis also have died.
   Also in Gaza, military appeals court rejected appeals of eight
Arab activists slated for deportation but upheld two other appeals
conditional on approval of military officials, Israel television
said. It said the eight planned to appeal to Israel's Supreme Court.
   Since the uprising started, Israel has deported 33 Palestinians.
</TEXT>
