<DOCNO> AP881117-0066 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-88 0722EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HospitalKidnapping     11-17 0483</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hospital Kidnapping,0497</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prosecution Changes Charge Against Woman Accused In Newborn's
Abduction</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MELISSA CONTI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state dropped a kidnapping charge
against a woman who now stands accused of ``permanent detention or
restraint'' in the abduction of a newborn boy from his mother's
hospital room.
   After the change in the charge Wednesday, Acqunetta Rushon Smith,
32, entered two pleas: innocent and innocent by reason of insanity.
   Chief Deputy Prosecutor Lloyd King said he decided to alter the
charge against Ms. Smith because of the alleged purpose of the crime.
   Kidnapping is an abduction for the purpose of holding someone for
a ransom, as a hostage, or to hurt the victim. Permanent detention
is holding or concealing a person ``without ever releasing him,
without ever returning him to the person or institution from whose
lawful custody he was taken.''
   King contended Ms. Smith wanted to raise the infant she is
accused of abducting.
   Kidnapping and permanent detention carry the same penalty: five
to 20 years in prison and a fine of up to $15,000. No bond was set.
   The innocent plea, according to public defender Bill Simpson, is
standard in criminal cases. He said the plea of innocent by reason
of mental disease or defect was made so that Ms. Smith could be
evaluated by psychiatrists.
   Among the issues to be settled is whether Ms. Smith is mentally
capable of standing trial.
   She was denied bond Tuesday after she entered an innocent plea on
the kidnapping charge in Little Rock Municipal Court.
   Ms. Smith was arrested at her Hot Springs home Monday after
police received a tip from an anonymous caller that she had taken
the baby, Christopher Michael Jones. The child was taken Nov. 1 from
his mother's hospital room, three days after he was born six weeks
premature, by a woman disguised as a nurse.
   The boy was returned to his parents, Annette Thomas-Jones and
Willie Jones, in good health. Authorities said the infant was well
taken care of during the two weeks he was missing.
   Ms. Smith and her boyfriend wanted to have a baby boy, said Capt.
Bob H. Moore of the Little Rock Police Department.
   A registered nurse at the University of Arkansas medical school
hospital recalled during a Wednesday interview that Ms. Smith was a
caring person who tended to her terminally ill sister for two years
before she died.
   Lisa Rutherford, the assistant head nurse of the hospital's
clinic, said Ms. Smith's sister died early this year. Mrs.
Rutherford would not reveal the woman's illness.
   ``She could have deserted her sister,'' Mrs. Rutherford said. ``A
lot of patients that come in here that have a very bad illness,
their families just totally turn on them. She could have done that
easily but she didn't.''
   Ms. Smith, divorced with four children of her own, cares for her
sister's child.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
