<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Poland 1stLd-Writethru   11-17 0683</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Poland, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0512,0699</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Protesters Say Fast Forced Officials To Agree To Rehire Strikers</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with comment from coal federation
and Solidarity, church criticism of plans to close Gdansk shipyard.
No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 50 people claimed victory today and
ended a five-day fast aimed at forcing officials to rehire the last
of about 100 workers dismissed for roles in Poland's worst labor
unrest in seven years.
   Agreement was reached through the mediation of the Roman Catholic
bishop in Katowice, said Adam Slomka, a spokesman for the fasters
protesting since Saturday in the Christ the King Cathedral in the
southern city.
   ``We managed to achieve in five days what hadn't been achieved in
several months,'' said Slomka, speaking by telephone from the
cathedral.
   The nation's bishops and Lech Walesa, leader of the banned
Solidarity independent labor movement, had appealed for the miners'
reinstatement. The opposition said rehiring them was a condition for
participating in talks with the government.
   Slomka said agreement was reached late Wednesday with the
national coal federation to reinstate the workers today. The strikes
were in August.
   Bishop Damian Zimon led a delegation that met with provincial
officials on Tuesday, Slomka said, adding that two more negotiating
sessions Wednesday led to the agreement.
   He said the workers won job reinstatements for all the dismissed
workers except two workers at the Stalowa Wola steel mill in the
southeast. The church will continue to mediate in that case, he said.
   Tadeusz Napieracz, a deputy director at the coal federation, the
body that oversees the mines, said, ``The miners are returning to
their old posts as of tomorrow.'' He denied they ever had been fired
and said officials had wanted to to give them new positions, while
the miners insisted on their old jobs.
   Solidarity national spokesman Janusz Onyszkiewicz said in Warsaw
that the the decision ``should have been mede several months ago.
Let us hope other positive signs will follow.''
   The hunger protest began early Saturday after a pro-independence
march Friday night turned violent. Organizers say about 250 people
took shelter from police inside the cathedral in Katowice, about 170
miles southeast of Warsaw.
   At the urging of one miner, about 80 of the people began a hunger
strike, originally aimed at winning freedom for detained fellow
demonstrators.
   But after those demonstrators were freed, the fasters decided to
adopt the cause of the fired miners.
   Andrzej Polmanski, whom authorities have said is a ringleader of
the August strike at the Andaluzja coal mine, said the fasters
included 16 dismissed miners. Students and various opposition
activists comprised the rest.
   The opposition originally counted 103 workers as fired or drafted
into the army for joining the August strikes for higher pay and
legalization of Solidarity, he said. The number of those still not
rehired had fallen to 49 miners and the two steelworkers by this
week, he said.
   Polmanski said the issue was broader than individual jobs. If
authorities succeeded in firing strike leaders, it would make
workers less willing to fight for their rights in the future, he
said.
   The question also became a stumbling block to talks between the
opposition and authorities on Poland's future and the legalization
of Solidarity, which was crushed in a 1981 military crackdown.
Walesa agreed to end the August strikes after the government agreed
to the talks.
   Walesa has said he will not come to the table until officials
honor a promise by Interior Minister Gen. Czeslaw Kiszczak at the
end of August that strikers would not be fired.
   Also blocking the talks is the government's objection to two
longtime Solidarity activists Walesa has refused to remove from the
opposition delegation _ Jacek Kuron and Adam Michnik.
   Solidarity also has insisted that the government reverse its
decision to close the Lenin Shipyard in Gdansk, where Solidarity was
born in an August 1980 strike wave.
   On Wednesday, the Episcopate Secretariat, which represents Roman
Catholic Bishops nationwide, criticized plans to close the shipyard
and said it was ``a political act not facilitating reconciliation.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
