<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ShootingSpree     11-17 0432</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shooting Spree,0446</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Say Milwaukee Man Shot State Trooper, Security Guard, Self</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELVIDERE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities in Illinois and Wisconsin are
trying to piece together the background of a man whose allegedly
shot his landlord, a state trooper and a security guard before
shooting himself.
   The suspect, Phuoc Tri Nguyen, 36, was listed in critical
condition Wednesday at Memorial Hospital in Woodstock, said a
spokeswoman.
   Trooper Jose Rangel, 33, twice was taken to surgery Wednesday at
St. Anthony Medical Center in Rockford, where he was in critical
condition with an abdominal wound, said hospital spokeswoman Betty
Cavers.
   Police in Milwaukee, where Nguyen lived eight years, know little
about the man suspected of the multiple shootings in that city and
in the Rockford area.
   Milwaukee police Capt. Albert Hentz said Nguyen came to the
United States from Vietnam in 1980, sponsored by a refugee program
of Milwaukee's Catholic Social Services. He became a naturalized
citizen in 1987.
   Nguyen shot security guard Michael T. Glee, 18, of Belvidere at
an auto dealership and robbed a Belvidere service station before a
police chase that ended with Nguyen shooting himself, police said.
   Glee was released from the hospital after treatment for a gunshot
wound to one arm.
   Police were unsure what caused Nguyen to open fire on Rangel in
the incident that began about 1 a.m. Wednesday at the Belvidere toll
plaza on Interstate 90, about 15 miles from the Wisconsin line.
   Rangel was shot after he stopped Nguyen's car because of Nguyen's
failure to pay the toll, state police Sgt. Tami Haukedahl said. The
trooper and his partner returned fire, but the suspect's car sped
off, Haukedahl said.
   The shooting at the auto dealership came next, followed by the
gasoline station robbery in Belvidere about 2:15 a.m., in which no
one was hurt, police said.
   After the robbery, Nguyen's car was pulled over in Belvidere by a
local officer, but after backup police arrived, the suspect led them
on a 20-mile chase, said Belvidere Police Chief Charles Burkhart.
   Police blocked Nguyen's car in a parking lot, and he fired one
shot at police before shooting himself in the head, Burkhart said.
   In Wisconsin, Nguyen was charged with attempted murder in the
Sunday shooting of his 74-year-old landlord, John Pietruscka, police
said. Nguyen also was charged with armed robbery for allegedly
taking $130 from a friend that night, they said.
   Nguyen also was the prime suspect in a robbery later Sunday at a
service station in suburban Milwaukee in which two others were shot,
police said.
   All three Wisconsin shooting victims remained hospitalized.
</TEXT>
