<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CocaineMother     11-17 0274</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cocaine Mother,0281</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pregnant Woman Arrested For Smuggling Cocaine Inside Body</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Doctors pumped nearly two pounds of cocaine in tiny
rubber bags from the stomach of a pregnant woman arrested along with
three men trying to smuggle the drug in their bodies, Customs agents
said.
   ``This is a new low, when a pregnant woman will put cocaine in
her body and risk not only her own life but the life of her unborn
child,'' said Customs spokesman Cliff Stallings.
   The four Colombians were arrested at Miami International Airport
on Sunday, charged with smuggling 427 bags containing more than
eight pounds of cocaine, said Michael Sheehan, another Customs
spokesman. The practice of smuggling cocaine by swallowing it is not
uncommon.
   The men were allowed to pass the cocaine at Jackson Memorial
Hospital; doctors pumped the stomach of the woman, Iveth Rocha, 22,
Sheehan said.
   ``It is possible, and it has happened here in Miami, for a
persons' digestive juices to eat through the rubber and release the
cocaine into the stomach,'' said Van Capps, Customs chief of airport
operations in Miami. ``If that happens, that person is dead in a
matter of minutes.''
   ``A lot of time these people, `mules,' are peasants really, from
very low levels of society,'' Stallings added. ``In many cases they
may be ignorant of the dangers.''
   Customs officials took the group to the hospital after they gave
suspicious answers to routine questions, Stallings said. The woman,
her husband, Manuel Ramos, 35, brother Thomas Rocha, 26, and Jaime
Cujea, 41, were being held in jail.
   Ms. Rocha's sons, ages 3 and 4, were placed in state custody.
</TEXT>
