<HEAD>Cessna Crashes; At Least 7 Dead</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with officials now saying some
passengers missed flight, CORRECTS to at least 7 dead, other
details; no pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>EVRY, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Cessna-441 crashed in heavy fog today in
lagoons west of Paris, killing at least seven people, some of them
journalists, officials said.
   Rescue workers went immediately to the site of the crash, the
Saclay lagoons on the edge of the Essonne and Yvelines districts
outside Paris.
   Local officials and rescue workers said the pilot and six
passengers, some of them reporters, were killed in the 10:30 a.m.
crash. The cause was not immediately known.
   The flight roster listed 10 people, according to the General
Direction for Civil Aviation.
   However, police and Essonne officials believed some scheduled
passengers failed to board the plane.
   They said there appeared to be no survivors in the debris
scattered 150 meters around the crash site.
   The plane took off in heavy fog from the Toussus-le-Noble airport
in the Yvelines and was headed for Montlucon, in central France,
authorities said.
   The Air and Frontier police said the aircraft apparently lost
radio contact with the control tower shortly after take-off.
   The flight was organized in part by Garages du Bac, a BMW
dealership in France, to take journalists to a factory and watch
test drives of a new model car.
   Jean-Charles Delesalle, a reporter with the newspaper Journal du
Dimanche said he was among those who missed the flight. He said
later he learned of the accident while in his car.
   ``I stopped the car. I had an intuition. I knew it was `my'
plane,'' he told French television. ``I just stayed there
trembling.''
</TEXT>
