<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Bush-Markets     11-17 0549</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush-Markets,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush's Spokeswoman Brushes Off Greenspan's Warning</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL PAGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The spokeswoman for George Bush's presidential
transition team today answered warnings from the chairman of the
Federal Reserve Board about the deficit by saying that ``economists
never agree on anything.''
   Sheila Tate also said in a television interview that
President-elect Bush's first appointments to his economic team have
sent a ``very clear signal'' to investors that ``by and large helped
calm the markets.''
   Bush aides have been scrambling to ease fears about the deficit,
and concerns about the vice president's pledge not to raise taxes,
which have sent stocks tumbling at home and put the already-weak
dollar into a further tailspin in international markets.
   The dollar fell today to a 15-year low against the Japanese yen
despite reported central bank intervention in Tokyo. The Dow fell
more than 38 points Wednesday and had dropped almost 90 points to a
2{-month low since last week's election.
   Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan added the strongest voice
yet to calls for action on the deficit, telling a national
commission Wednesday the red ink ``already has begun to eat away at
the foundations of our economic strength. And the need to deal with
it is becoming ever more urgent.''
   Greenspan, who was appointed to the Federal Reserve post by
President Reagan, addressed questions of a possible tax increase by
saying how the deficit is reduced ``is far less relevant than that
it is done.''
   Asked on ABC-TV's ``Good Morning America'' about his warning,
Tate said:
   ``Economists never agree on anything. For every economist you
cite we can trot out one who is diametrically in opposition.''
   Asked whether Bush as president would be at odds with Greenspan,
Tate said:
   ``It's traditional economists simply don't agree with each other.
And there's a lot of jockeying going on right now. We just have to
wait and see what President-elect Bush decides to do.''
   ``There's a lot of talk now swirling about the deficit,'' she
said. ``I think his appointment of (Treasury Secretary) Nicholas
Brady gave a very clear signal as to the kind of administration he's
going to have and I think by and large helped calm the markets.''
   Investors in the United States and abroad have attributed some of
the bad economic news to strong campaign statement of ``Read my lips
_ no new taxes.''
   ``I think it's that traditional nervousness with change,'' Tate
said of the market plunge.
   ``He (Bush) has said time and time again he wants to meet with
Congress. He's expressed conciliatory gestures. ... I think they'll
work together to deal with the issue,'' she said.
   Greenspan was one of several witnesses who told the National
Economic Commission, which is studying how to deal with the deficit,
that the problem has been too long ignored.
   ``This country is imperiled and it is going to take a whole lot
of guts to face this fact and deal with it,'' said William Brock,
who was Labor Secretary under Reagan.
   The Fed chief testified that the deficit is more likely to be cut
permanently through spending cuts rather than tax increases because
congressmen tend to spend new revenues from taxes. But he added that
any long-range plan would help lower interest rates ``regardless of
its components.''
</TEXT>
