<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Fiji     11-17 0373</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fiji,0385</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fiji Cabinet Suspends Internal Security Decree</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SUVA, Fiji (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government today lifted laws that had given
the military and police wide powers of arrest and limited press and
personal freedoms.
   The decree had been in effect since June, following the discovery
of illegally imported weapons, including automatic rifles from the
Soviet Union, hand grenades and ammunition.
   In a statement tonight, Information Minister Ratu Imoke Kubuaeola
said the Internal Security Decree was intended to close gaps in
existing laws to ensure security in this South Pacific nation, which
has experienced two coups in 1{ years.
   The decree limited freedom of movement and expression and allowed
searches and detentions without charges being filed.
   ``Now that most of the illegal arms have been recovered and
greater peace and stability exists in the country, it was the view
of Cabinet that the time was right for the ISD to be suspended,''
Kubuaeoloa said after a Cabinet meeting.
   At the same time, the government deployed troops outside
government buildings and the capital's two radio stations. It was
not clear if that was related to the lifting of the security decree.
   The soldiers were not carrying arms.
   Military Forces spokesman Capt. Eroni Volavola described the
deployment as ``a normal and regular security exercise.''
   About 30 soldiers were posted outside state-run Radio Fiji and
the private commercial radio station FM-96; a building housing the
offices of ministers of the interim government; and electricity and
water installations.
   Fiji has a population of about 715,000, of which native Fijians
comprise 47 percent. Indians, descendants of British imported sugar
plantation labor in the 19th century, make up 49 percent of the
population.
   On May 14, 1987, Sitiveni Rabuka led armed soldiers into
Parliament and arrested the month-old Indian-dominated government of
Prime Minister Timoci Bavadra. Rabuka led a second coup Sept. 25,
saying the rights of the minority ethnic Fijians remained threatened.
   He broke the nation's ties with the Commonwealth in October by
declaring Fiji a republic.
   Rabuka later handed power to an interim government, headed by
Ratu Sir Kamisese Mara, while a new constitution was drafted to
ensure Fijians have permanent and dominant control in Parliament.
Rabuka elevated himself to chief of the army and home affairs
minister.
</TEXT>
