<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PilgrimSpill     11-17 0418</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pilgrim Spill,0431</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>2,000 Gallons of Radioactive Water Spill At Plant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 2,000 gallons of radioactive water overflowed
a collection area during maintenance at the Pilgrim nuclear plant,
and some of it seeped outdoors into a parking lot, the plant's owner
said.
   One worker was slightly contaminated.
   Peter Agnes, Gov. Michael Dukakis' chief aide on nuclear power,
said elevated levels of radioactivity were detected as far away as
the perimeter fence. He gave no indication of whether the spill
posed a threat to the public.
   The spill occurred Wednesday at a low-level nuclear waste
processing area at the plant, which is awaiting word from the
Nuclear Regulatory Commission on whether it can begin low-level
power testing after a 2{-year shutdown.
   About 100 gallons seeped outside the processing facility and onto
an asphalt truck parking lot, Boston Edison Co. spokeswoman Elaine
Robinson said. The water inside and out was mopped up, she said.
   Karl Abraham, an NRC spokesman, said the commission may call in a
special inspector to investigate.
   ``The normal routine follow-up would be by the resident
inspectors,'' he said. ``But with all of the attention focusing on
Pilgrim, we can't rule out the possibility that something else will
happen (such as) sending a specialist to look at this.''
   The plant has been closed because of management and equipment
problems.
   Agnes, assistant secretary of public safety, said he sent a
Public Health Department team to report on the cleanup and get
information on what caused the spill.
   ``Since we are speaking about a substantial amount of waste water
and an exposure that at least resulted in elevated readings as far
out as the perimeter, it's a significant event,'' Agnes said.
   The accident happened in a waste processing area during
preparations for shipping a container of waste from the plant. The
water was being filtered through earth to remove radioactivity. The
earth was to be shipped to a storage facility in Barnwell, S.C.,
Robinson said.
   A plant operator making a tour of the plant discovered that the
water had overflowed and immediately cut off the water, she said.
   The worker's knee touched some water during the cleanup and was
washed with soap and water, Edison spokesman John Fidler said.
   ``The level of contamination on his knee was just barely above
the minimum level where we say something is contaminated instead of
clean,'' Fidler said.
   He said the plant has roped off and is testing the area around
the spill.
</TEXT>
