<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PlaneSearch     11-17 0423</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Plane Search,0435</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Insurance Company Ends Lake Search, Deepening Mystery of Missing
Pilot</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY REEVES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DADEVILLE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former insurance agent accused of
bilking policyholders of $590,000 disappeared after renting a small
plane, and officials failed to locate him after a two-week search of
a lake bottom.
   U.S. Aviation Underwriters called off its search at a
recreational lake for Blan Stewart and the single-engine plane he
was flying, said Marshall Dean, a claims manager with the company,
which had a policy on the plane.
   ``It's really difficult,'' Dean said of the hunt, which for three
days was aided by a $1,500-a-day sonar device. ``The terrain under
there is so rough. It's like finding a needle in a haystack.''
   Stewart, a 45-year-old former agent with Travelers Corp.,
disappeared Oct. 31 while en route from Vero Beach, Fla., to
Huntsville, flying into blustery weather to the north.
   Some of those involved in the search speculated that Stewart
ditched the Piper Cherokee or staged a crash and his death to escape
having to stand trial on charges of theft by deception that could
bring up to 100 years in prison.
   ``If he's not at the bottom of that lake, he's a fugitive from
justice,'' said Holly Wiseman, an assistant state attorney general
who built the case that led to Stewart's indictment in August.
   Others said he might have crashed intentionally to let his wife
and business collect on numerous life insurance policies that
prosecutors said totaled some $3 million.
   ``The whole circumstances are mighty unusual,'' said Bump Holman,
vice president of the Vero Beach, Fla., company that rented the
plane to Stewart.
   The pilot's brother, Gene Stewart of Columbia, S.C., said divers
and others would return to Lake Martin for a last time today, with
the family footing the bill. After that, a reward will be offered to
lure salvagers, he said.
   ``I'm convinced it's in the lake somewhere,'' he said.
   Gene Stewart, who was at the helm of a search boat Wednesday,
said his brother had acknowledged the thefts and repaid some
$400,000. He said his brother never would try to escape justice by
faking his death.
   Stewart surrendered his insurance license earlier this year.
   Dean said pieces of airplane wheels have been found in the search
area, and one resident reported hearing an airplane with engine
trouble and what sounded like an explosion the night Stewart
disappeared.
   ``We're convinced it's in the lake,'' Dean said. ``I think it hit
the water, tore off the gear and sank.''
</TEXT>
