<2ND_LINE>PM-Prison Escape,0266</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Inmates Captured In Kentucky In Stolen Corrections Department
Car</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police captured two escaped murderers today
after an officer became suspicious when a car bearing the seal of
the West Virginia corrections department drove through town about 2
a.m., authorities said.
   Freddie Rakes, 29, and Dickie Wimmer, 36, escaped from the West
Virginia Penitentiary at Moundsville on Wednesday by crashing a
maintenance truck and a prison car through a gate. The two worked in
the prison motor pool.
   They were captured without incident about 400 miles away.
   London Patrolman Billy Osborne radioed the prison car's license
number to a dispatcher this morning because the car seemed out of
place in this town.
   When the report came back that the vehicle was being sought in an
escape, Osborne called for backup and the town's two other officers
responded.
   A spokesman at the penitentiary said West Virginia authorities
were awaiting word on how the inmates will be returned.
   Moundsville Warden Jerry Hedrick said the escape occurred early
Wednesday when an inmate crashed a gate in a stolen maintenance
truck and was followed by the second pirsoner in the car. The truck
was abandoned a short distance away.
   The motor pool is outside the 122-year-old prison's stone walls
but surrounded by a chain-link fence, Hedrick said.
   Rakes is serving a life sentence without parole for the 1980
robbery-murder of a 74-year-old man. Wimmer is serving two life
sentences, one without parole, for the 1979 slayings of his
estranged wife and their two children.
