<2ND_LINE>PM-Council Slurs,0174</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chicago City Council Vote to Curb Aldermanic Slurs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chicago's rough-and-tumble City Council has passed
a measure designed to curb sexual, racial or ethnic insults during
committee hearings.
   The measure passed 25-18 Wednesday despite objections from
several aldermen that it would restrict their rights in questioning
mayoral appointees or witnesses.
   The resolution was introduced by Alderwoman Kathy Osterman in
reaction to what she felt were irrelevant and inappropriate
questions of witnesses.
   The resolution says religious beliefs, gender and heritage
``shall be considered irrelevant and inappropriate considerations in
the decisions regarding appointment, confirmations or eligibility to
present testimony.''
   Alderman Robert Shaw insisted that the measure would infringe on
the council's ``right to be vigilant and protect the public
interest,'' in addition to barring questioning of membership in such
groups as the Ku Klux Klan.
   Shaw was accused last month by a Jewish organization of
``Jew-baiting'' during a committee hearing, a charge he denied.
   Osterman insisted the measure was not designed to stifle
responsible questioning.
</TEXT>
