<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-88 1017EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WashingtonPortrait     11-17 0352</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington Portrait,0360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Portrait of Washington Sold For $497,000</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Gilbert Stuart portrait of George Washington
that sold in London for $497,000 was sold in New York five months
earlier for only $3,300 because of questions about its authenticity,
says a report published today.
   The painting of the president in a dark blue coat and white neck
cloth sold Wednesday for more than five times its top estimate.
   Both Sotheby's in London, which auctioned the painting Wednesday,
and Christie's East in New York, which auctioned it earlier this
year, said they had asked Marvin Sadik, an expert on Washington
portraits, about the painting's authenticity and had based their
descriptions on his opinion, The New York Times reported.
   Sadik, former director of the Smithsonian Institution's National
Portrait Gallery in Washington and now a consultant and art dealer
in Falmouth, Maine, told the Times he had seen only photographs of
the painting. He also said he was not paid for the opinions he had
given.
   A Christie's spokeswoman, Roberta Maneker, said the work had been
consigned in 1987 as a George Washington painting in the style of
Gilbert Stuart. She declined to identify the painting's owner.
   Debra Force, a Christie's specialist in American paintings, said
she showed the actual painting to Sadik in New York last November or
December because of doubts about its authenticty and Sadik said it
was not by Stuart, the Times said.
   But Sadik said he could not recall seeing the painting.
   James Miller, specialist in British paintings at Sotheby's in
London, told the Times that a Briton purchased the painting in New
York, brought it to London and ``recognized what the painting was.''
It was auctioned as a Stuart painting.
   The painting was purchased Wednesday by the Berry-Hill Gallery of
New York. Miller, who conducted the auction, said it had belonged to
President James Madison and had hung in Madison's Virginia home.
   Sotheby's had estimated its value at only $54,000 to $90,500
because it was one of more than 100 portraits of the president that
Stuart painted after Washington died in 1799, Miller said.
</TEXT>
