<1ST_LINE>u i PM-SAfrica-Gunman 1stLd-Writethru   11-17 0606</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SAfrica-Gunman, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0503,0626</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede JOHANNESBURG</HEAD>
<HEAD>White Racist Group Banned; Suspect in Black Shootings to Mental
Hospital</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: New thruout with government banning white supremacist group;
changes byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government today banned a
white supremacist group after a self-proclaimed white racist was
charged with shooting to death six blacks during a casual walk
through Pretoria.
   Barend Strydom, 23, was ordered to undergo treatment at a
psychiatric hospital after a court hearing, in which he appeared in
khaki clothes and leg irons.
   Strydom, a former policeman, smiled throughout the hearing before
Magistrate P. Johnson. He said he had no desire to cooperate with
the court.
   Later, the government banned the small White Liberation Movement,
the first time such action has been taken against a right-wing
group. Strydom has been linked to two extremist organizations,
including the large Afrikaner Resistance Movement, but not to the
White Liberation Movement.
   Both groups have swastika-type symbols and have expressed
sympathy for the Nazis.
   Law and Order Minister Adriaan Vlok imposed the ban under
national emergency regulations, which have also been used to ban 23
anti-apartheid organizations. He did not explain why the White
Liberation Movement in particular was outlawed.
   The Movement was formed in 1985 but did not come to public notice
until 1987. Its leader, Johan Schabort, said it has more than 1,000
members but many more sympathizers.
   He said the government's action reduced the ``outlet for
frustration of white South Africans. ... Now we cannot control
people who are worried about their race survival. Some of them could
organize underground.''
   Schabort, a biochemist, said his group supports banishment of all
Jewish and Indian South Africans to Israel or India and removal of
all blacks from white urban centers, including the ``clearing out''
of Soweto, home to 2.5 million blacks outside Johannesburg.
   He said the group does not support violence and added, ``I fully
blame the government for what happened in Pretoria on Tuesday.''
   ``Whites are living under tremendous pressure and are being
undermined by blacks,'' Schabort said.
   The shooting spree prompted government officials to promise a
broad crackdown on white extremists.
   Dr. Willem Pieterse, a court-appointed psychiatrist who examined
the suspect, said Strydom showed symptoms of being a psychopath and
had expressed pride in what he had done.
   Strydom was sent to Weskoppies Hospital for 30 days of
observation and ordered to reappear in court Dec. 19.
   He was charged with murdering six blacks and attempting to murder
17 as he walked, smiling and laughing, through downtown Pretoria
firing an automatic pistol.
   Speaking in Afrikaans, Strydom told the court, ``If communists
such as (Anglican Archbishop) Desmond Tutu and (former South African
ambassador to the United Kingdom) Dennis Worrall are arrested, then
I will cooperate.''
   Strydom frequently turned to wave at his family in the courtroom,
which was packed and guarded by policemen with shotguns. In an
unusual move, photographers were allowed inside.
   Nic Strydom, a retired policeman who is a member of the movement,
and another son were present, wearing business suits.
   Members of the movement frequently dress in khaki uniforms and
wear swastika-type emblems and weapons.
   Critics of the white minority government frequently have
questioned why right-wing white organizations which appear to
espouse violence are not banned while anti-apartheid organizations
are outlawed.
   A member of the governing National Party raised the question
again Wednesday. A government official said an investigation would
have to be conducted.
   Under apartheid, South Africa's 26 million blacks have not vote
in national affairs and the country's 5 million whites control the
economy and maintain separate residential districts, schools and
health services.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
