<1ST_LINE>r i PM-France-Beaujolais     11-17 0347</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-France-Beaujolais,0357</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Devotees and Sceptics Debate Merits As New Beaujolais Arrives</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLINE ALLEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seals came off the barrels and corks popped all over
Paris today after the midnight embargo on consumption of this year's
Beaujolais nouveau expired.
   Thousands of Parisians braved the chill of the November night to
sip a glass of the wine whose annual export by jet, helicopter, boat
and truck to all corners of the world has boosted both image and
sales of the French viticulture industry.
   Outside Le Val d'Or wine bar near the Champs Elysees, two
220-liter barrels of the light red wine, specially chosen by owner
Geraud Rongier, were emptying fast.
   ``This year, it's good, very light, very perfumed,'' Rongier said.
   At other watering holes, waiters like Jean-Louis Ribolla said the
wine has the same aftertaste and aroma of banana as last year's
vintage.
   Le Figaro newspaper described this year's batch of Beaujolais as
``more nuanced, more subtle and more traditional than last year's.''
   Not all the French are seduced by what some maintain is media
hype of the annual uncorking meant to bluff foreigners. ``I never
drank the stuff before all this started and I still don't,'' growled
one seasoned customer.
   Beaujolais distributers work to perfect the near mythic annual
arrival of the wine, and some fretted Wednesday as a dock strike
held up 230 trucks with the precious cargo bound for Britain at
Calais. They were rerouted to Boulogne and Dunkirk.
   ``The paralysis of the port today (Wednesday) is a real disaster
for business and the image of the Beaujolais,'' said Henri Ravisse,
president of the Chamber of Commerce and Industry at Calais.
   Last year, 8 million bottles of Beaujolais crossed the Channel to
invade beer-based English pubs.
   One German driver bound for Dortmund in West Germany was
evidently convinced of the qualities of this year's harvest. He was
arrested as his truck laden with 20,000 bottles zigzaged down the
highway late Tuesday.
   The driver, who's name was not released, was banned from driving
in France for six months, police said.
</TEXT>
