<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Pakistan-Election 4thLd-Writethru a0551 11-17 0809</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pakistan-Election, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0551,0835</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bhutto Claims Victory, Calls For Permission To Form Government</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 10th graf, `She said...' to CORRECT that Bhutto sees no
problem forming coalition; PICKS up 11th pvs, `The country's...</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY9</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BIERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Populist leader Benazir Bhutto
defeated her right-wing opponents in Pakistan's first free national
elections in 11 years and today called on the president to let her
form the new government.
   In Wednesday's balloting, the voters gave ``a mandate for
democracy, dignity ... justice and technology,'' the 35-year-old
politician told reporters at her family villa in southern Sind
province.
   The U.S.-educated Ms. Bhutto would be the first woman to lead a
Moslem nation if she is chosen to form the government. Pakistan was
run by Gen. Mohammed Zia ul-Haq until his death Aug. 17 in a plane
crash.
   Ms. Bhutto's Pakistan People's Party captured 92 seats in the
237-member National Assembly, easily outpacing its main rival, the
right-wing Islamic Democratic Alliance, which won 55 seats.
   Independent candidates and minor parties captured 57 seats.
Results from 13 races were not available.
   The remaining 20 seats will be filled by women chosen by the
elected assembly members.
   Two of the Alliance's three major figures, including former Prime
Minister Mohammad Khan Junejo, were defeated by People's Party
candidates.
   About 30 political parties fielded candidates, but the campaign
boiled down to a race between the People's Party and the nine-party
Alliance, which includes loyalists of Zia.
   Ms. Bhutto said President Ghulam Ishaq Khan ``should now call
upon the PPP to form the government,'' which would allow her to
recapture the prime ministership her father lost in a 1977 coup.
   She said the People's Party had already started talking with
other left-leaning parties and said forming a governing coalition
would not be difficult.
   The country's Constitution requires Ishaq Khan to choose a prime
minister who will be ``most likely to command the confidence of the
majority of the National Assembly,'' but he is under no deadline to
act.
   Asked Wednesday whether he would be reluctant to designate a
woman as head of government of this male-dominated soceity, Ishaq
Khan replied: ``I think a woman prime minister might be a good
change.''
   The army pledged had not interfere in Wednesday's balloting and
thousands of soldiers and police were deployed for the election,
which was largely peaceful.
   Junejo, once the undisputed leader of the Alliance-dominating
Pakistan Muslim League, was defeated in his hometown of Sindhri by a
People's Party candidate.
   The chairman of the Alliance and leader of the center-right
National People's Party, Ghulam Mustafa Jatoi, lost to People's
Party candidates in both districts he contested.
   The Alliance's leading political strongman, Punjab chief minister
Nawaz Sharif, was assured a seat from Lahore.
   Ms. Bhutto, in a show of her personal popularity, won all three
seats she was contesting.
   Candidates could contest more than one seat to improve their
chance of election, but must forfeit all but one. The vacant seats
are contested later.
   While she monitored election results, about 5,000 supporters
gathered in the streets outside, dancing and chanting, ``Benazir,
prime minister.''
   Officials reported no major violence or fraud in the nationwide
balloting despite widespread fears of disruption. Newspapers today
reported three election-related deaths, but the incidents could not
be immediately confirmed.
   The election focused on political personalities.
   Ms. Bhutto's father was Zulfikar Ali Bhutto, whose government was
toppled by Zia in 1977. Zia had him hanged two years later.
   She proved a charismatic campaigner, drawing enthusiastic crowds
numbering in the tens of thousands throughout the country.
   Ms. Bhutto and the Alliance both pledged to continue close ties
with the United States, to support anti-communist guerrillas in
neighboring Afghanistan and to stick to Zia's program to make
Pakistan a more Islamic nation.
   But she said she would not allow the religious policy to harm
women's and minorities' rights. Considered very Westernized, she
studied at Harvard and Oxford.
   About 48 million of Pakistan's 107 million people were eligible
to vote and unofficial estimates said slightly more than half voted.
Illiterate millions chose their candidates by symbol, and men and
women voted separately, in keeping with strict Moslem practice.
   Zia ruled for eight years under martial law before holding
national elections in 1985. Ms. Bhutto's party and other opposition
groups boycotted those polls, allowing a sweep by candidates who
barely hid their ties to the Muslim League.
   The league formed a government under Junejo, but Zia abruptly
fired the Junejo Cabinet in May and dissolved the National Assembly,
accusing them of corruption, incompetence and dragging their feet on
Islamization.
   Several Muslim League members stayed on in a Zia-appointed
caretaker government.
   Zia called Wednesday's elections before he died in a plane crash
that also killed the U.S. ambassador and 28 other people. The cause
of the crash has not yet been determined.
</TEXT>
