<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Prince     11-17 0306</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Prince,0313</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Deputies Dethrone High School `Prince'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DAYTON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who masqueraded as the Prince of
Morocco at a high school and once rented a limousine to carry him to
a school football game has been charged with receiving stolen
property _ the sporty red car he drove to class.
   Michael W. Taylor, who is actually 27 or 28, enrolled as
17-year-old Prince Sparkle Shannon on the third day of classes at
Meadowdale High School, affecting a foreign accent. He was polite,
punctual and shy, school officials said.
   ``He fit in well,'' Principal Ben Kirby said. ``He dressed like a
student, acted like a student. In terms of behavior, I could have
used a few hundred more Prince Sparkles.''
   Taylor was the subject of an article in the school newspaper and
recently told student leaders that he would inherit the Moroccan
throne when King Hassan II died. Taylor also said he had studied
with the KGB in the Soviet Union.
   Taylor, who was enrolled as a senior, dressed in the latest
fashions, with gold around his neck and a large diamond on his
finger, school officials said. He shunned school buses in favor of
his red 1988 Dodge Daytona.
   The Louisville, Ky., man was arrested Wednesday and jailed on
$7,500 bond. Kentucky authorities planned to go before a grand jury
today with more than 50 counts of fraud and related crimes,
investigators said.
   Police believe Taylor used another man's name when he bought the
car in Louisville, said Montgomery County sheriff's detective Bob
Weaver. Weaver said the theft was discovered when the other man
protested a bill received for the car.
   ``When we confronted him with the name Mike Taylor, he knew we
had him so he basically admitted that it was him,'' Weaver said.
``And that accent cleared up real fast.''
</TEXT>
