<DOCNO> AP881117-0096 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-88 1106EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Bishops 1stLd-Writethru a0464 11-17 0827</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bishops, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0464,790</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: First 6 grafs new, picking up 2nd graf pvs, And, far</NOTE>
<HEAD>Bishops Reject Vatican Document _ Politely</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT FURLOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's Roman Catholic bishops concluded
their annual meeting today with formal pleas for religious liberty
in Eastern Europe and for the easing of a law covering legal status
for undocumented Hispanic workers in the United States.
   Archbishop Roger Mahony of Los Angeles said the bishops were
challenging Soviet leaders, whose policies have heavy influence
throughout Eastern Europe, ``to match their recent talk of reform
with concrete action.''
   Despite improvements in some countries, the church leaders said
in their statement, ``A general pattern of intolerance of religion
remains clearly evident.''
   As for Hispanic workers, the bishops said in a separate statement
that there is widespread discrimination in this country, partly
because employers don't understand immigration rules concerning whom
they can or can't hire.
   The bishops said they are compiling files of discrimination cases
in hopes of persuading lawmakers to rewrite the law.
   One day earlier, the bishops politely but firmly told the Vatican
to go back and start over on its document questioning the authority
of national bishops conferences such as theirs.
   And, far from expecting an angry reaction from Rome, one of the
bishops' leaders says he expects Vatican officials to do as the
American churchmen are asking.
   About 100 such conferences around the world were asked to comment
on the Vatican draft, and Bishop James Malone of Youngstown, Ohio,
said Wednesday that many of them seem to be ``expressing opinions
similar to ours.'' In response, the Vatican will likely work up a
new draft, he said, though the bishops are not predicting what it
might say.
   The U.S. bishops voted 205-59 earlier Wednesday _ barely meeting
the required two-thirds of the conference's 305 active members _ to
reject the Vatican draft.
   Before the vote, they softened the tone of their rejection notice
considerably. But they stood firm when Cardinal Bernard Law of
Boston and several other bishops tried to amend the response even
further, so it would merely ask for more work on the Vatican draft
rather than a new start.
   ``Half a loaf is better than none,'' Law said.
   Malone's committee of past conference presidents was first to
give ground, withdrawing the original version of the bishops'
response on Monday, the first day of the church leaders' annual
meeting.
   Suddenly gone from the bishops' proposed description of the
Vatican draft were such phrases as ``rigid and confusing'' and
``overly defensive and negative.''
   Then Wednesday, by voice vote, the bishops deleted these words:
``non placet _ the draft is not suitable.'' Several bishops had
argued that the phrase, especially the formal Latin, was too blunt,
perhaps even offensive to the Vatican.
   Still, the final version says elsewhere, ``We do not believe that
the working document is suitable as a basis for discussion.''
   The first version had received considerable news coverage, and
some bishops have criticized the accounts as too negative.
   However, Archbishop John Roach of St. Paul-Minneapolis, a member
of Malone's committee, said, ``They perceived a sharpness in the
tone of the document which I don't think we intended'' and helped
spur the bishops to write a better response to the Vatican.
   The American bishops' most controversial efforts _ their national
pastoral letters taking issue with Reagan administration policies on
nuclear weapons and on treatment of the poor _ have won public
praise from Pope John Paul II.
   However, the rising prominence of such conferences has also
brought criticism from Vatican officials, who note that such
organizations are not part of the Roman church's traditional
hierarchy.
   The Vatican draft declares that bishops conferences have little
real standing, that the church lodges authority in the individual
bishops under the pope, the bishop of Rome.
   The U.S. bishops, in their reply, do not lay out a case arguing
that the Vatican is wrong. Rather, they argue that the draft
distorts some evidence and generally gives only one side of the
matter.
   On another topic, the bishops also voted Wednesday to set
guidelines on preaching by lay men and women during Catholic masses.
   Several bishops said the guidelines could lead to more such
preaching. But others noted that they reiterated clear strictures
against anyone other than an ordained minister preaching the main
sermon interpreting the gospel during mass.
   Retired Bishop William McManus of Fort Wayne-South Bend, Ind.,
argued that the guidelines restating that implicit ban on some
preaching by women _ who cannot be ordained as Catholic ministers _
would be an unnecessary new ``source of irritation'' for the
denomination's women.
   He offered what he described as the ridiculous possibility that a
local church would have Mother Teresa as its guest but could allow
her to speak only early in the service or at the very end, leaving
the main sermon to a male deacon parroting ``Bible lessons he
learned in the second grade.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
