<1ST_LINE>r a PM-RobinHoodTeller     11-17 0241</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Robin Hood Teller,0246</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Says Embezzling Teller Played Robin Hood</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former bank employee who admitted
embezzling $14,000 said she gave part of the money to needy families
who were denied bank loans.
   Sharon Granstaff Morgan, 21, was placed on five years' probation
Wednesday for stealing in 1986-87 from Commerce Union Bank, where
she was in charge of issuing travelers checks and savings bonds. She
pleaded guilty to embezzlement Sept. 9.
   ``You just ran a private charity, Ms. Morgan,'' said U.S.
District JUdge Thomas A. Wiseman Jr. ``You took from the bank and
gave to these families, thinking you were Robin Hood.''
   Ms. Morgan told Wiseman she gave money to two needy families who
had been denied bank loans. Defense attorney Bill Farmer said the
gifts constituted a ``substantial'' portion of what she took and
that the families needed groceries and clothing.
   ``It's a commendable trait to want to help people,'' the judge
said, ``but you can't buy friendships.''
   Ms. Morgan claimed to have stolen about $14,000; bank officials
said she cost them $27,650. Wiseman ordered her to repay $19,500. He
also ordered her to perform fours hours a week of community service
work for a year.
   ``She took money from what people paid her to buy travelers'
checks and savings bonds, destroyed records, turned in falsified
amounts to American Express and the bank and simply kept the
money,'' said Assistant U.S. Attorney Wendy Goggin.
</TEXT>
