<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>WASHN: to comment.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Bush had shrugged off repeated questions about his reported
choice of Sununu, which cheered conservatives but worried some
others including Jewish lobbyists still upset with the New Hampshire
governor for being the only governor to refuse to endorse a
proclamation attacking a 1975 U.N. resolution that equated zionism
with racism.
   Sununu, who is Arab-American, told reporters in Concord Wednesday
he refused to sign the proclamation because he felt ``it was
inappropriate for a governor to try to ... influence foreign
policy.''
   Sununu has a reputation for being a quick study, highly
intelligent and assertive. Some regard him as as arrogant and
abrasive, traits that could hurt him in working with Congress. He
made light of that reputation Wednesday when asked to describe his
managerial skills.
   ``I am what I am _ a warm, charming effective manager who by the
skills of gentle encouragement of individuals ... has been able to
do a few good things for the state of New Hampshire,'' he said.
   Sununu had declined to run for a fourth term, citing a need to
return to ``the real world to get a real job.'' Sununu and his wife,
Nancy, have eight children. He is credited with helping revive
Bush's candidacy with a win in the New Hampshire primary last
February after the vice president finished a poor third in Iowa's
caucuses.
   Sources also said Atwater was a strong contender to take over
chairmanship of the RNC from Fahrenkopf, a 48-year-old Reno lawyer
whose seven years in the post make him the longest-serving GOP chief
in this century.
   Atwater, 37, was a chief architect of Bush's winning campaign. A
South Carolina native, Atwater was a White House aide to President
Reagan and also worked for Sen. Strom Thurmond of South Carolina.
