<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Poachers,0194</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Kill 2 Poachers, Recover Two Rifles</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police fought a gunbattle with elephant
poachers in a national park, killing two of them, a newspaper
reported Thursday.
   The poachers were killed Wednesday in Tsavo East National Park in
a gunbattle with paramilitary police, the Standard reported. Police
sought an undisclosed number of other poachers Thursday, it said.
   Police were sent to reinforce game rangers in Tsavo East and
neighboring Tsavo West national parks, 225 miles south of Nairobi,
in August after poachers killed a ranch foreman and a policeman.
Nine policemen and rangers were injured.
   The government has embarked on a campaign to stop the widespread
slaughter of its elephants. Newspapers say 160 elephants have been
killed by poachers since May.
   Kenya's elephant population has fallen by 15 percent in the past
15 years, according to a United Nations study. An aerial survey in
February of the Tsavo area found fewer than 5,500 elephants, down
from 35,000 in 1974.
   Experts blame the intensified slaughter on an all-time high ivory
price, which has climbed steadily since the early 1970s and averages
$82 per pound.
