<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Religious,0366</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Orthodox Party Demanding Religious Radio Station</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ultra-Orthodox Shas political party has
asked Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir to create a radio station with
exclusively religious programming, a spokesman for the party said
Thursday.
   ``We would like to bring some of the light the Torah gives to the
people,'' said Shas spokesman Moshe Peretz said. ``Many of our own
people do not know the ABCs of Judaism because they are denied by
the educational system.''
   Shamir's hardline Likud party has made many concessions to Shas
in order to gain the support of the religious party, which controls
six seats in the parliament, or Knesset. Chief among them was a
promise to amend a law narrowing the definition of who is a Jew.
   Shamir was asked to form the government by President Chaim Herzog
after his party got 40 seats, compared with 39 for the rival Labor
Party, in Nov. 1 elections for the 120-seat parliament. But
negotiations to form a coaltion still are continuing.
   The Shas party, which represents Sephardic Jews _ those of North
African and Arab origin _ also has requested the creation of a
third, separate school system to be devoted to educating Orthodox
Sephardic students.
   The financially strapped, state-financed school system already
supports both secular and religious school systems.
   Peretz said Likud has not received definite answers about the
radio station or the school system.
   The Hadashot newspaper said last week that Likud would transform
Israel's only classical music program into a religious station.
There are three state-run radio stations, and an additional station
run by the armed forces.
   The proposed radio station would broadcast courses on Judaism and
be used to counter attacks Peretz charged were made routinely by the
mainstream media.
   ``There are journalists in Israel who find it their goal in life
to attack Judaism,'' he said. ``We would like to bring to the people
the right face of Judaism.
   ``The real security of Israel will be in the moral fabric of the
people. We want to bring people back closer to the Jewish roots, to
see the strength of the people,'' he said.
</TEXT>
