<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Reagan-Trade     11-17 0787</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Trade,770</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Softens U.S. Stand on Agricultural Subsidies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan, seeking to give new impetus
to international trade negotiations, announced Thursday he is
dropping a demand that other countries join the United States in
phasing out agricultural subsidies by the year 2000.
   An eventual elimination of government interventions into farm
markets remains the American goal, Reagan said in a speech to the
U.S. Chamber of Commerce.
   But he acknowledged that talks under the auspices of the General
Agreement on Tariffs and Trade have beast in part,
because of the U.S. demand for a fixed deadline fogged down, at lor getting
governments out of the business of subsidizing their agricultural
economies.
   Reagan failed, at the seven-nation economic summit in Toronto at
the end of May, to persuade principal U.S. trade partners to endorse
such a timetable, which has been criticized heatedly by the European
Economic Community and Japan.
   On Tuesday, U.S. Trade Representative Clayton Yeutter announced a
new U.S. proposal to be taken up at the mid-term review of the
Uruguay Round of talks under GATT. The proposal called for a freeze
on all farm price supports, subsidies and trade barriers in the next
two years, but made no mention of an end-of-century deadline for
phasing subsidies out.
   Noting the coming mid-term review in t. It is a testament to the commitment
of our two
governments to the principles of the open market and to economic
cooperation.''
   The United States' government subsidized American agriculture in
the amount of more than $26 billion in the fiscal year that ended
Sept. 30, and there has been little enthusiasm in Congress for the
administration's push to lower the government's profile in the
farming business.
   Reagan said that instead of continuing to pursue agreement on a
phase-out deadline of the year 2000, the U.S. negotiators will ``be
ready to discuss flexible adjustment'' procedures to cushion the
shock of ending subsidies. He said the United States would be
``flexible about timetables so long as everyone agrees on nailing
down an adjustment plan with specific dates for ending
trade-distorting subsidies and market access barriers. The final
goal is what is important.''
   Reagan also said that the United States recognizes the concerns
of many nations among the 96 that are members of GATT, over the
question of ``food security'' _ or the worry on the part of some
nations that if trade barriers disappear, they would be left at the
mercy of others in the event of food shortages.
   ``Again, they may have a point,'' he said. ``And so, in Montreal,
we'll be ready to talk about government stockpiles, land purchases
and other ways of dealing with what has been called `food security.'
''
   On another matter, Reagan told his business audience that the
U.S. policy of seeking to open new markets for American products and
to remove trade barriers will continue intact under President-elect
George Bush.
   In fact, he said, ``President-elect Bush has been on board every
step of the way. Anyone who thinks that American policy in this area
might shift with the new administration or the new Congress is
deluding himself.''
   He said he and Bush would meet with Yeutter and Secretary of
Agriculture Richard Lyng to ``reiterate our mutual support'' before
the Montreal talks.
   Among other key objectives of U.S. GATT negotiators in Montreal,
Reagan said, are these:
   _Steps to improve intellectual property protections, particularly
to attack counterfeiting and piracy.
   _Establish rules which for the first time would cover trade in
services, as well as in goods and products.
   _Steps to bring about greater discipline over trade-related
investment.
</TEXT>
