<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--DamSafe     11-17 0179</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Dam Safe,0182</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Experts Say Willow Creek Dam Reliable</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Willow Creek Dam above the Eastern
Oregon town of Heppner is reliable, according to a review panel
asked to look at the safety of the flood-control dam because of
worry about erosion.
   Criticism of the dam's design was without merit, the five-member
technical panel said in its report. The dam was the first in the
nation built entirely by the roller-compacting method rather than
the traditional method of pouring concrete.
   The review was ordered by Sen. Mark Hatfield, a ranking
Republican on the Senate energy and water subcommittee.
   In a statement issued after the panel's report was released
Wednesday, Hatfield said the allegations of safety problems were
`quite serious,'' but ``after a thorough study by Army experts and
an independent investigator, it appears reasonable to assert those
concerns were unfounded.''
   The 169-foot-high dam was completed in 1983 at a cost of $34.7
million to protect residents of Heppner. In 1903, one third of the
town's population died in a flash flood of Willow Creek.
</TEXT>
