<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--TBOutbreak     11-17 0159</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--TB Outbreak,0162</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tuberculosis Outbreak Reported in Enterprise Schools</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ENTERPRISE, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least 250 students in the Enterprise
School District should receive preventive medication for
tuberculosis because of their contact with a senior who has the
respiratory disease, officials said.
   Dr. Margaret Morrison, state health officer for the east
Mississippi area, said the disease may have spread because the
unidentified student, who is hospitalized, had attended school for
some time before he sought medical treatment.
   Morrison said the faculty and all 800 students in the rural
district's two schools were tested for TB. She said the 16 people
who tested positive are on medication.
   She recommended that at least 250 additional students who may
have been exposed to the disease receive medication to prevent
future health problems. School officials say a note was sent home
with those children suggesting they see a doctor and get preventive
medication.
   The students will be retested in March, Morrison said.
</TEXT>
