<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland     11-17 0650</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland,0670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Walesa Reported to Accept Date for TV Debate with Official Union
Chief</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa has aghat the date was
acceptable to Walesa, but the banned union considered the
arrangements tentative.
   In another development, 51 people ended a hunger strike in the
southern city of Katowice after winning the reinstatement of the
last of about 100 miners dismissed in August for striking. The
decision clears away one of the major obstacles blocking promised
talks between authorities and the opposition.
   Alfred Miodowicz, a member of the ruling Politburo in addition to
being leader of the official union alliance known by its Polish
initials OPZZ, had challenged Walesa to a debate Tuesday in the
Communist Party daily Trybuna Ludu.
   Polish radio announced the debate should take place after the
evening news Nov. 30. The state-run news agency PAP later carried an
identical report.
   Walesa on Tuesday agreed in principle for a televised debate on
union issues.
   It would be Walesa's first appearance on state TV since 1983,
when he challenged then-Deputy Prime Minister Mieczyslaw F. Rakowski
during a televised speech at the Lenin Shipyard in Gdansk. Rakowski
became Poland's prime minister in September.
   Attempts to reach Walesa for comment were not successful. His
wife said he was not at his Gdansk home.
   Solidarity spokesman Robert Kozak confirmed the date was
acceptable to Walesa, but said the union considered it to be
tentative. He did not elaborate.
   Walesa earlier authorized Solidarity adviser Adam Michnik and
Solidarity national spokesman Janusz Onyszkiewicz to make the
technical arrangements. But neither of them was at home late Tuesday
to answer questions.
   Walesa and Miodowicz will face the cameras alone without any
advisers for 45 to 60 minutes, the radio report said.
   Miodowicz indicated the debate might be a partial substitute for
the talks authorities promised during the August wave of strikes.
The talks were to consider the issue of union pluralism and broader
topics of economic and political reform.
   Besides the fate of the dismissed miners, the talks have been
delayed by government objections to the participation of Solidarity
advisers Jacek Kuron and Michnik.
   Miodowicz has headed the official unions since they were set up
by the government in 1982 after the authorities banned Solidarity,
the Soviet bloc's first independent trade union.
   Solidarity supporters, demanding their union be made legal again,
believe more than one union should be allowed in each workplace
because the OPZZ does not adequately represent workers.
   Miodowicz favors one union in one enterprise and says Solidarity
activists are welcome to join his unions and try to change them from
within.
   In Katowice, Adam Slomka, a spokesman for 51 people fasting since
Saturday in the Christ the King Cathedral, said the agreement to
rehire dismissed workers was reached through the mediation of Roman
Catholic Bishop Damian Zimon.
   ``We managed to achieve in five days what hadn't been achieved in
several months,'' said Slomka, speaking by telephone from the
cathedral. He said agreement was reached late Wednesday with the
national coal federation to reinstate the workers as of Thursday.
   Workers broke their fast Thursday morning, eating rolls with
butter and sweetened tea, Slomka said.
   Slomka said 49 miners who still had not been reinstated were to
be restored to their old jobs. He said only two workers at the
Stalowa Wola steel mill in southeast Poland, another region of the
country, have not gotten back their jobs since the August strikes.
   Tadeusz Napieracz, a deputy director at the coal federation, the
body that oversees the mines, confirmed the reinstatements, but he
denied they had been fired. He said officials wanted to reassign
them, while the miners insisted on their jobs back.
</TEXT>
