<HEAD>Car Belonging To Missing Adults Found; Four Bodies Discovered
^Eds: UPDATES with four apparently in an auto accident, other
detail; REMOVES outdated material; tightens throughout. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A car belonging to four young adults
missing since Saturday was found in a river today with four bodies
in it, police and witnesses said. Identities of the victims were not
immediately released.
   The car had approached a swing bridge open at the time and went
over a concrete barrier into the water, said Lt. James Forrentino,
police spokesman.
   Police divers at the scene said they had found four bodies in the
car. Forrentino refused to confirm that.
   The discovery came four days after three women and one man, ages
19 and 20, disappeared after drinking illegally at a bar near Yale
University and leaving together about 3 a.m. Sunday, said state
police Detective Andrew Trudelle.
   He said the information came from an employee of the bar, which
under state law can't serve anyone under 21.
   Police divers found the group's car submerged in about 15 feet of
water in the Mill River, in a little-traveled, old industrial part
of the city, police said. A crane was brought in to remove the car.
   Earlier today, Francis ``Bud'' Mullen, former head of the federal
Drug Enforcement Agency and a private investigator looking for the
four, said he believed the friends from East Lyme were being held
against their will by someone.
   The four were last seen by their parents at 7 p.m. Saturday, when
they left for an evening in New Haven. Mullen was hired by their
parents.
   ``I believe they're in New Haven and being held against their
wills,'' said Mullen, who also worked previously for the FBI. His
first major case with the FBI was as an agent assigned to the 1963
kidnapping of Frank Sinatra Jr.
   Family and friends described the four former high school buddies
as responsible adults unlikely to take off without telling anyone.
The parents distributed pictures of the missing and offered a
$25,000 reward, Mullen said.
   The missing adults were: Jill Sawyer, 19, a student at the
University of Rhode Island; Christy Stevens, 19, a student at
Mohegan Community College in Norwich; Michael Gallo, 20, a student
at Southern Connecticut; and Laura Lagrotteria, 19.
</TEXT>
