<HEAD>Precede BAGHDAD, Iraq</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New material, editing thruout</NOTE>
<HEAD>US Diplomat Expelled for Contact with Kurds and US Retaliates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department today denounced as
``unjustified'' Iraqi's expulsion of an American diplomat and
retaliated by throwing out an Iraqi diplomat stationed here.
   Referring to the American diplomat, identified in Baghdad as
Haywood Rankin, head of the U.S. Embassy's political section, State
Department spokesman Charles E. Redman said, ``None of his
activities have been incompatible in any way with his diplomatic
status.''
   Assistant Secretary of State Richard W. Murphy informed the Iraqi
ambassador, Abdul-Amir Al-Anbari, that an Iraqi diplomat here had
been declared persona non grata, Redman said.
   He said ``this action was taken in response to the unjustified
expulsion of a U.S. diplomat in Baghdad by the Iraqi goverment.''
Redman declined to identify the Iraqi or his job.
   In Baghdad, speaking on condition of anonymity, diplomats said
Rankin was asked to leave Iraq after making an unauthorized trip to
the north, home of Iraq's estimated 3.5 million Kurds.
   Both the Iraqi Ministry of Foreign Affairs and the U.S. Embassy
refused to comment on Rankin's expulsion. Diplomats said he already
has left Iraq.
   About 60,000 Kurds fled across the northern border to Turkey and
thousands of others went into Iran in August, claiming Iraq dropped
chemical bombs on their villages.
   Militants among the 20 million Kurds living in a region extending
into Turkey, Iran and Iraq have fought for independence for a
century.
   Iraq pounded Kurdish settlements on its northwestern border
shortly after accepting an Aug. 20 cease-fire in its 8-year-old war
with Iran. Kurdish guerrillas received support from Iran during the
war.
   The Congress considered economic sanctions against Iraq, based on
State Department reports it was using chemical weapons against the
Kurds. Iraq denied the use and the legislation was dropped in the
rush to close Congress before the November presidential elections in
the United States.
</TEXT>
