<2ND_LINE>AM-Transition-Cabinet, 1st Add,720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>WASHN: Ehrlenborn, R-Ill.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>HEALTH AND HUMAN SERVICES</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A Republican member of Congress figures prominently in the
handicapping for a successor to former Indiana Gov. (and M.D.) Otis
R. Bowen _ as HHS secretary. But a physician who heads a non-profit
hospital chain has also emerged as a front-runner.
   They are:
   _Rep. Willis D. Gradison Jr. of Ohio, the ranking Republican on
the House Ways and Means health subcommittee and an architect of
Medicare's new catastrophic illness insurance insurance.
   _Dr. Monroe Trout, the head of American Healthcare Systems, a
close friend of future first lady Barbara Bush from their service
together on the board of Morehouse College, a black institution in
Atlanta.
   Rep. Lynn Martin, R-Ill., is also a possibility. Dorcas Hardy,
the Social Security commissioner and longtime Reaganite, has her
hand raised. Deborah Steelman, Bush's domestic policy adviser during
the campaign, is also a possibility.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>HOUSING AND URBAN DEVELOPMENT</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary Samuel R. Pierce Jr. is the only original Reagan
Cabinet member left. He'll head back to New York to practice law.
   His successor could be Cleveland Mayor George Voinovich, who just
lost a bid to unseat Sen. Howard Metzenbaum, D-Ohio. Bush could tap
Robert Woodson, a black conservative and advocate of turning public
housing projects over to tenants who is president of the National
Center for Neighborhood Enterprise.
   Other possibilities include Deborah Steelman and Thaddeus
Garrett, who was a Bush aide; Maurice Bartsdale, a former HUD
official; and Shirley Wiseman, who is in line to become president of
the National Association of Home Builders. Some have suggested a
possible return engagement for Carla Anderson Hills, HUD secretary
under President Ford.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>TRANSPORTATION</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary Jim Burnley, at 40 the youngest member of Reagan's
Cabinet, has taken himself out of the running.
   Craig Fuller, 37, Bush's vice presidential chief of staff for the
past four years, is a possibility for transportation secretary.
Fuller, a licensed pilot, is also mentioned as a possible head of
the National Aeronautics and Space Adminsitration.
   Jim Burnett, a member and former chairman of the National
Transportation Safety Board, is also mentioned, along with New
Jersey Gov. Thomas Kean and Rep. Guy Molinari, R-N.Y., who ran
Bush's campaign in New York. A strike against Molinari with
conservatives is that he has favored rehiring the striking air
traffic controllers whom Reagan fired in 1981.
   Transportation might also be another place where Rep. Lynn
Martin, R-Ill., could crack the Cabinet circle.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>ENERGY</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary John S. Herrington has served nearly a four-year stint
and is certain to be replaced.
   The possibilities include ALCOA chairman Paul O'Neill, who also
figures prominently in the Defense rumors; Peter Johnson, director
of the Bonneville Power Administration, and former Rep. Thomas
Loeffler of Texas, who ran Bush's campaign in his adopted state.
   Some names on the Interior lists _ Dan Evans and Manuel Lujan _
also figure in the Energy speculation. Other possibilities include
William Martin, a Bush campaign adviser and former deputy secretary
of energy; Martha Hesse, the current chairman of the Federal Energy
Regulatory Commission, and Fred Khedouri, a former OMB official.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>EDUCATION</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary Lauro F. Cavazos, the first Hispanic ever to serve in
the Cabinet, would like to stay there. But after two months on the
job, his fate is in doubt. Conservatives have criticized some of the
former Texas Tech University president's pronouncements and said he
didn't campaign hard enough for Republicans.
   Kean, the New Jersey governor, is a possibility at Education. So
is Rep. Bill Goodling of Pennsylvania, a former school principal and
superintendent who is a leading Republican on the House Education
and Labor Committee. Former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander, now
president of the University of Tennessee system, is also a
possibility.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>VETERANS AFFAIRS</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The 14th and newest Cabinet entity will open for business next
March, and the early favorites to be its inaugural secretary include
two former Vietnam prisoners of war and a Democratic congressman.
   The ex-POWs are Everett Alvarez Jr., a former No. 2 official at
the Veterans Administration who was heavily involved with the Bush
campaign, and former Sen. Jeremiah Denton, R-Ala. Rep. Sonny
Montgomery, D-Miss., chairman of the House Veterans Affairs
Committee, is also a contender.
   Ridge, the Pennsylvania Republican congressman and Vietnam
veteran mentioned as a possible Labor secretary, is also a
possibility, as is Rep. John Paul Hammerschmidt of Arkansas, ranking
Republican on the Veterans Affairs Committee.
</TEXT>
