<1ST_LINE>r a PM-RacialControversy     11-17 0338</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Racial Controversy,0346</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Controversy Erupts over Selection of College President</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EAST PEORIA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Local civil rights leaders have accused
Illinois Central College officials of racism in bypassing a black
Fulbright Scholar and selecting a white man with less experience as
its new president.
   Local NAACP officals said Wednesday they believe racial prejudice
influenced the appointment last week of Thomas K. Thomas, who has
been president of Red Rocks Community College in Lakewood, Colo.,
since March 1987.
   ``The black candidate is a Fulbright Scholar, studied at Harvard
and has 20 years' experience as a college president. The white
candidate has 20 months' experience as a college president,'' said
John Gwynn Jr., state and local president of the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People. ``It was just so
obvious the black candidate was so much more qualified.''
   Trustees at the college voted 5-2 to appoint Thomas, 47, rather
than Abel B. Sykes Jr., 54, president at Kings River Community
College in Reedley, Calif., for 15 years.
   The Peoria NAACP called for the decision to be overturned and
filed complaints with the Illinois Board of Higher Education, the
Illinois Board of Education and the Illinois Department of Human
Rights. State officials said they would investigate.
   Some trustees defended the appointment.
   ``Racism was not an issue in the selection,'' said Douglas
Stewart, chairman of the college's board of trustees. ``I think we
had three qualified candidates provided by the search committee. We
chose one of them.''
   The lone black board member, Louis Owens, disagreed.
   ``If Sykes was white, there is no question that he would have
been chosen,'' Owens said. ``What's worse, had I not been on the
search committee, Dr. Sykes' name would have never come up. I'm
disappointed and devastated.''
   Owens was board chairman but was removed from that position after
the vote on Thomas. Owens said board members told him he was ousted
because they felt he could not support the new president.
   The two-year college serves 12,000 students in eight counties
surrounding Peoria.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
