<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Bulgaria-Israel     11-17 0396</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bulgaria-Israel,0407</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Diplomatic Ties Between Israel, Bulgaria Gain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SOFIA, Bulgaria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The wife of Israeli Premier Yitzhak Shamir
met Thursday with Bulgarian leader Todor Zhivkov, and another
Bulgarian official said diplomatic ties with Israel would be resumed
once unspecified hindrances are gone.
   Shulamit Shamir, who was born in Bulgaria but left at age 17 in
1941, held no substantive talks with Zhivkov, according to Bulgarian
officials at the meeting in Zhivkov's official residence.
   Western journalists were excluded from the meeting, which also
was attended by some participants in a two-day conference examining
Bulgaria's role in saving 50,000 Jews from the Nazis.
   When that conference ended Thursday, Bulgarian host Stefan
Petrov, head of the government news agency Sofia Press, was asked
whether the symposium _ the first of its kind in Communist
Bulgaria's history _ might help to restore ties with Israel.
   ``Diplomatic relations will be established after hindrances are
removed,'' Petrov told an Israeli journalist at a news conference.
He did not say what the hindrances were.
   Bulgaria and all Soviet bloc nations except Romania severed
diplomatic relations with Israel over the 1967 Middle East war.
   The symposium on Bulgaria's rescue of Jews brought together
Jewish leaders from Israel, the United States, France, Austria, East
Germany, and Hungary for the first time on Bulgarian soil.
   The Soviet Union, Poland, Hungary and East Germany recently have
moved to improve relations with international Jewish communities and
with Israel. Czechoslovakia has said it will hold a conference on
the Middle East that officials say will include former Israeli
Foreign Minister Abba Eban.
   Serge Kwajgenbaum, secretary general of the European Jewish
Congress said he met for 45 minutes with Zhivkov on Thursday and
detected Bulgarian willingness to improve ties to Jewish communities
around the world.
   Zhivkov invited the president of the World Jewish Congress, Edgar
Bronfman, to visit Bulgaria as soon as possible, Kwajgenbaum said.
   He indicated, however, that full diplomatic ties between Bulgaria
and Israel would not be restored before Moscow takes the same action.
   Bulgaria has a tiny Jewish community of about 3,000. In 1943,
when the Nazis allied to the Bulgarian government tried to deport
50,000 Jews to death camps in Poland, political and popular protests
and a turn against German fortunes in the war foiled the plan. Most
of the Jews eventually emigrated to Israel after the war.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
