<1ST_LINE>r i AM-USMissiles     11-17 0164</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US Missiles,0168</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First Cruise Missiles Reported Removed From Base</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COMISO, Sicily (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities removed a first group of cruise
missiles from a base Thursday in compliance with the U.S.-Soviet
treaty to eliminate medium- and shorter-range nuclear weapons,
Italian officials reported.
   A Foreign Ministry spokesman said he didn't know the number but
the Italian news agency ANSA said 16 missiles were removed from the
base for eventual destruction in the Arizona desert.
   According to U.S. and Italian officials, 112 Tomahawk cruise
missiles are deployed in Comiso.
   ANSA said the missiles, covered by white canvas sheets, and the
mobile launching pads were transported on special trucks to the
Sigonella NATO air base near Catania.
   Earlier this week, a Soviet team conducted its second inspection
of the base.
   The inspections were made under terms of the 1987 treaty, which
requires the United States and the Soviet Union to eliminate within
three years medium and shorter-range land-based missiles with ranges
from 300 to 3,400 miles.
</TEXT>
