<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ImpersonatorArrested     11-17 0324</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Impersonator Arrested,0336</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Pro Football Player Impersonating Giant Is Arrested In Check
Forgery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HACKENSACK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former pro running back has been
charged with impersonating New York Giants athlete Joe Morris in a
check forgery, the latest in a string of cases in which he posed as
football stars, authorities said.
   Israel Lang, 46, a former reserve player for the Philadelphia
Eagles and Los Angeles Rams, was arrested Tuesday after persuading
United Jersey Bank to cash a check by passing himself off as Morris,
the Giants' all-time leading rusher, police said.
   He was charged with forgery and related counts and jailed on
$75,000 bail.
   Lang retired from pro football in 1969, and authorities said he
had been arrested 24 times since then.
   Lang, who has also been accused of impersonating Lawrence Taylor
and Leonard Marshall of the Giants, as well as other stars, has been
convicted at least eight times of charges including forgery and bank
fraud, authorities said.
   Two months ago, he was freed on $5,000 bail in Virginia on
charges he impersonated Doug Williams, quarterback of the Washington
Redskins, authorities said.
   ``He has been a nemesis to the National Football League,'' said
Warren Welsh, league director of security.
   Despite their name, the Giants play their home games at the
Meadowlands in northern New Jersey.
   ``You are in Giant territory here,'' said police Capt. Emil
Canestrino. ``If someone calls and says, `I'm Joe Morris,' you are
liable to bend the rules. He used the name to open up doors.''
   ``He seems to have some personal information about these
players,'' Welsh said. ``He seems to be the consummate con man.''
   Police said Lang knew Morris had an account at the bank and
called, saying he wanted to open an account for his father-in-law,
named Israel Lang. The imposter was arrested after a second attempt
to pass a $950 check, police said.
   A United Jersey spokeswoman refused to discuss the case.
</TEXT>
