<1ST_LINE>u i PM-KafkaManuscript 1stLd-Writethru a0583 11-17 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Kafka Manuscript, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0583,0322</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Trial' Manuscript Fetches Record of Nearly $2 Million</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf pvs, `The amount ...' to CORRECT that Bauer was
Kafka's fiancee; PICKS up 3rd pvs, `The buyer ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GRAHAM HEATHCOTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The West German government today paid $1.98 million
_ the highest price ever for a modern literary treasure _ for the
handwritten manuscript of Franz Kafka's novel ``The Trial.''
   The amount paid for the manuscript, which came from an
unidentified seller, eclipsed the $605,000 paid in New York last
year for Kafka's letters to his fiancee, Felice Bauer.
   The buyer was a West German antiquarian bookseller, Heribert
Tenschert, who said he was contacted by West German government
authorities to buy the manuscript for the Marbach Literary Institute
near Stuttgart.
   ``It was really surprising, the price,'' he said. ``I would have
bought it for myself''
   The bidding lasted only one minute, starting at $720,000 dollars
and rising in $90,000 increments against one other unidentified
bidder.
   The selling price was $1.8 million but Sotheby's, the auction
house, adds a 10 percent commission to the price.
   The 316-page German-language manuscript was finished in 1920 and
published in 1925, a year after Kafka, a German-speaking
Czechoslovak Jew, died of tuberculosis at age 41.
   The novel has become a symbol of the 20th century alienation,
totalitarianism and choking bureaucracy. The hero, Joseph K., who
has done nothing wrong, is arrested, tried and executed without ever
being informed of his charges.
   Kafka instructed his literary executor, Max Brod, to burn his
works, but Brod ignored the order.
   Kafka only wrote two other novels, ``The Castle,'' and the
unfinished ``Amerika.'' His short story, ``The Metamorphosis,'' is
another modern classic.
   The previous record for a purely literary work was $370,000 paid
in July 1985 for a notebook of poetry and prose by the Irish writer
William Butler Yeats.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881117-0137 </DOCNO>
