<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Avtex     11-17 0380</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Avtex,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Warner Cites Safety Concerns At Avtex Plant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. John Warner, R-Va., said Thursday that
meeting health and safety concerns should be a main component in the
decision on whether to keep open a Virginia plant that makes
``absolutely critical'' components for rocket nozzles.
   ``It is essential to our national security to keep this plant
operating, providing we can meet the health and safety concerns of
the people in the immediate area,'' Warner said after headingg a
meeting between the federal and state agencies concerned with the
Avtex Fiber Inc. plant in Front Royal, Va.
   The closed-door meeting was intended to trade information about
the situation among the various agencies, Warner said.
   NASA and the Pentagon want Avtex to stay in business, because the
plant is the only supplier for a carbonizable rayon fiber which is a
key component of rocket nozzles for the space shuttle and some of
the Air Force's nuclear-tipped weapons.
   But the Environmental Protection Agency and the Virginia attorney
general's office want Avtex to clean up the plant that has a history
of environmental and worker safety problems.
   On Oct. 31, Avtex Chairman John Gregg announced he would close
the Front Royal plant because of environmental regulations and
foreign competition for other textile products made by Avtex. Gregg
stopped production Nov. 3, but recalled the work force one week
later as the government began a bailout of Avtex.
   Last week, NASA gave Avtex $7 million for the rights to the
fiber. The space agency said it will sign an $11 million contract
for the fiber, if Avtex can show by Friday it will generate enough
contracts to keep the plant in business.
   Warner noted that only three or four percent of the Avtex's
production involves the nozzle materials.
   But he said ``it would require as much as two years'' to develop
another source for this material. In the meantime, U.S. national
security could be harmed if missiles couldn't be launched, he said.
One example he gave was the use of Air Force missiles to launch
reconnaissance satellites.
   One major concern, Warner said, is to make sure that any federal
bailout money is not used to pay off any fines which could be levied
against Avtex.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
