<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Bush-Thatcher 2ndLd-Writethru a0540 11-17 0767</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush-Thatcher, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0540,750</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 9 grafs new with Thatcher news conference, pick up 2nd
graf pvs, Mrs. Thatcher</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher said
today the acceptance by the PLO parliament-in-exile of two key
United Nations resolutions on the Middle East is a ``modest step
forward'' on which progress toward peace could be made.
   At a news conference shortly before ending her two-day visit
here, Mrs. Thatcher offered a slightly more upbeat assessment of the
declaration by the Palestine National Council, the legislative arm
of the Palestine Liberation Organization, than has the Reagan
administration.
   She criticized the PNC for proclaiming the establishment of a
Palestinian state and said the declaration did not go far enough in
repudiating terrorism.
   ``Obviously there are a lot of things in it that none of us
like,'' she said.
   But she said that approval of U.N. resolutions 242 and 338 ``is a
modest step forward and something on which you could build.'' The
resolutions call for Israeli withdrawal from occupied territories
and assert the right of all countries to live within secure borders.
   Mrs. Thatcher added that ``strenuous efforts'' should be made to
get peace negotiations going in the Middle East.
   Mrs. Thatcher reaffirmed her high regard for President-elect
George Bush, citing his extensive experience in government as a
major asset.
   ``You will have a president who doesn't have to be briefed,'' she
said.
   Earlier, she said she had ``not the slightest shadow of a doubt''
that Bush will deal responsibly with the U.S. deficit.
   Mrs. Thatcher repeated similar expressions of confidence in Bush
and the U.S. economy in three network television interviews prior to
meeting with the vice president for breakfast. The meeting followed
an evening of reminiscing at a state dinner with President Reagan,
whom she described as ``a marvelous president.''
   ``I have not the slightest shadow of doubt that in good time the
deficit will be considered in a responsible way,'' Mrs. Thatcher
said in an interview on ``CBS This Morning.''
   ``I don't share concerns about George Bush's ability to deal with
fundamental problems,'' she said on ABC-TV's ``Good Morning
America.'' ``I think he will deal with them in his own time and in
his own way and very responsibly indeed.''
   On NBC-TV's ``Today'' show, Mrs. Thatcher said Bush and his
advisers will need time to come up with policies for dealing with
the deficit. ``I don't think we should hurry them,'' she said.
   When Mrs. Thatcher arrived at the vice president's residence for
her meeting with Bush, he greeted her as ``the star of `Good Morning
America'.''
   The prime minister said in the interviews, all broadcast live
from Blair House, that she and Bush were talking about the world
economy, the Middle East and East-West ties.
   Mrs. Thatcher, who was ending her two-day state visit this
afternoon after a news conference, said Wednesday that the Western
alliance is ``very fortunate'' to have Bush as Reagan's successor.
   ``For the first time we will have continuity of policies,
stretching over a second presidency. And that brings enormous
stability and confidence to the feeling of the world,'' she told
reporters as she sat next to Reagan during an Oval Office photo
session.
   Mrs. Thatcher also has said of Bush, ``We know him as a friend,
we admire him as a man of unrivaled experience and we respect him
because he stands for all that is best in America.''
   After a private meeting between Reagan and Mrs. Thatcher, Bush
joined a subsequent meeting attended by top officials of both
governments. Like most others in the room, Bush said little,
deferring to the president and the prime minister, who met in their
respective capacities for the last time.
   Despite signs that Bush and Mrs. Thatcher will be able to work
well together, Bush will have a difficult time matching the
partnership Reagan forged with the British leader.
   The White House arrival ceremony for Mrs. Thatcher on Wednesday
was filled with expressions of mutual admiration.
   ``Together our nations have faced the challenges of our time, and
have not flinched. We forged ahead with strengthening the peace,
spreading prosperity and safeguarding liberty,'' Mrs. Thatcher said.
   Reagan lauded Mrs. Thatcher for her ``extraordinary role in the
revitalization of freedom,'' and said she has contributed to a
``remarkable change'' in her country through policies that encourage
individual creativity.
   Looking beyond his own term of office, Reagan added, ``It is
profoundly reassuring to me and to all who care about freedom that
you will continue to share with America your vision and your steady
hand.''
</TEXT>
