<HEAD>U.S. Officials Say Two Afghan Diplomats Have Defected</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with background, no Afghan spox
available. No pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two diplomats who accompanied Afghanistan's
prime minister on his mission to the United Nations last week have
defected, U.S. officials said today.
   An official at the U.S. Mission to the United Nations said the
State Department confirmed two Afghan diplomats did not return to
the Afghan capital of Kabul, but would not say more about their
whereabouts. He spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Other U.S. officials, also speaking on condition of anonymity,
confirmed both diplomats had defected to the United States.
   No spokesmen were available at Afghanistan's Mission to the
United Nations. A receptionist said they were out of the office.
   Sources at the United Nations said the defectors were a deputy
foreign minister named Lanikwal, and a diplomat named Kamal.
   Afghan Prime Minister Mohammad Hassan Sharq was in New York last
week for talks with Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar and
other officials.
   In April, Pakistan and Afghanistan signed a U.N.-mediated accord
in Geneva, with the United States and Soviet Union signing as
guarantors.
   Under the accord, the Soviet army began withdrawing from
Afghanistan on May 15, with half of their about 100,000 troops out
in August.
   The Soviet Foreign Ministry said early this month that it has
``suspended'' the withdrawal because of attacks by U.S.- and
Pakistan-backed guerrillas, who have rejected the pact.
   Soviet troops intervened in Afghanistan in 1979.
