<2ND_LINE>AM-People,0899</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Folk singer Arlo Guthrie said he intends
to release what he calls a new and improved version of ``Alice's
Restaurant'' as soon as he finds ideal recording conditions.
   ``It's just a matter of getting the right recording of the right
timing of the right audience on the right night,'' Guthrie said.
   The anti-war ballad of the Vietnam era tells of the 41-year-old
songwriter's Thanksgiving Day arrest for littering.
   The song has been updated with Guthrie's comments on historical
events since the 1965 arrest that kept him out of the draft because
of his conviction on the littering charge, said Sharon Palma,
manager of Guthrie's label Rising Son Records.
   ``The funniest is that he hints at the coincidence that the only
things that are 18 minutes and 20 seconds long are the song and the
erased Nixon tapes,'' Palma said Thursday from the folk singer's
studio in this small Bershires Hills town.
   The song should be re-recorded soon, ``but with him you can never
tell,'' Palma said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Doug Marlette, Pulitzer Prize-winning
editorial cartoonist and creator of the comic strip ``Kudzu,'' says
he doesn't set out to include politics in the strip.
   ``But I like looking at the bigger issues confronting our
society,'' he said Wednesday at a book-signing to promote his book,
``I Am Not a Televangelist!''
   ``I'm less interested in the daily ebb and flow than in the life
and death issues, and that may shade over into the political,'' said
Marlette, editorial cartoonist for the Atlanta Constitution.
   In ``Kudzu,'' the bumbling Rev. Will B. Dunn just ran for
president. Marlette said other ``Kudzu'' characters will appear more
frequently now that the campaign is over.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Radio and TV personality Gary Owens, who went
into diabetic shock while behind the wheel of his car and struck
another vehicle, is being sued by two Canadians injured in the crash.
   The Superior Court suit filed Monday seeks $50,000 in damages.
   Owens collided with a vehicle Sept. 16 being driven by Norman
Page of Montreal.
   The suit contends Page and his passenger, Kimberly Campbell,
suffered permanent disabilities, said Page's attorney, William
Rehwald.
   Page suffered a broken leg and Ms. Campbell suffered a broken
shoulder, Rehwald said.
   Owens is probably best-known to national TV audiences as the
``Laugh-In'' announcer who cupped his hand to his ear and put
``beautiful downtown Burbank'' on the map.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lawyer representing American actress Koo Stark, a
former girlfriend of Prince Andrew, said Thursday she plans to
proceed with a libel case against London's Daily Mirror.
   It will be the second legal action taken by Miss Stark, 32,
against publisher Robert Maxwell's newspapers.
   Earlier this month, Miss Stark was awarded $549,000 libel damages
in the High Court from the Sunday People newspaper over a story that
she had an affair with the prince after her marriage.
   ``So far as we are aware, an action will take place in the High
Court on Monday,'' said Miss Stark's lawyer, Keith Schilling.
   Miss Stark said the allegations about a continuing relationship
with the prince were published in December 1985 when she was having
marital problems, and dashed her hopes of reconciling with her
husband, Timothy Jeffries.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A $765,000 lawsuit against rock singer
Billy Idol has been settled out of court for an undisclosed sum.
   Five people filed the circuit court lawsuit following a May 13,
1987, rock concert at Portland Memorial Coliseum during which fans
rushed the stage after Idol said, ``I feel lonely up here.''
   The remark prompted a disturbance as fans rushed a barricade and
knocked a number of people to the ground.
   The plaintiffs said they were sitting in seats in front when Idol
made his remark and the crowd behind them surged forward. As a
result, the plaintiffs alleged, they sustained various physical
injuries and emotional distress.
   The settlement involves all but one plaintiff, whose separate
lawsuit remains pending, said Elizabeth Sampson, a Portland lawyer
who represented Idol and a production company.
   ``The terms of the settlement are confidental,'' she said. ``The
defendants continue to deny any liability.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joy Hall, a 10-year-old from Baltimore, was named
National Easter Seal Child for 1989 at the society's national
convention Thursday.
   Born with cerebral palsy, Joy lacks motor control in her legs and
arms. But with the help of leg braces, she hasn't allowed the
handicap to limit her activities.
   Joy participates in a gymnastics class geared to building
strength in children with disabilities. She also plays basketball
and bowls, and adds she isn't discouraged even when she throws a
gutter ball.
   ``Even if I do badly, I try,'' she says.
   Joy, a fifth-grader, attends a Baltimore public school. Her
mother, Janet, said her daughter established her independence at an
Easter Seal summer camp.
   As National Easter Seal Child, Joy will represent disabled people
who receive rehabilitation services from the nationwide network of
Easter Seal programs.
   Walter E. Shinault, 28 and a stock broker from Jackson, Miss.,
was named the National Easter Seal adult representative for 1989.
</TEXT>
