<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SriLanka     11-17 0487</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sri Lanka,0504</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bombs, Shootings Kill At Least 17</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assailants hurled bombs at a public
meeting and into a video store Thursday, and police opened fire to
disperse anti-government protesters during ethnic unrest that killed
at least 17 people, officials said.
   One person was killed and 10 were injured when police opened fire
to break up an anti-government demonstration in the north-central
Kurunegala district, a government communique said.
   In Colombo, Sinhalese radicals threw bombs at a meeting being
addressed by Ossie Abeygoonasekara, one of the three candidates for
next month's presidential elections, police said.
   At least 40 people suffered minor injuries in the attack and an
ensuing stampede, said officials, who were not identified in
accordance with briefing rules.
   Military officials said three people were killed and one was
injured when a bomb was thrown at a video center just south of
Colombo.
   They said the video center was attacked because it stayed open
last week when the People's Liberation Front, a militant Sinhalese
group, called for an anti-government strike.
   The victims were shop employees.
   At least 13 people were killed by radical Sinhalese in the south
and center of the island, and three Sinhalese men were shot and
killed by Tamil rebels in the northeast, said police and military
officials.
   The attacks occurred Wednesday and Thursday. Officials said among
the victims were four government supporters, a bus driver, a school
principal, two employees of the Colombo port, a civilian clerk and
his nephew.
   The port employees were involved in compiling lists of employees'
names so police could escort them to work during a strike at the
port last week, sources said.
   The military officials gave no reasons for the other killings,
but the victims were believed to be Sinhalese who defied the strike.
   Sinhalese militants are agitating for the resignation of
President Junius R. Jayewardene, himself a Sinhalese. They are
opposed to an accord Jayewardene signed that is aimed at ending
Tamil rebels' five-year war for autonomy.
   Sinhalese radicals say the accord, signed July 29, 1987, makes
too many concessions to the minority Tamils, who comprise 18 percent
of the 16 million population.
   The main Tamil rebel group, the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam,
has refused to accept the accord, saying it does not go far enough.
   The People's Liberation Front stepped up its anti-government
campaign last week and called for a four-day strike in the south,
which crippled business in the Sinhalese heartland and caused food
and gasoline shortages.
   Jayewardene hit back by ordering troops to open fire at
anti-government demonstrations and decreeing the death penalty for
anyone convicted of instigating strikes.
   Jayewardene is to leave office in January and elections to choose
his successor are scheduled Dec. 19. The Front says he should resign
immediately.
   The group called for a boycott of the elections and has
threatened to kill all the candidates.
</TEXT>
