<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RayParole     11-17 0231</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ray Parole,0237</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>James Earl Ray Wins Parole Hearing In January</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   James Earl Ray, serving 99 years in
prison for the 1968 assassination of civil rights leader Martin
Luther King Jr., has been granted a parole hearing in January.
   Ray, 60, pleaded guilty to shooting King with a high-powered
rifle in Memphis. He said he avoided a trial to escape a possible
death penalty but now wants the case heard by a jury.
   Ray became eligible for parole in November, said Gretchen
Faulstich, executive director of the Parole Board. The hearing was
continued until January pending a routine psychological evaluation
as well as his institutional record, Ms. Faulstich said.
   Ray is held at Brushy Mountain State Prison near Petros, from
which he escaped briefly in June 1977. He was tracked down in wooded
mountains nearby.
   Ray was a fugitive from a Missouri prison at the time King went
to Memphis to lend his support to a strike by sanitation workers
seeking higher pay. He was identified from fingerprints on a rifle,
found near the Lorraine Motel, where King was killed as he stood on
a balcony.
   On the day his trial was to begin, Ray entered a surprise guilty
plea. He began almost immediately to recant, claiming he was
pressured into entering the plea to escape the death penalty.
   He since has continuously proclaimed his innocence.
</TEXT>
