<DOCNO> AP881117-0148 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-88 1458EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Reagan-Arts     11-17 0344</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Arts,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Six-Year Study Concludes Arts Need More Federal Support</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government support of the arts is needed to
supplement private giving, a presidential committee told President
Reagan on Thursday after a six-year study.
   The committee, created by a presidential executive order in 1982,
presented its report to Reagan at a meeting in the Roosevelt Room of
the White House.
   The committee noted that during the 1980s there has been ``a
diminution of tax incentives for charitable giving'' and warned that
``reduced incentives can damage the vitality of American
philanthropy.''
   ``The main vehicle for support of the arts and humanities remains
private monies, a resource that must be encouraged and increased,''
the report said. ``We firmly believe government support is
necessary, however, for it seems clear that the culture of this
country cannot be sustained solely by private funding.''
   The federal government currently provides support for the arts
through the National Foundation on the Arts and the Humanities, and
the Institute of Museum Services, which have combined current
budgets of $330.1 million.
   The report called for the creation of a presidential commission
made up of both leading private citizens and government officials.
   ``There should be sufficient annual appropriations to sustain the
federal government's capacity as grantor; innovative leadership to
inspire its role as catalyst; and continued incentives through the
tax system to encourage private giving,'' the committee said.
   It said private giving to the arts and humanities has grown at a
greater rate than inflation since 1980 but the two major tax
revisions passed during the Reagan administration resulted in
reduced incentives for charitable contributions.
   The 35-member committee was made up of leaders of business,
government and the arts under the chairmanship of Andrew Heiskell,
retired chairman of Time Inc.
   It held meetings throughout the United States and made a
recommendation in 1984 that led to establishment of the National
Medal of Arts, presented annually by the president.
   Executive director Diane J. Paton said the committee operated on
an annual budget of about $300,000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
