<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-88 1501EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Bishops     11-17 0629</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bishops,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Catholic Bishops Decry Religious Persecution in Soviet Bloc</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT FURLOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's Roman Catholic bishops said
Thursday the U.S. government could help fight ``sustained and
comprehensive'' religious persecution in the Soviet bloc by linking
that issue to others the Soviets care about.
   In a lengthy document, the bishops detailed what they saw as
religious intolerance and discrimination in the nations of Eastern
Europe, but they also suggested the time may be right to win
improvement.
   They said Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev's stated policies of
openness and restructuring ``offer potentially significant changes
in thought and practice and deserve to be taken seriously and
encouraged ... as a potential basis for gradual expansion of
freedoms.''
   The U.S. government ``should consider the possibility of using
affirmative measures to influence human rights policies and
practices, including developing closer relations, extending credits
and encouraging cultural and educational exchanges and tourism,''
the bishops said.
   ``In all such initiatives U.S. diplomacy should make it clear
that continued improvement in relations will depend in part on
continued improvement with regard to religious liberty and human
rights.''
   The statement was approved on the last day of the annual meeting
of the National Conference of Catholic Bishops.
   Earlier Thursday, on a matter closer to home, the church leaders
called for changes in a 1986 federal law covering legalization of
illegal aliens, many of whom are Catholic Hispanics.
   They said more Hispanics should be allowed to stay in this
country legally, and they complained in particular that the law's
provisions on penalties for employers who hire undocumented workers
are poorly understood and lead to discrimination against Hispanic
workers in general.
   The two new statements backed up the declaration earlier this
week by the conference's president, Archbishop John L. May of St.
Louis, that the bishops would continue to speak out on controversial
public issues despite criticism.
   The bishops, leaders of the nation's largest religious
denomination with more than 53 million members, spent much of the
week concentrating on an intra-church dispute with the Vatican. They
rejected a Rome-prepared draft document that questioned the
authority of their conference and others like it.
   However, May continued to play down talk of any major
confrontation.
   ``I don't look on these discussions as a tug-of-war or an ongoing
fight or crisis or any of these words that are used,'' he said at a
news conference after the meeting ended Wednesday.
   ``We are in a most serene time,'' May said, adding that Pope John
Paul II had spoken favorably of the U.S. church during American
bishops' visits to Rome this year.
   The bishops appeared solidly united in loud voice votes favoring
the new statements on religion in Eastern Europe and on treatment of
Hispanic immigrants in the United States.
   Archbishop Roger Mahony of Los Angeles said the bishops were
challenging Soviet leaders, whose policies have heavy influence
throughout Eastern Europe, ``to match their recent talk of reform
with concrete action.''
   Despite improvements in some countries, the church leaders said
in their statement, ``The scale of persecution has been and remains
sustained and comprehensive, and its roster of victims all
inclusive: Catholics, Protestants, Orthodox, Jews, Muslims,
Jehovah's Witnesses and many others.''
   Although church attendance is sometimes allowed, religiously
active people are often subject to discrimination in other areas,
the bishops said.
   Concerning Hispanics, the church leaders said many employers
don't understand the immigration law's provisions and thus fire or
refuse to hire many eligible Hispanics out of fear of being raided
and fined by the government.
   The bishops called for action on three fronts: compiling detailed
records of discrimination to force Congress to change the law,
promoting legislation to provide legalization opportunities to more
recent immigrants and educating employers on provisions of the
current law.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881117-0151 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-88 1513EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Beaujolais     11-17 0690</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Beaujolais,0711</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Good Cheer Flows at Arrival of New Beaujolais</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SYDNEY RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corner bistros overflowed with bon vivants and
parties sprouted in the most unlikely places as Parisians celebrated
the arrival of the new Beaujolais, joining other wine lovers
worldwide.
   Commuters rushing through the Gare de Lyon railway station at 7
a.m. were offered a Beaujolais breakfast, poured from a special
high-speed train that carried cases of the wine to the capital. A
huge crowd of happy commuters gathered around the railway car
flowing with Beaujolais ``primeur,'' the first wine produced from
the autumn harvest.
   Jean-Pierre Benoit, a grower pouring wine at the train, took a
few sips of the juicy Beaujolais nouveau himself before moving on to
the next official party, scheduled for 11 a.m.
   ``Wine drinking is a habit with people in Beaujolais,'' he said.
``I can go to 10 wine tastings and never get drunk ... at least I
hope so.''
   Benoit hurried from the station to a sound stage at Pathe Cinema
in Montmartre where a reconstructed Beaujolais village served as the
setting for an elaborate tasting attended by about 500 journalists
and friends of the Beaujolais wine growers association.
   ``This wine is completely different from last year's, much more
of a Gamay taste,'' said Michel Deflache, who produces wine on land
owned by his family since 1550 and also serves as spokesman for the
Beaujolais wine growers' association.
   Deflache poured glasses of wine under a plastic cherry tree on
the town's quaint main street, across from an old-fashioned pharmacy.
   ``This year's Beaujolais is generous in the mouth, more
full-bodied. It is a more masculine wine,'' Deflache said.
   Across town at Le Val d'Or wine bar off the Champs Elysees, owner
Geraud Rongier was quickly emptying two 220-liter barrels. ``This
year, it's good, very light, very perfumed,'' Rongier said.
   Le Figaro newspaper described this year's batch as ``more
nuanced, more subtle, more traditional than last year's'' which was
said to have an aftertaste of bananas.
   Wine growers say the 1988 vintage has had the advantage of being
one of the earliest harvests in a long while. The harvest Sept. 10,
compared with Sept. 22 last year, gave producers a longer time to
make the wine which is meant to be consumed quickly, but benefits
from a few weeks in the bottle.
   Not all Frenchmen are seduced by the hype and extravagant
tastings, and remind the unwary foreigner that the new Beaujolais
once was regarded as cheap table wine.
   ``I never drank the stuff before all this started and I still
don't,'' growled one seasoned customer in a bar Thursday morning.
   Two decades of clever marketing have paid off and more than half
of this year's estimated 50 million bottles of new Beaujolais will
be exported.
   Since Monday, jets, trucks and trains have been delivering the
wine to far-flung bon vivants, some of whom beat Parisians to the
first sip.
   Australians claimed they were the first, popping corks on the
simple, fruity wine 11 hours ahead of the French because of the
difference in time zones.
   Japanese wine lovers held parties at restaurants about 8 hours
before the French. Officials at Suntory Ltd., a major Japanese
distiller and importer, said overall Japanese imports will total
153,000 cases, an increase of 70 percent over last year.
   The wine, which sells for about $3.30 a bottle here, will cost
the equivalent of $42 a bottle in Tokyo restaurants, according to
wine officials in Beaujolais.
   Although Japan is the fastest growing market for the new wine,
which accounts for 55 percent of the total Beaujolais crop, it is
not the biggest market. West Germany, Britain and Switzerland
combined drink 60 percent of the exported Beaujolais nouveau.
   The U.S. market represents about 10 percent of the new Beaujolais
sales and celebrations were planned for Thursday in New York, San
Francisco, Los Angeles, Dallas, Atlanta and Pittsburgh.
   About 500 people were expected at a Beaujolais soiree sponsored
by the French Embassy in San Salvador, Deflache said.
   ``There are always new markets for this uncomplicated wine,'' he
said. ``And everyone likes an occasion to party.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
