<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     11-17 0597</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0615</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STANFORD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's bearly believeable, but a 7-foot
stuffed grizzly swiped more than two years ago from its place of
honor at the University of California has written to say he may be
coming home.
   Stanford University's News and Publications office says it
received a letter Wednesday from the behemoth, which vanished Aug.
3, 1986, from his home in a display case on the Berkeley campus. No
charges were filed, but most folks at Berkeley believe the abduction
was master-minded by students at rival Stanford.
   The two schools meet Saturday for a football game that in the San
Francisco Bay area is called ``The Big Game.''
   In the letter, the missing bear said he had visited Disneyland,
Reno, Nev., and gone to the Olympics in Seoul. He also expressed
concern about Berkeley's decline in a U.S. News and World Report
survey of top-rated universities. The campus dropped from No. 7 to
No. 24 in the rankings.
   ``If I stay away any longer,'' the note said, ``it may become a
junior college.''
   The bear also appeared a bit miffed that his pals at Berkeley had
failed to follow up on a ransom note. ``It seems like everybody's
forgotten I've been on vacation with my friends at Stanford,'' he
groused.
   Yet the beast appeared ready to let bygones be bygones.
   ``I've had a great time on the farm (a nickname for the Stanford
campus),'' the letter read. ``But I think it's about time to go
back.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 12-year-old lowland gorilla who made a
hit in her last home with unexpected trips outside her cage is on
loan in Columbus to become a mate and stepmother.
   Molly has been introduced to what Columbus Zoo officials hope
will be her new mate, Bongo, and Bongo's son, Fossey.
   Bongo has been raising Fossey for over a year since the young
gorilla's mother, Bridgette, died from peritonitis. Molly was
airlifted Oct. 4 from the Kansas City, Mo., Zoo to take over
mothering Fossey and perhaps _ in concert with Bongo _ raise a few
Fosseys of her own.
   The loan is part of a national endangered-species breeding
program. If Molly becomes a mother, the Kansas City Zoo gets her
first female child. Columbus gets her first son, and the zoos will
alternate taking later offspring.
   This is Molly's first trip away from Kansas City, but not her
first adventure. She gained notoriety for unscheduled jaunts outside
her cage at the Kansas City Zoo's Great Ape House.
   On her first trip out, Molly propped a stick against a wall and
used it to climb out. For her second outing, she climbed atop the
ape house roof and jumped onto a walkway, Kansas City Zoo
spokeswoman Jori Glazer said recently.
   Her keeper at Kansas City, Karen Kline, said Molly was a pleasure
to know.
   ``Molly knows a few sign words _ she can say she's hungry, can
say `I see you,' show people her teeth, can comb her hair,'' Ms.
Kline said. ``We didn't keep up with her teaching _ we wanted her to
relate to gorillas instead of people _ but she retained the
knowledge.''
   The gorilla's socialization is coming along just fine, said
Charlene Jendry, Molly's Columbus keeper.
   ``By day 10, she was having long playing sessions with Fossey,''
she said. ``She's now allowing him to reach through the mesh
(separating their cages) and take her food. The other day, Fossey
took one of the two halves of orange Molly gets in the afternoons,
and Molly didn't do a thing.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
