<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-88 1519EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PershingBurn     11-17 0333</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pershing Burn,0341</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Army To Begin Destroying Pershing Rocket Motors Dec. 5</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PUEBLO, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Burning of more than 450 Pershing 2 rocket
motors as part of the Treaty on Intermediate-Range Nuclear Forces
will begin Dec. 5 at the Pueblo Army Depot Activity, the Army
announced Thursday.
   Similar motor burns have been going on at the Longhorn Army
Ammunition Plant near Marshall, Texas, since Sept. 8.
   Army spokesmen said the Pueblo burns would be witnessed by a team
from the Soviet Union, as called for in the treaty.
   The rocket motors will be static fired, restrained by a concrete
and steel structure. The burned-out motor cases then will be crushed
and buried at the depot, 16 miles east of Pueblo.
   The Colorado Department of Health gave permission Nov. 1 for the
Army to burn the motors. The permit requires emissions monitoring,
governs the frequency of burns and limits them to be fired only when
winds from the west are 4 mph or greater and only during daylight.
   Only one missile can be fired per hour and no more than six per
day. Emissions of any pollutant may not exceed 250 tons per year.
   The depot is scheduled to destroy 234 Pershing 2 Stage I motors,
each containing 7,940 pounds of propellant, and 233 Pershing 2 Stage
2 motors, each containing 4,940 pounds of propellant, state
authorities said.
   The rest of the Army's stockpile of 849 Pershing 2 missiles are
being destroyed at the Texas site, Army spokesmen said.
   The burn-date announcement caps an 11-month process that included
a test firing of one rocket motor last May at the depot. Public
meetings and hearings and analysis of environmental effects also
were part of the process.
   At the time the permit was issued, Gov. Roy Romer said he had
wanted Colorado to help destroy the motors ``so that this country
could fulfill its treaty obligations. However, I wanted it to be
done safely and we have worked that out with the U.S. Army.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
