<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BRF--EraseIlliteracy     11-17 0186</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Erase Illiteracy,180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Billboards To Promote Literacy Campaign</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some 10,000 billboards proclaiming ``Erase
Illiteracy'' will appear along U.S. roads this year in a drive
launched Thursday by two government agencies and the nation's
printing and outdoor advertising industries.
   The billboards are painted to look like blackboards. The words
``Erase Illiteracy'' are printed in yellow on top of a book and the
word ``Read.''
   Education Secretary Lauro Cavazos said there are 27 million
functional illiterates in America and another 40 million to 50
million people who can't read above a 4th grade level.
   He called the billboard initiative ``a perfect example'' of the
type of public-private cooperation needed to reverse the trend
toward illiteracy. He said the number of illiterate adults is rising
by more than 1 million a year.
   ``Public awareness is a terribly important piece of licking the
problem,'' said Thelma Reese, head of Philadelphia's literacy
commission. ``It really does lessen the shame of coming forward.''
   Sponsors of the billboard effort are the Education Department,
the Government Printing Office, the Outdoor Advertising Association
of America and Printing Industries of America Inc.
</TEXT>
