<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-88 1546EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ExploitedChildren     11-17 0315</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Exploited Children,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Children's Groups Launch Personal Safety Program for Youngsters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two children's safety groups announced a
program Thursday to teach youngsters how to protect themselves
against abuse, exploitation and abduction without unduly alarming
them.
   The program, known as ``Kids and Company: Together for Safety,''
teaches youngsters about personal safety ``in a very upbeat way''
that bolsters their self-esteem, said John Walsh, whose 6-year-old
son, Adam, was abducted from a Florida shopping mall and killed in
1981.
   Walsh, who founded the Adam Walsh Child Resource Center and
serves on the board of the National Center for Missing and Exploited
Children, said the program teaches grade school-age youngsters how
to protect themselves without frightening them. The two centers
worked together to develop the program.
   It teaches youngsters to ``use your brain, train your body, trust
your feelings and remember your friends'' in uncomfortable
situations. The teaching materials include teachers' guides, a
teacher training video, an in-class video, student activity sheets
and a materials for parents.
   Walsh said that following his son's death, he and his wife, Reve,
wondered ``if we had told Adam appropriate things'' about how to
protect himself.
   ``We agonized on many occasions and said, `Maybe we shouldn't
have made him, or tried to make him, so polite, so much of a little
gentleman,''' Walsh said. ``Maybe he'd be here today if he had
better tools, if he knew he could have said no, or he could have
yelled, or run.''
   ``Our children have the right to have the skills and confidence
they need to play an active role in their personal safety,'' Walsh
said. ``Children have the right to know that they can say no.''
   The program is to be launched initially in school districts in
Rochester, N.Y.; Marlboro, Mass.; Fort Lauderdale, Fla.; Nashua,
N.H.; and Orange County, Calif.
   Digital Equipment Corp. contributed more than $300,000 toward its
development.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
