<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hirohito     11-17 0209</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hirohito,0217</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Illness Takes Toll On Japanese Emperor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emperor Hirohito, bedridden for nearly two months
since he fell seriously ill, is becoming weaker and more anemic,
palace officials said Thursday.
   Hirohito's voice ``is so feeble these days his doctors and nurses
wouldn't hear him very well,'' said Kenji Maeda, spokesman for the
Imperial Household Agency.
   The 87-year-old monarch vomited blood Sept. 19 and has since
suffered from bleeding near his upper intestine, where doctors
performed a bypass operation last year.
   He has received 42 pints of blood in transfusions and gets about
600 calories intravenously each day.
   Although doctors have found no signs of internal bleeding during
the past week, the emperor is becoming anemic and weaker, Maeda told
reporters.
   ``More often there are moments when the doctors can't tell if the
emperor is awake or asleep,'' he said.
   There were no immediate plans for further blood transfusions, he
said, adding that doctors were concentrating on maintaining, rather
than improving, the emperor's condition.
   By late afternoon, Hirohito had a temperature of 99.9 degrees.
The emperor's normal temperature is about 95.9 degrees.
   Palace officials have not given details on Hirohito's illness,
and they would not comment on Japanese news reports that the emperor
has pancreatic cancer.
</TEXT>
