<DOCNO> AP881117-0165 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-88 1524EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Pakistan Bjt   11-17 0719</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pakistan, Bjt,0739</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bhutto Wins, Says She Can Form Majority Coalition</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY9</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KARACHI, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Benazir Bhutto's populist party defeated
the right wing in the first free election since a coup ousted her
father 11 years ago, and she expressed confidence Thursday that she
can form a majority coalition.
   Ms. Bhutto said her Pakistan People's Party ``has emerged as the
largest single party'' in the National Assembly as a result of
Wednesday's parliamentary election.
   ``Given consultations with different groups and independent
people, we are confident that we can get a simple majority,'' the
35-year-old political leader declared after arriving in this
southern city for coalition talks. She would be the first woman to
lead a Moslem nation.
   Her party captured 92 seats in the 237-member assembly, compared
with 55 for the nine-party conservative Islamic Democratic Alliance.
The alliance includes supporters of Gen. Mohammed Zia ul-Haq, the
military president killed in a plane crash three months ago.
   Independents and minor parties got 57 seats. Results from 13
districts were not available and 20 seats reserved for women will be
filled later by vote of the assembly.
   The last free National Assembly election in 1977 was a landslide
for Prime Minister Zulfikar Ali Bhutto, who founded the Pakistan
People's Party, and Gen. Zia overthrew him soon afterward. Bhutto
was convicted of complicity in a political murder plot and hanged in
1979.
   In Washington, the State Department praised Pakistan, a U.S.
ally, for the elections. Spokesman Charles Redman said: ``We
congratulate the Pakistani people and their leaders for this
impressive and important step in strengthening democracy in
Pakistan.''
   At her family home in Larkana earlier Thursday, Ms. Bhutto urged
President Ghulam Ishaq Khan to give her party the mandate to form a
government.
   She said she wouild begin coalition talks Friday, but would not
name parties on the list. Likely candidates are some of her
left-leaning partners in the former opposition alliance called the
Movement for the Restoration of Democracy.
   Ms. Bhutto also is expected to consult a relatively new party of
Moslem immigrants from India called the MQM, which carried the
southern cities Karachi and Hyderabad.
   Her personal popularity was demonstrated by the fact that she ran
for three National Assembly seats and won them all. Two will have to
be filled through by-elections.
   The constitution requires the president to designate a person to
form a government who will be ``most likely to command the
confidence of the majority of the National Assembly,'' which usually
would mean the leader of the largest party.
   Ishaq Khan was asked Wednesday whether he would be reluctant to
choose a woman in this male-dominated society, and he replied: ``I
think a woman prime minister might be a good change.''
   Pakistan's official news agency said the president sent
congratulatory telegrams to election winners but it did not mention
deliberations on the choice of a prime minister.
   Before Ms. Bhutto left for Karachi, about 5,000 supporters
gathered outside the family villa in Karkana, dancing jubilantly and
chanting: ``Benazir, prime minister!''
   No major election-related violence or fraud was reported by
officials through Thursday but reports of three violent deaths
appeared in newspapers.
   Thousands policemen and soldiers patrolled Sind, a southern
province noted for ethnic violence, on election day.
   Both Ms. Bhutto and the conservative alliance have said they
would continue Pakistan's friendship with the United States and its
support of Moslem guerrillas fighting the communist government of
neighboring Afghanistan.
   Although Ms. Bhutto also said she would pursue Zia's program of
increasing the influence of Islam in the nation's life, she pledged
not to let the religious policy interfere with the rights women and
minorities.
   Mrs. Bhutto attended both Harvard and Oxford and is considered
Westernized. She lived in Europe for several years while Zia was in
power.
   Zia ruled by martial law for eight years after the coup, then
held national elections 1985 in which political parties were not
permitted to enter candidates. Mrs. Bhutto's party and others in the
opposition boycotted the elections.
   The general dismissed the government and National Assembly in May
on grounds of corruption, incompetence and delay in putting Pakistan
under Islamic law. Zia called Wednesday's election before the plane
crash Aug. 17 in which he, the U.S. ambassador and 28 other people
were killed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
