<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Gorbachev     11-17 0199</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gorbachev,0205</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Leaves For India</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev left Thursday for
India where he is expected to hold several meetings with Prime
Minister Rajiv Gandhi during a three-day visit, Tass said.
   The official Soviet news agency ran a one-paragraph annoucement
of his departure for New Delhi, and later said that Gorbachev had
arrived in Tashkent, the capital of the Uzbek Soviet republic.
   It did not say what Gorbachev's schedule would be in Tashkent,
but Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov said such a stop
was normal in the long trip from Moscow to New Delhi. The meetings
in New Dehli will begin Friday.
   The trip will be Gorbachev's second visit to India since assuming
leadership in 1985.
   Gorbachev and Gandhi are expected to focus on expanding trade,
sharing technology and changing relations between the United States
and the Soviet Union. An agreement to increase the value of
Soviet-Indian trade to $4.7 billion in 1989 was signed Wednesday, up
from an estimated $1.9 billion last year.
   Other agreements to be signed involve cooperation in the areas of
the economy, culture and energy.
   Next month, Gorbachev will travel to the United States, Cuba and
Britain.
