<DOCNO> AP881117-0169 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-88 1648EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Japan-US-Rice     11-17 0476</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-US-Rice,0489</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Rice Official Assails `Evil Empire'' of Japanese Agriculture</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan's refusal to import U.S. rice is the work of
an ``evil empire'' of cooperatives manipulating its agricultural
scene, the head of the U.S. Rice Millers' Association said Thursday.
   ``(It) is a fantastic example of economic distortion and it
basically stinks,'' said Stephen Gabbert, president of the group of
rice producers in six U.S. states.
   He said Japan could start to ease much of what he sees as its
social problems by liberaling its strictly controlled rice market.
   In October, the U.S. government rejected a petition by the Rice
Millers' Association complaining about Japan's ban on rice imports.
But it noted Japan's policy contravened trade agreements.
   Gabbert reserved his sharpest attack for the network of
agricultural cooperatives that are powerful political lobbyists with
huge economic resources.
   Japan's rice policy, Gabbert said, ``is tied to a cooperative
framework which I would characterize as basically an evil empire.''
   The cooperative movement is supposed to help Japanese farmers and
consumers, but ``it exploits farmers and gouges consumers,'' he
claimed.
   He said the cooperatives had mounted an expensive lobbying effort
in the United States against U.S. rice exports, resulting in what he
saw as some ``jaw-droppers'' in American news reports and editorials
saying Washington should not press Japan to open its sacrosanct rice
market.
   After laborious negotiations earlier this year, Japan agreed to
accept more U.S. beef and oranges, but firmly rejected calls to open
its rice market. Rice is Japan's staple food and the government
policy is to keep self-sufficiency in rice, though it requires
massive subsidies to farmers and retail prices more than triple
those in the United States.
   ``We shouldn't have any sacred or cultural cows in trade
relationships,'' Gabbert said. ``These kinds of sensitivities should
not be reasons for avoiding confronting trade issues.''
   Rice in Japan costs $3.85 for 2.2 pounds, compared with $1 in the
United States.
   Japan's 122 million people consume about 10.3 million tons of
rice a year. The government subsidy last year, including some
payments to keep paddy fields idle, was $3.6 billion.
   Gabbert proposed a gradual opening of 2.5 percent a year of
Japan's rice market over a four-year period. Ten percent of Japan's
rice market would be as much as American growers could produce, he
said.
   Gabbert said he was aiming for $300 million worth of the Japanese
rice market. He said American farmers can deliver milled rice at 400
dollars a ton versus $2,500 a ton in Japan.
   If Japan liberalizes its market, he predicted that Japanese
farmers would become more efficient, that land and housing prices
would go down because some paddy land would be freed for housing,
and that Japanese consumers could spend less on agricultural
products and more on manufactured imports, thus further helping the
country reduce its huge trade surplus.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
