<HEAD>Mafia Figure Convicted of Fraud</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALERMO, Sicily (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man convicted last year of leading the
Sicilian Mafia was found guilty Thursday of corruption and trying to
defraud the European Economic Community, the Italian news agency
ANSA reported.
   Convicted along with Michele Greco were his brother, Salvatore,
and four other men.
   Greco already is serving a life term for leading the Mafia's
executive commission, which ordered the 1982 execution of Gen. Carlo
Alberto Dalla Chiesa, chief of the government's fight against the
Mafia.
   The Greco brothers were partners with two other men, Giovanni di
Pace and Michelangelo Aiello, in a fruit company based in southern
Sicily, ANSA said.
   The men were convicted of falsifying figures submitted to the EEC
on the amount of fruit they destroyed instead of sending it to
market, in order to earn EEC agricultural subsidies, ANSA said.
   The four also were convicted of bribing two employees of Italy's
Institute of Foreign Trade to hide the fraud, ANSA said.
