<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BuriedBodies-Tipster     11-17 0662</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Buried Bodies-Tipster,0684</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Murder Suspect A Friendly, Gray-Haired Widow To Police Tipster</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Buried Bodies Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL FLEEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man whose tip led to the arrest of a woman
suspected in the deaths of seven boardinghouse residents says he's
not really glad to have put someone in jail but feels ``like I'm a
good citizen.''
   Charles Willgues says he was befriended by the pleasant,
gray-haired woman whom he met in a bar, but he became suspicious
because of her interest in his disability checks and her suggestion
that they live together.
   Dorothea Montalvo Puente was arrested late Wednesday and was
being held by police in Sacramento for investigation of murdering
seven tenants found buried in shallow graves outside the Victorian
boardinghouse she ran there.
   Police believe Puente killed the tenants for their Social
Security checks.
   It was Willgues, 67, who lives alone in a downtown apartment here
and draws Social Security and other disability checks, who tipped a
CBS editor and then police Wednesday to Puente's whereabouts in a
motel near a bar where they had met earlier in the day.
   He didn't immediately recognize her when he talked with her in
the bar, but he realized later that he had seen her face from a
morning newscast on CBS.
   ``I'm not really happy about putting somebody in jail,'' Willgues
said in a telephone interview. ``I am happy in a way, though. I
believe in justice. I feel like I'm a good citizen.''
   He said Puente seemed pleasant when they met at the bar, an
out-of-towner in need of a friend. She told Willgues she was from
San Francisco and was looking for a place to repair her shoes.
   ``I took her shoes across the street to a shoe repair place. And
that's how the whole thing got started,'' Willgues said.
   She told him she was an only child, that her husband died a month
ago, and that the cab driver who took her to her motel stole her
luggage, Willgues said.
   ``She seemed nice and sincere,'' he said.
   But he said she had a strange interest in his disability checks.
And after only one meeting she started talking about living together.
   ``I didn't exactly agree to that. I said we should talk about it
tomorrow. We were going to go shopping,'' he said.
   When he got home, the woman's face wouldn't leave him. ``I said
to myself that I know this woman. I've seen her before,'' he said.
   Then he remembered and called the local CBS bureau, and with the
help of assignment editor Gene Silver, Willgues found out who his
mystery woman was.
   ``I wasn't just going for the scoop,'' Silver said later. ``This
woman could have been trying to prey on him. He was disabled and
drawing a pension. It became more than just a story. It became a
concern for somebody's life.''
   Silver went to Willgues' apartment and the two of them looked at
a newspaper photo of the woman and watched a newscast of the story
about the buried bodies. They decided to call police, said Silver.
   Another elderly man who knew Puentes said Wednesday that he may
have unwittingly helped dig the graves in the boardinghouse lawn.
   ``I was just doing favors for Dorothea. She was always asking us
to do things for her,'' said Homer Myers, 74. He said she told him
the holes were for a tree or for garbage.
   Myers said he lived at Montalvo's boardinghouse for two years,
but moved out last week after refusing to sign over his checks to
her.
   ``I feel real lucky just to be here talking,'' he said. ``I guess
I could have ended up in one of those holes I dug.''
   Myers said boardinghouse tenants seldom exchanged more than a few
words and assembled together only for meals twice a day. Sometimes
boarders disappeared, ``but folks were always coming and going,'' he
said. ``Nothing unusual about that.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
