<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Iraq, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0683,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Ejects Iraqi Diplomat in Retaliation for Ouster in Baghdad</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 4th graf pvs, bgng: `The ousted,' with 2 grafs to UPDATE
with U.S. source saying Rankin's trip was approved. Picks up 5th
graf pvs, `The State</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department on Thursday announced the
expulsion of an Iraqi diplomat in retaliation for the
``unjustified'' ouster of an American diplomat in Baghdad.
   But spokesman Charles E. Redman stressed the United States wanted
to improve relations with the Arab country. ``There are mutual
interests,'' he said.
   U.S. relations with Iraq were restored by President Reagan in
1984 after a 17-year break. Some analysts detected a trend toward
moderation in the ruling Baath party.
   The ousted American was identified Thursday in Baghdad as Heywood
Rankin, head of the U.S. Embassy's political section who has since
left the country. Diplomats in the Iraqi capital said he had made an
unauthorized trip to the north, home of Iraq's estimated 3.5 million
Kurds.
   But a U.S. official here, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
said the trip had been approved by the Iraqis.
   The State Department earlier this year criticized Iraq's
treatment of the non-Arab minority and accused Iraq of using
chemical weapons against Iran in the Persian Gulf war.
   Without identifying Rankin, Redman said ``none of his activities
have been incompatible in any way with his diplomatic status.'' He
declined to say whether the American had met with the Kurds.
   However, Redman said he did not know of any restrictions on U.S.
contacts. The spokesman called the expulsion ``a serious matter''
and said in retaliation Assistant Secretary of State Richard W.
Murphy had informed the Iraqi ambassador, Abdul-Amir Al-Anbari, that
an Iraqi diplomat assigned to the embassy in Washington had been
declared ``persona non grata.''
   ``This action was taken in response to the unjustified expulsion
of a U.S. diplomat in Baghdad by the Iraqi government,'' the
spokesman said.
   Redman declined to identify the Iraqi or his job. Efforts to
reach the embassy by telephone were unsuccessful.
   About 60,000 Kurds fled across the northern border to Turkey and
thousands of others went into Iran in August, claiming Iraq dropped
chemical bombs on their villages. The State Department said it had
substantiated the accusations.
   Militants among the 20 million Kurds living in a region extending
into Turkey, Iran and Iraq have fought for independence for the past
century.
   Iraq attacked Kurdish settlements on its northwestern border
shortly after accepting an Aug. 20 cease-fire in its eight-year war
with Iran. Kurdish guerrillas received support from Iran during the
war.
   Congress considered imposing economic sanctions against Iraq,
based on State Department reports it was using chemical weapons
against its Kurdish minority. Iraq denied the use, and the
legislation was dropped in the rush to adjourn Congress before the
November U.S. presidential election.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
