<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-88 1615EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-TheChiefofStaff 1stLd-Writethru a0613 11-17 0955</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-The Chief of Staff, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0613,920</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>White House Chief of Staff is Nobody's `Dogsbody'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Revises throughout to update with Bush, Fuller announcements;
earlier version also moved for Thursday PMs as the Washington Today
column</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Attorney General Edwin Meese III heard
that Donald Regan had abruptly resigned as President Reagan's chief
of staff, he put in a quick telephone call to Howard Baker.
   ``Howard, I think you better get over to the White House,'' he
told the former Tennessee senator who was in line to succeed Regan.
``There's no one in charge.''
   The story, told by former Baker aide Jim Cannon, speaks volumes
about the key role played in the modern White House by an official
unheard of a few decades ago.
   Attention is focused on the job again by President-elect George
Bush's announcement Thursday that he is naming outgoing New
Hampshire Gov. John Sununu to the post.
   ``The job of chief of staff requires the ability to lead, to
motivate, to direct an important organization in the best interests
of the country,'' Bush said in making the announcement.
   Sununu said, ``My principal responsibilities will be to make sure
that the new president gets the information and the tools that he
needs to make the policies that dicate the programs that will go
forth from the White House. I am also very aware that once those
policies are made I have a responsibility to try and get them
implemented as effectively as they can.''
   Sununu said the key to how he operates as chief of staff will be
``the way the vice president, once he becomes president, wants the
White House run.''
   In dealing with domestic policy issues, he said, ``I have two
responsibilities. One is to be an honest broker and present the
views on the various sides of the issue, and after I fulfill that,
then I have the opportunity to indicate my recommendations.''
   Sununu will be the second former governor to hold the position.
Baker was a former Senate majority leader. Regan was a former
treasury secretary.
   Yet the post of chief of staff is not even mentioned in the
Constitution, and no president had one until Dwight Eisenhower, the
former Army general, came to the White House growling, ``Do I have
to be my own sergeant major?''
   Most people would think that even without Donald Regan or Howard
Baker, or for that matter John Sununu, there is somebody in charge
at the White House: the president.
   ``Of course, he is in charge,'' said Cannon, who has observed the
process both as an adviser to Baker and as a senior aide to
President Ford.
   However, he added, ``Given the size and complexity of problems in
Washington now, you can't run a good administration without a
first-rate chief of staff.''
   Does this make the staff chief a glorified clerk, or possibly the
second most powerful official in the government? Depends on how you
look at it, but closer to the second than the first.
   ``Constitutionally he is and has to be the president's mere
dogsbody, to borrow a British term,'' presidential scholar Richard
E. Neustadt of Harvard University wrote in a 1986 study of the chief
of staff.
   The Oxford English Dictionary defines ``dogsbody'' as ``a junior
person, especially one to whom a variety of menial tasks is given.''
   Don't kid yourself. The White House chief of staff is nobody's
dogsbody.
   ``The chief of staff is system manager _ the boss of none but the
quarterback of everything,'' former White House aide Bradley H.
Patterson Jr. writes in a new book on the White House staff, ``The
Ring of Power.''
   ``He is anything but a pencil pusher,'' said Cannon.
   If there is a tornado in Oklahoma or a crisis in Afghanistan,
word of it comes to the chief of staff, who is on call at all hours
of the day or night.
   ``A chief of staff's power thus derives from his ability to
schedule the president's time, allocate access to him, and shape his
agenda,'' Samuel L. Popkin of the University of California at San
Diego wrote in the 1986 study.
   After Regan's abrupt resignation, said Cannon, ``it would have
been awkward if something very serious had happened somewhere in the
country or the world, and there was no chief of staff in the White
House.''
   The role of the chief of staff varies, however, from
administration to administration.
   Presidents Kennedy and Johnson chose not to have such
functionaries, although other aides filled much the same role. Nixon
returned to having a chief of staff and Ford followed suit. Carter
first favored a ``spokes of the wheel'' approach, in which various
assistants reported directly to him, but abandoned it and made
Hamilton Jordan chief of staff.
   Discussing Bush's staff chief, Cannon said, ``I think probably he
will have less power relatively than the present chief of staff
because Ronald Reagan's style was to turn over more decisions to the
chief of staff. ... My feeling is that Bush will have more decisions
in his own hands and less in the hands of the chief of staff.''
   And what of Craig Fuller, the former White House aide who headed
Bush's staff through most of his second term as vice president?
   He was in the running for White House chief of staff, but was
passed over and reportedly was being considered for a Cabinet post
instead.
   He declined the consolation prize before it was offered,
announcing Thursday that he would have been happy to be chief of
staff but now plans to return to private life.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>EDITOR'S NOTE _ W. Dale Nelson covers the White House for The</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Associated Press.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881117-0181 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-88 1904EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CollapsedTelescope     11-17 0528</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Collapsed Telescope,0543</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Telescope Collapse Will Hurt Research Efforts, Experts Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAIGE St. JOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GREEN BANK, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The collapse of one of the world's
largest radiotelescopes will hinder astronomy over the long term and
will even hamper an experiment planned for an upcoming space shuttle
mission, experts say.
   The dish-shaped radiotelescope at the National Radio Astronomy
Observatory at Green Bank, which crashed Tuesday night, was as wide
as a football field is long but built on a shoestring budget 26
years ago. It was capable of listening to objects 10 billion light
years away.
   ``It's a major blow. There's no way to deny that,'' said George
Seielstad, NRAO's assistant director at the Green Bank operations.
   Seielstad said the telescope's loss will affect a long list of
research proposals, including a future space shuttle project.
   ``The Gamma Ray Observatory is scheduled to be launched by NASA
in 1990 from the space shuttle, and one of the things they will look
for will be pulse signals,'' he said. ``We were going to use this
telescope to monitor 100 of the brightest pulsars in conjunction
with the Gamma Ray observations.''
   He said no other telescope can take over such work.
   ``We're shocked,'' said Donald Backer, a University of
California-Berkeley astronomer who is doing pulsar research at a
sister observatory in Arecibo, Puerto Rico. ``We'll miss it.
   ``I'm sure a lot of operators of big dishes elsewhere across the
world are going to go out next week or tomorrow morning and check
what they never checked before.''
   Backer, who used Green Bank's 300-foot radiotelescope last year
to search for pulsars, said it long ago exceeded its expected
lifespan. It was built for $850,000 in 1962.
   Engineers from the National Science Foundation, which funds Green
Bank for a consortium of nine universities, flew to the site
Wednesday in an attempt to discover what caused the dish to topple.
   Seielstad said the telescope's 600 tons of metal dropped to the
ground without warning Tuesday night. The twin steel towers upon
which the structure moved were twisted and snapped. White aluminum
mesh panels that once made up the dish blanketed the rubble like an
umbrella pushed inside-out.
   ``It looks so much like someone lifted a big bowl into the air
and let it drop,'' Seielstad said.
   The unidentified employee operating the radiotelescope said there
was no warning, Seielstad said.
   Workers said the structure routinely snapped and popped,
especially as it cooled at night, but that it had survived heavy
snows, thunderstorms and 75 mph winds. Weather was calm Tuesday
night when the scope tumbled to the ground, workers said.
   The radiotelescope was capable of intercepting naturally emitted
radio signals from celestial bodies billions of light years away.
   Its most celebrated contribution to science came in 1968, when
astronomers used it to discover a pulsar at the center of the Crab
Nebula. The find helped prove that pulsars are the dense remains of
supernovae, or exploded stars.
   The observatory, which opened in 1959, has eight smaller
telescopes, the smallest 40 feet in diameter. Green Bank is located
in the Monongahela National Forest about 10 miles from the Virginia
border.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881117-0182 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-88 1920EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Mexico     11-17 0548</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Mexico,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panel Says Reducing Demand Key To Curbing Drug Flows</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A panel of leading Mexicans and Americans
recommended Thursday that the United States give top priority to
curbing U.S. demand for drugs as part of a more balanced policy in
dealing with that problem.
   The recommendation was contained in a lengthy study by the
Bilateral Commission on the Future of United States-Mexican
Relations on five areas of concern between the two countries.
   The commission was co-chaired by William D. Rogers, who held two
senior State Department posts during the Ford administration, and
Hugo B. Margain, a member of the Mexican Senate who is a former
ambassador to the United States.
   The 238-page study said the United States has placed excessive
emphasis on law enforcement to curb drug smuggling and that recent
increases in funding levels to reduce demand for drugs will prove
inadequate.
   ``The commission urges the U.S. to give top priority to learning
how to reduce demand and to allocate sufficient resources to move
rapidly in attacking this critical problem,'' the report said.
   ``A balanced strategy must also include a vigorous international
effort, in which drug control concerns are given high diplomatic
priority,'' it said.
   It suggested that the U.S. government subordinated the drug issue
in its relations with Panama and Honduras because priority was given
to security concerns.
   ``Such obviously selective application of its international
narcotics control policy undermines U.S. credibility with other
countries and with the multilateral institutions pledged to combat
drug abuse,'' the report said.
   Release of the report was timed to coincide with the advent of
new administrations in both Mexico and the United States. Mexican
President-elect Carlos Salinas de Gortari will be inaugurated on
Dec. 1, seven weeks before his U.S. counterpart, George Bush.
   Rogers told a news conference that Mexico ``stands second only to
the Soviet Union in its significance to the U.S.'' Copies of the
report were delivered to Secretary of State George P. Shultz and
national security adviser Colin Powell.
   The report also covered such issues as economics, migration,
foreign policy and education. Following are excerpts:
   Debt _ ``For Mexico ... debt service obligations in the future
should be designed subject to (its) capacity to pay under conditions
of growth. Without growth, adjustment will not be sustained; without
growth, resources for debt service will not be available.''
   Trade _ ``Both countries should continue to agree to generalized
trade concessions. They should move promptly to free-trade
agreements in all sectors where benefits from free trade may exist,
especially industrial sectors.''
   Migration _ ``Both governments ... should undertake to reach a
bilateral accord on migration, which should consider: a possible
increase in the legal quotas of Mexican migration to the U.S., an
agreement on the flow and treatment of `seasonal agricultural
workers,' the protection of migrants' human and labor rights and the
possibility of a long-run temporary worker program.''
   Foreign Policy _ ``A first step is to initiate a frank and open
dialogue on the concept of regional security. The commission
believes that regional security involves not only military-strategic
concerns but must also encompass questions of socio-economic
development.''
   Other commission members included former World Bank President
Robert McNamara, San Antonio Mayor Henry Cisneros, and Colegio de
Mexico President Mario Ojeda.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
