<1ST_LINE>u w AM-StateSpending     11-17 0505</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-State Spending,490</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>For Release 6:30 p.m. EST</NOTE>
<HEAD>Federal Aid to Local, State Governments Lowest Since 1966</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State and local government reliance on federal
aid last year sank to its lowest level in more than 20 years, the
Census Bureau said Thursday.
   From a high of 18.7 cents per dollar of state and local
government revenue in 1978, the federal contribution withered to
13.6 cents in 1987. It was the lowest since 1966, when Lyndon
Johnson was gearing up the Great Society programs and the federal
contribution was 13.5 cents per dollar.
   Total federal aid actually has risen throughout the period _ from
$70 billion in 1978, to $113 billion in 1986 to $115 billion in
1987. But it is increasing at a slower rate than other state and
local government revenues.
   While the federal contribution grew at an average of 5.7 percent
a year from 1978 to 1987, the amount raised by state and local taxes
grew an average of 8.5 percent a year.
   Last year, state and local taxes grew 8.6 percent to $405.1
billion, while federal aid increased only 1.7 percent. Revenue from
all sources totaled $842.6 billion.
   Henry Wulf, a Census Bureau analyst, said the federal share
likely will slip again in future years because state and local
governments will be increasing spending to upgrade
``infrastructure'' items such as sewers and roads.
   Randolph Arndt, a spokesman for the National League of Cities,
said the trend is disturbing because the bulk of state and local
taxes, based either on sales or real estate, are more regressive
than the federal sliding scale for income taxes.
   Also, he said, ``The significance of these reductions goes beyond
the numbers in that the results have been felt most severely in
those communities where needs are already the greatest.''
   ``The fact is when a region is distressed, whether it is the Oil
Patch now or the Great Lakes Rust Belt earlier in the decade, it has
much less capacity to generate revenues,'' he said.
   Arndt said federal assistance began declining in the Carter
administration as part of an effort to fight inflation. It continued
to decline in administration of President Reagan, first as part of
Reagan's ``new federalism'' shifting many government functions to
the local level and second as part of the effort to reduce the
federal budget deficit.
   According to the Census Bureau, state and local government
spending grew 8.1 percent last year to $775.3 billion, up $57.9
billion, compared with a 9.1 percent rise a year earlier. Average
growth in spending since 1978 has been 11 percent.
   Topping the spending list were education, $227 billion (29.3
cents per dollar spent); public welfare, $83 billion (10.7 cents);
publicly owned utilities, $66 billion (8.5 cents); and highways, $52
billion (6.7 cents).
   Salaries and wages accounted for 35.4 percent of state and local
government spending, but increased at a slightly slower rate, 6.9
percent, than overall spending.
   Outstanding state debt also increased, up 9.1 percent to $718.7
billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
