<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Kafka     11-17 0615</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kafka,0636</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nearly $2 Million Paid For Kafka's `Trial'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GRAHAM HEATHCOTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The handwritten manuscript of Franz Kafka's ``The
Trial,'' which was smuggled to safety during World War II despite
the author's dying wish that it be burned, sold for a record $1.98
million Thursday.
   The 316-page text of the novel, which came to symbolize
20th-century totalitarianism, was bought at auction by the German
state government of Baden-Wuerttemberg for 1.1 million pounds.
   Kafka, a Czechoslovak Jew, completed the novel in 1920 and it was
published in 1925, a year after he died from tuberculosis at age 41.
The novel's hero, Joseph K., who has done nothing wrong, is
arrested, tried and executed without ever being told of what he is
accused.
   The novel's terrifying account of K.'s entrapment in judicial
bureaucracy gave the word ``Kafkaesque'' to the language.
   Kafka gave his manuscripts in 1924 to Max Brod, who ignored the
writer's orders to burn them and fled with the works to Palestine
the night the German army entered Prague in 1938. Brod, Kafka's
literary executor, died in 1968.
   A spokesman for the state government in Stuttgart said the
manuscript would probably go to the German Literature Archives in
Marbach.
   ``We want it in Germany because Kafka wrote it in German, and
because it is the most important novel of our century,'' said the
successful bidder, antiquarian bookseller Heribert Tenschert from
Rotthalmunster, near Munich.
   ``I would have bought it for myself and paid double what I did,
but our authorities contacted me to buy it. I would have gone to 2
or 3 million pounds,'' Tenschert told reporters outside Sotheby's
saleroom.
   The 40-year-old bookseller, a previous buyer of medieval
manuscripts in London, added: ``It is definitely a very good deal, a
bargain. For such a work, one has to be prepared to pay.
   ``I hope there will be a lot of happiness in Germany about this
purchase, especially at this price.''
   The seller was not identified.
   Brod left his papers to his secretary and companion, Ester Hoffe.
When Tenschert was asked if Ms. Hoffe was the seller, he hesitated
and then said he couldn't discuss that.
   Auctioneer Roy Davids started the bidding at 400,000 pounds, or
$720,000, and ended it one minute later, with Tenschert and another
person bidding in $90,000 increments.
   Asked if he knew who the other bidder was, Tenschert said: ``I
wasn't interested in underbidders _ I was determined to get it. I
knew I would get it.''
   The final bid was exactly 1 million pounds, but the auctioneers
add a 10 percent commission.
   The price was an auction record for any modern literary
transcript. Auctioneers define ``modern'' as anything written since
the Middle Ages, a historians' loose term for the 5th to 15th
centuries.
   The price eclipsed the $605,000 paid in New York last year for
Kafka's letters to his fiancee, Felice Bauer, and the previous
record for a purely literary work, the 275,000 pounds, about
$370,000, paid in July 1985 for a notebook of poetry and prose by
Irish writer William Butler Yeats.
   ``What makes `The Trial' even more valuable is that Brod left his
own manuscripts in Prague to put Kafka's in his suitcase,''
Tenschert said.
   Tenschert said he will pay for the manuscript when he returns to
London on Dec. 6, the two-week delay needed for British authorities
to issue an export license.
   ``Poor old Kafka, he died broke,'' commented a reporter.
   ``Yes,'' said Tenschert, ``and my wife said if I bought `The
Trial' I should burn it because Kafka wanted that.
   ``Well, if it was my money buying it I would consider that, but I
can't because someone else is paying.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
