<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Stealth     11-17 0492</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Stealth,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Union of Concerned Scientists Criticize Stealth Bomber</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new Stealth bomber is unlikely to be able
to carry out its wartime job of destroying mobile Soviet
nuclear-tipped missiles, according to a report issued Thursday.
   The Soviets probably will be able to counter the bomber, meaning
``prospects for success in holding a significant fraction of Soviet
mobile targets at risk are very poor,'' said the report by the Union
of Concerned Scientists.
   The 19-year-old private organization has been critical of other
Reagan administration national security policies, particularly
President Reagan's Star Wars anti-missile research program.
   The report was issued less than a week before the Air Force
publicly unveils the bomber for the first time. The plane, known as
the B-2, uses composite materials and an unusual ``flying wing''
shape to hide it from Soviet radars.
   The Air Force is planning to buy 132 B-2s at a cost of $68.8
billion, making it one of the most expensive weapons ever built.
   The Stealth would be one of the components _ along with the new
B-1 and older B-52 _ of the bomber leg of America's three-pronged
nuclear force. Other components of that deterrent are land-based and
submarine-based nuclear missiles.
   According to the Union of Concerned Scientists' study, the main
mission of the Stealth bomber would be to ``hunt down and destroy
Soviet mobile nuclear targets during a protracted nuclear conflict.''
   But that could cause arms control problems, the study noted. With
both nations aiming to cut their arsenals of long-range atomic
weapons by 50 percent through START negotiations under way in
Geneva, ``the survivability of their remaining forces will be
critical to stability,'' it said.
   ``For the land-based forces of both superpowers, mobility will be
a key means of satisfying this requirement,'' the report said. ``The
B-2 bomber is thus out of phase with the trend of arms control.''
   ``At a time when the United States should be tailoring its
procurement of strategic forces to the post-START world _ and to the
realities of a constant or declining defenses budget _ the B-2 is a
step in the wrong direction,'' the report noted.
   But Capt. Jay DeFrank, an Air Force spokesman, said, ``The B-2
may be at the heart of solving the mobile ICBM (intercontinental
ballistic missile) problem, but the mobile missile issue is not the
heart of the B-2 requirement.''
   ``The B-2's primary mission is deterrence across the spectrum of
conflict,'' DeFrank said. ``The B-2 will have the capability to
penetrate the most sophisticated enemy defenses and threaten their
most valued targets whatever they may be.''
   But there are other problems, the study said. For example, the
B-2 would be vulnerable to future Soviet defenses, such as
space-based radar systems that could ``look down'' and spot the
plane.
   In addition, the aerial refueling planes and necessary airfields
needed to support B-2 flights wouldn't survive a prolonged nuclear
war, the study contended.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
