<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FarmBureau     11-17 0419</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Farm Bureau,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Farmers Could Live With Budget Freeze, Farm Bureau Chief Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmers could live with a spending freeze
designed to erase red budget ink without new taxes if they were not
singled out for sacrifice, the leader of the nation's largest farm
group said Thursday.
   ``I'm not talking about eliminating federal programs or cutting
current outlays,'' Dean Kleckner, president of the American Farm
Bureau Federation, told a news conference.
   ``I'm only suggesting a moratorium on spending increases,''
Kleckner said. ``Stop the increases, just the increases, and the
budget would balance itself.''
   Kleckner, an Iowa hog, corn and soybean producer, is a member of
the National Economic Commission, which is seeking ways to reduce
the deficit. He has been mentioned as a possible Bush selection for
secretary of agriculture.
   Kleckner said even a partial freeze with $30 billion to $40
billion in new spending could reduce the deficit quickly because of
projected increases in revenue over the next five years of $80
billion to $90 billion annually.
   Bush has urged a ``flexible freeze'' to reduce the deficit while
vowing not to attempt to balance the budget with a tax increase.
   It remains unclear how a flexible freeze might effect politically
popular farm payments programs, which totaled $17.5 billion last
year.
   Rebellion would not erupt in the Farm Belt over a freeze provided
the agricultural sector did not come in for disproportionate cuts,
Kleckner said.
   ``I'm convinced that farmers won't object to a freeze ... as long
as they understand that they are not alone,'' he said.
   But claimed that the idea behind the National Economic Commission
was to recommend a politically unpalatable tax increase and in so
doing allow politicians to shift the blame from their own shoulders.
   ``Let's be honest,'' Kleckner said. ``The commission was created
to provide cover for a tax increase.''
   Kleckner said there has been a campaign in the news media and
elsewhere to convince voters that there is no alternative to a tax
increase.
   ``The common conventional Washington wisdom is that unless you
people know that we need a tax increase to balance the budget you
have your head in the sand and you're from Sticksville,'' Kleckner
said.
   He said the Bush victory was evidence that the bulk of American
voters take exactly the opposite view of a tax hike.
   ``I will make the case that the election was a referendum on that
issue because the other issues weren't that clear,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881117-0190 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-88 1937EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FCC-Satellites     11-17 0272</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-FCC-Satellites,270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FCC Authorizes Construction, Launch of Satellites</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Communications Commission on
Thursday authorized construction of 13 domestic communications
satellites and the launch of nine. It also authorized construction
and launch of 10 replacement satellites.
   The action brings to 42 the number of authorized domestic
satellites providing a variety of telecommunications services,
including video and data services.
   The FCC said the newly authorized satellites, set to be launched
through 1994, will provide domestic satellite capacity through the
end of the century.
   The last group of satellites was authorized in 1985. Of the 20
spacecraft in the group, only four are being constructed. The
remaining 16 were casualties for various reasons, notably a slump in
the satellite industry following the explosion of the space shuttle
Challenger in January 1986, which grounded the U.S. space program
and severely limited commercial satellite launch options, said Fern
Jarmulnek, an FCC satellite official.
   The commission said it granted all of the applications it
received for the orbital slots 22,300 miles above the equator. The
authorizations leave nine slots unassigned, Jarmulnek said.
   In making assignments, the FCC also changed the position of
certain slots in the orbit as required by a recent agreement with
Canada and Mexico expanding the orbital space assigned to those two
countries. In reassigning U.S. satellites, however, the United
States retains the same number of orbital slots for its satellites.
   As a result of the agreement, three U.S. satellites that are in
orbit will have to relocate. This will be accomplished by firing
small thruster rockets on the satellites that are used to fine-tune
the spacecraft's position in orbit.
</TEXT>
