<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Reagan-Dams     11-17 0237</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Dams,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Signs Bills Preventing Dams on Idaho Rivers, Georgia Lake</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan signed legislation Thursday
prohibiting the construction of hydroelectric dams on stretches of
the Snake and Salmon Rivers in Idaho.
   The measure also was designed to prohibit the Federal Energy
Regulatory Commission from granting a license for a hydroelectric
facility on Lake Tobesofkee in Georgia without approval of the
governing body of Bibb County.
   The president said part of the bill was unconstitutional because
it would have given local authorities power to perform ``significant
authority'' pursuant to federal laws. As a result, he said, he was
signing the bill with the understanding that it simply forbids the
licensing of hydroelectric dams on the lake.
   Sponsors of the bill said it was designed to prevent interference
with the use of the manmade lake, which has 345 private homes and a
number of county beaches on its shores and to avoid interference
with county revenues.
   In Idaho, the bill will affect 33 miles of the Snake River north
of Hells Canyon and 112 miles of the Salmon River upstream from its
confluence with the Snake.
   Some stretches of the two rivers already are protected from
dam-building because they are part of the Wild and Scenic Rivers
System, and sponsors of the bill sought to extend this protection to
the additional stretches even though they had not been designated
part of the system.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
