<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0653,0803</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israeli Soldiers Wound 27 Palestinians in Occupied Territories</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 6th graf pvs `Islamic extremists...' with 3 grafs to
UPDATE with bomb attack, PICKS UP graf 7th pvs `A fundamentalist...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli soldiers wounded at least 27
Palestinians during street battles in the occupied lands Thursday,
including a 9-year-old boy and 14-year-old girl who were in critical
condition, hospital officials reported.
   The army eased curfews and other restrictions imposed in an
effort to curtail violence and celebration connected with Tuesday's
proclamation by the PLO of an independent Palestinian state.
   More than 7,000 Palestinians have been wounded since the uprising
against Israeli occupation began nearly a year ago in the West Bank
and Gaza Strip, which Israel captured from Jordan and Egypt in 1967.
Eleven Israelis and at least 313 Palestinians have been killed.
   Hospital officials reported at least four people seriously
wounded in confrontations in Tamoun, a West Bank village, and
several areas of Gaza, including the Shati and Deir al-Balagh
refugee camps.
   The wounded included the 9-year-old from the Shati camp, who was
shot in the head, and a 14-year-old girl from Tamoun, who was hit in
the spinal cord by a bullet, the Palestinian doctors said.
   In Arab east Jerusalem, a bomb exploded Thursday as a police
vehicle passed nearby, Israel television said. No injuries were
reported.
   The attack followed a day of scattered clashes in Jerusalem,
which Israel considers its capital. Three policemen were injured by
rocks, and at least ten Palestinians were detained.
   Islamic extremists circulated a new leaflet Thursday urging
residents of the territories to reject the declaration of an
independent state by the Palestine National Council, which acts as
the legislature of the Palestine Liberation Organization.
   A fundamentalist group named Hamas (Zeal) called for a three-day
strike beginning Friday to protest the declaration, which includes
acceptance of U.N. resolutions that implicitly recognize Israel.
   ``Palestine extends from the Jordan River to the (Mediterranean)
sea,'' it said. ``This independence is imaginary and does not exist
in the world of reality.''
   ``The PNC's acceptance of (U.N. resolutions) 242 and 338 means
putting the armed struggle aside and giving Israel the right to
Palestine,'' it said.
   An army spokesman said troops raided Tamoun village, 15 miles
northeast of Nablus, and soldiers opened fire on young Palestinians
who hurled rocks.
   Officials at Al Ittihad Hospital in Nablus said 13 Palestinians
were wounded, three seriously. The army confirmed four wounded and
said it was checking the other reports.
   Residents said health officials had announced they would give
polio vaccinations Thursday and many of the 50 people wanted by the
Israeli authorities returned to Tamoun from hideouts in the area.
   Soldiers arrived in nine vehicles and ordered the health
officials to leave, the residents said.
   They reported three hours of street battles in the hilltop
village, which was decorated with five outlawed Palestinian flags
and pictures of PLO chairman Yasser Arafat.
   Windows in five houses were smashed. Izat Bisharat, 38, showed a
reporter his damaged car, which he said soldiers commandeered to
chase stone-throwers.
   ``It was like a war,'' said Feisal Jaballah, 20. ``Every time
somebody got wounded, people escalated their resistance.''
   Slogans painted on the walls reflected the rift in Palestinian
ranks.
   ``No to 181 partition plan. Don't accept council that accepts
compromises,'' said one signed by the pro-Syrian Salvation Front.
Another painted by the pro-Iraq Arab Liberation Front said: ``Syria
has no right to interfere in our affairs.''
   Syria opposes Arafat's leadership of the PLO and the independence
declaration, and supported Iran in its war with Iraq.
   The ``181 partition plan'' refers to U.N. General Assembly
Resolution 181 of 1947, which called for both Jewish and Arab states
in what then was Palestine.
   During the uprising, Israeli soldiers have carried out several
raids in the West Bank to make Palestinians obliterate anti-Israeli
slogans and take down the black, green and red Palestinian flags.
   In the occupied Gaza Strip, the army lifted a 6-day-old curfew in
most towns and cities but kept it in place for the 250,000
Palestinians in the coastal territory's eight refugee camps. A
curfew also was kept on the Nur Shams refugee camp near Tulkarem in
the West Bank.
   Troops confronted Palestinian rioters in the Gaza towns of Rafah,
Khan Yunis and Gaza City and two refugee camps, wounding 14
Palestinians, hospital officials said. The army said it was checking
the reports.
   Telephone lines remained cut to homes and businesses for a
seventh day in the West Bank cities of Hebron, Nablus, Ramallah and
Jenin. Service was halted to prevent Palestinians from coordinating
anti-Israeli activities during the Palestine National Council
meeting in Algiers.
</TEXT>
