<2ND_LINE>AM-No Children,0300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Condo Group Threatens Child with Eviction after Her Mother Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARGATE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 9-year-old girl who moved into an
adults-only condominium complex after her mother died of cancer now
lives under the threat of eviction.
   Jamie Swartz moved in with her father, Lynn Swartz, and
stepmother, Jill, last spring after her mother began chemotherapy
treatment. Her mother died in September, and Friday Jill Swartz
received a letter saying the Viewpoint Condominium association would
seek a court order to remove Jamie from the complex in this town
north of Miami.
   ``I felt like, `My God, they really hate children, they really
hate children,''' said Jill Swartz, who added the turmoil could be
tough on the youngster. ``With the trauma of having already lost her
mother, she doesn't need this.''
   The association this week gave the family a one-month reprieve.
Jill Swartz asked the condo board Wednesday to allow Jamie to remain
with the Swartzes until they sell the condominium, and association
attorney Douglas Neway said the board would consider the request.
   ``No litigation is going to be instituted at this point,'' said
Neway.
   ``I'm grateful. I regret that it took this for them to be
considerate of our feelings and our circumstances,'' Mrs. Swartz
said.
   The couple said they notified the association last spring that
Jamie would stay with them periodically while her mother, Maye
Swartz, was hospitalized. They also promised to find a new place to
live if the problem became long-term.
   The board agreed to suspend its rule for three months, but last
Friday threatened the family with the court order.
   Neway said board members were unaware of Maye Swartz's death when
they asked him to notify the family of the possibility of a court
order.
</TEXT>
