<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FCC-PhoneServices 1stLd-Writethru a0689 11-17 0574</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-FCC-Phone Services, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0689,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FCC Moves to Make Advanced Phone Services Widely Available</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts new 2nd graf and adds 5 grafs at end with pricing
controversy and reaction; longer version on business news wire</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Communications Commission took a
major step Thursday toward making advanced telephone services such
as voice mail and computer gateways available on a wide scale to
average consumers.
   The FCC also, however, reopened a thorny issue that earlier met
vigorous opposition from the providers of these electronic
information services who resisted an agency proposal to add hefty
charges to their bills.
   The commission's action moves toward opening the phone networks
so that connections and circuits will be available on an equal basis
to competing companies that want to provide advanced phone services.
   Competition, the commission says, will result in lower prices and
more choices for consumers, as long as the Bell companies are not
allowed to use their control of the local phone networks to
disadvantage competitors.
   Open Network Architecture, as the plan is called, ``will pass
along to average residential consumers the ability to patronize the
fruits of the information age,'' said FCC Chairman Dennis R. Patrick.
   The three sitting commissioners voted unanimously to approve the
Bell companies' plans in substantial part but to require revisions
in specified areas, in part to ensure greater uniformity among their
separate plans. The FCC also approved American Telephone & Telegraph
Co.'s plan in total.
   Many of the enhanced services dealt with in the plans are already
available on a limited scale from the phone companies. Open Network
Architecture is expected to result in more competition, which would
bring the services to more consumers at lower prices, the FCC said.
   The FCC pointed to voice mail as an example of a service that it
expects to become more widely available and attractive to average
consumers. This service permits callers to send and receive recorded
messages in a manner similar to that now available with telephone
answering machines.
   However, instead of having to buy an answering machine, callers
would need only a touch-tone phone. The messaging capabilities would
be provided out of a centralized computer.
   Computer gateways allows easier access to electronic data bases.
Computer users would have access to many different information
services by dialing just one number.
   Most of the Bell companies applauded the action, but BellSouth
said the FCC should have allowed its plan to charge information
service providers based on their usage of the network, instead of a
flat rate as they are now.
   Attorney Stephen Bell, who represents Tymnet and has been a
leading spokesman for the information providers, said that while
there was ``a lot of good news'' in the FCC's action, he was
concerned about the issue of how these providers will be charged by
phone companies.
   The commission specifically noted that an existing exemption from
network access charges would continue for information service
providers, although the FCC agreed to begin proceedings that could
consider removing the exemption under certain circumstances.
   ``This could have a dramatic and serious effect on the
information services industry,'' Bell said, promising to fight
vigorously against removal of the exemption.
   Earlier this year, after an outcry from the industry, the FCC
retreated from a proposal to lift the exemption. Without the
exemption, costs could more than double, in some cases, for computer
users dialing into information data bases.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881117-0199 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-88 1727EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Atwater-Profile 1stLd-Writethru a0738 11-17 0886</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Atwater-Profile, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0738,870</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>If They Couldn't Hire Him, They Hated Him</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 24th graf pvs, bgng ``New York ...''to
update with Kemp comment; edits 25th graf pvs for transition</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD L. VERNACI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Political candidates who found themselves
opposed by Lee Atwater would often wind up wishing they could hire
him _ or else blaming him for alleged dirty tricks that damaged
their campaigns.
   Now President-elect George Bush has handpicked the 37-year-old
Atwater to work on behalf of all Republicans who run for office.
   Bush selected his former campaign manager Thursday to become
chairman of the Republican National Committee, a choice sure to be
ratified, probably unanimously, when the committee meets Jan. 18,
two days before Bush's inauguration.
   ``He's a friend; I'm proud of his accomplishments,'' Bush said of
the man who helped orchestrate his victory Nov. 8.
   Atwater will succeed Frank Fahrenkopf Jr., a 48-year-old Reno,
Nev. lawyer whose seven years in the post make him the
longest-serving GOP chief in this century.
   Atwater's friends say that while he likes having a ``tough-guy''
image, his reputation for stepping beyond the bounds of political
propriety is undeserved.
   Atwater, who described himself as a ``nuts and bolts
politician,'' will take control of a party that has been successful
in electing five of the last six presidents but has not been able to
gain control of Congress. Politics has been his life; he's been
active since his college days.
   ``I will be extremely campaign-oriented,'' Atwater told
reporters, adding that he hoped to help Republicans win elections
from the courthouse to the state house to the White House. He said
he would launch special efforts to lure black and Hispanic voters
into Republican ranks.
   ``Every political reporter in the country worth his salt has
scoured Lee's background and haven't found one dirty trick,'' said
Christopher Simpson, press secretary to Sen. Strom Thurmond, R-S.C.
Atwater, a South Carolina native, worked for Thurmond as an intern
in 1978.
   ``I would say he's tough as nails,'' Simpson said. ``I think
people probably do confuse tough with dirty.''
   Thurmond praised Atwater as a ``superb choice'' for the RNC post.
   ``He's got a tough-guy image,'' said South Carolina GOP Chairman
Van Hipp. ``I think Lee enjoys it, to be honest with you.''
   At times in the 1988 race for the White House, the image of
Atwater pulling strings seemed to drive some of Bush's Republican
opponents to distraction.
   Early this year Sen. Bob Dole, R-Kan., accused Atwater of being
behind a series of disclosures about his wife's finances.
   Atwater's answer was to call Dole ``a typical schoolyard bully _
he can dish it out but if someone hits him back, he starts
whining.'' He also sent Dole a 10-page letter listing negative
tactics that he said Dole had used.
   Asked about that, Dole said, ``I don't respond to Lee Atwater.''
   But he already had.
   A day earlier, Dole confronted Bush on the floor of the Senate
and demanded an apology.
   Simpson used ``brilliant'' to describe Atwater's ability of
drawing an opponent's fire to himself and away from the candidate he
serves.
   That's what happened in the Dole-Bush confrontation when Dole
complained, ``Here's the Bush campaign, maybe not the vice president
himself, but Lee Atwater and others out distributing things that
they think might reflect on Elizabeth Dole for some reason.''
   Television evangelist Pat Robertson, at the time also a candidate
for the GOP presidential nomination, accused Atwater of being
personally responsible for setting the date of the South Carolina
primary to give Bush a boost just before the crucial one-day round
of Southern primaries in March.
   Robertson could not bring himself to utter Atwater's name, but
his meaning was unmistakable: ``I understand a campaign manager of
an unnamed vice president is from South Carolina, and he has
determined he would like to have his man have a bit of an edge by a
big win here ... that would propel him to a better showing
throughout the South.''
   Hipp denied that Atwater had anything to do with the timing of
the South Carolina primary.
   New York Rep. Jack Kemp, another of this year's unsuccessful
Republican presidential candidates, wanted to hire Atwater to manage
his campaign.
   ``I've always been a fan of Atwater's; I think he's a sharp
guy,'' Kemp said Thursday. ``I knew I couldn't hire him.''
   ``Is he going to have enemies? You bet,'' Kemp said. ``I think
people should let bygones be bygones. What good is it to hold
grudges in politics?''
   Atwater signed on with Bush, whom he had helped defeat for the
presidential nomination in 1980. At the time Atwater was the manager
of Ronald Reagan's campaign in South Carolina and was credited with
unleashing a series of radio commercials attacking Bush on gun
control.
   In 1984 Atwater was the deputy manager of Reagan's re-election
campaign and later he became a partner in the lobbying firm of
Black, Manafort & Stone, whose $800,000 contract to represent the
Bahamian government briefly became a campaign issue this year.
   Atwater became politically active when he went to college and
became national director of the College Republicans when Bush was
RNC chairman in 1973-74.
   Before that, he was a professional musician, playing the guitar
for rock 'n' roll singer Percy Sledge.
</TEXT>
