<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-88 1731EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Obit-Lee     11-17 0261</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Lee,0267</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First British Arts Minister Jennie Lee, 85</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jennie Lee, Britain's first arts minister and the
widow of Labor Party politician Aneurin Bevan, has died, her friend
Lord Goodman said Thursday. She was 85.
   Goodman said Ms. Lee died Wednesday at her London home. The cause
of death was not immediately available.
   Ms. Lee's major achievement was to take politics ``clean out of
the arts,'' said Goodman, who was chairman of the state-appointed
Arts Council when Ms. Lee was made arts minister in 1965-1970 by
Labor Prime Minister, Harold Wilson.
   As minister she had a leading role in establishing the Open
University, which offered higher education through evening classes,
radio and television and correspondence to thousands who had never
been to college.
   Labor Party leader Neil Kinnock in a tribute called her a ``woman
of brilliance and vision, a great socialist, who inspired so many
and was loved by all who knew her warmth and passion for justice.''
   Ms. Lee received a life peerage as Baroness Lee of Asheridge with
a seat in the House of Lords after losing her House of Commons seat
in the 1970 general election. In 1972 she promoted legislation
allowing theaters to open on Sundays.
   Jennie Lee, a Scottish miner's daughter, won a scholarship to
Edinburgh University, where she majored in law and then qualified as
a schoolteacher.
   Bevan, a Welsh miner's son whom she married in 1934, established
the state-run National Health Service in 1948 against opposition
from the medical profession. He died in 1960. The couple had no
children.
</TEXT>
