<DOCNO> AP881117-0201 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-88 2003EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Iran-Contra     11-17 0396</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Contra,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Rejects North Charge Of Prosecutor Abuse</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The judge in the Iran-Contra conspiracy case on
Thursday rejected Oliver L. North's charges of prosecutorial abuse
by independent counsel Lawrence E. Walsh, saying the defense had
indulged ``misinformation and hyperbole'' in a motion to dismiss the
case.
   ``North finds it appropriate to assert prosecutorial misdconduct
in the harshest terms based solely on his self-serving suspicions,''
U.S. District Judge Gerhard A. Gesell said in turning back the
motion.
   ``This is not the mark of responsible advocacy,'' Gesell said,
chastising the former presidential aide's defense lawyers.
   ``This is a motion which, by caption and text, appears
significant, but which, in substance, is, to a considerable extent,
based on misinformation and hyperbole,'' the judge wrote in a
five-page opinion.
   The defense contended that prosecutors had given grand jurors
``patently erroneous'' legal instructions and ``systematically
excluded'' evidence that would show the retired Marine lieutenant
colonel's innocence.
   But Gesell, who has reviewed the grand jury transcript, said
``these exaggerated statements are made in total disregard of the
careful instructions and monitoring of the grand jury throughout its
proceedings by the chief judge of this court.''
   ``Moreover, the statements concerning what occurred before the
grand jury are largely based on inferences reached by counsel
without any knowledge of what actually took place'' during the
secret proceedings, the judge said
   North, a former National Security Council aide, is charged with
conspiring with former national security adviser John M. Poindexter
and arms dealers Albert Hakim and Richard V. Secord, to illegally
divert profits from U.S.-Iran arms-sales to the Nicaraguan rebels.
   No date has been set for North's trial, the first of four ordered
by Gesell.
   The judge dismissed North's suggestion that prosecutors failed to
tell the grand jury about whether the so-called Boland Amendments
prohibiting direct U.S. military aid to the Contras applied to the
National Security Council staff.
   ``There is no requirement that the grand jury be instructed on
every aspect of the law, as North appears to suggest,'' Gesell said.
   ``Never have prosecutors had to present all possible legal
defenses to a grand jury, much less did the independent counsel have
to introduce the ones suggested by North, many of which are based on
the most speculative of legal theories, as this court has so ruled
in dismissing several of his motions.''
</TEXT>
