<HEAD>U.S. Officials Say Two Afghan Diplomats Have Defected</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 4th pvs `Sources at...' to UPDATE with
reports of possible identity of deputy foreign minister, PICKS UP
graf 5 pvs `No spokesmen...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two diplomats who accompanied Afghanistan's
prime minister on his mission to the United Nations last week have
defected, U.S. officials said Thursday.
   The State Department confirmed the diplomats did not return to
Kabul but would not say more about their whereabouts, according to
an official at the U.S. Mission to the United Nations who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   Other U.S. officials confirmed the diplomats had defected to the
United States.
   Sources at the United Nations and other U.S. officials said the
defectors were a deputy foreign minister and another senior diplomat.
   Abdul Ghaffar Lakanwal serves as deputy foreign minister for
Afghanistan, according to Rosanne Klass, a former New York Times
reporter who wrote ``Afghanistan: The Great Game Revisited.''
   U.N. and State Department sources said earlier Thursday that one
of the defectors was a deputy foreign minister named Lanikwal. The
U.N. sources said the other defector was named Kamal.
   Lakanwal's career had been in decline, Klass said. He was
minister for Agriculture and Land Reform from 1981 to March 1987,
when he was dropped from the Cabinet.
   No spokesmen were available for comment at Afghanistan's Mission
to the United Nations. Government offices were closed in Pakistan
and Afghanistan when the U.S. officials confirmed the defection.
   Afghan Prime Minister Mohammad Hassan Sharq was in New York last
week for talks with Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar and
other officials.
