<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SouthKorea-Protest     11-17 0294</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Korea-Protest,0301</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Battle Farmers Marching On US Embassy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Korea</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By C.W. LIM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Riot police fired tear gas Thursday to
drive back thousands of angry farmers who were marching on the U.S.
Embassy to protest imports of American farm products.
   Fighting began when police barred the path of about 7,000
farmers. Hundreds of protesters armed with rocks and clubs charged
about 2,000 policemen, who formed a human barricade behind their
shields a few hundred yards from the embassy.
   Scores of radical students joined the farmers and hurled
firebombs.
   About a dozen protesters and police were seen bleeding or being
carried away but police did not provide figures on injuries or
arrests. Suh Kyong-won, an opposition legislator, was injured when
he tried to stop police who charged protesters.
   Some citizens booed police when elderly farmers hurled their
bodies against shields. Officers refrained from firing tear gas at
that point and some moved away.
   The protesters dispersed after about 90 minutes, but thousands of
police ringed the embassy and guarded adjacent streets and nearby
residences of U.S. diplomats.
   Farmers had marched peacefully for about six miles after a rally
near the National Assembly building, shouting ``Drive out Yankees!''
and ``Oppose U.S. agricultural imports!''
   It was the most violent demonstration in Seoul by farmers, who
have protested U.S. pressure on South Korea to open its markets to
beef, wine and other agricultural products. Many wore headbands
saying, ``No U.S. wine and beef'' and ``Down with U.S.
imperialists.''
   South Korean farmers believe cheap agricultural imports threaten
their livelihoods and have urged the government to resist U.S.
pressure.
   Trade conflicts between the allies have fanned anti-American
sentiment. Thursday's protesters chanted ``Drive out Yankees, who
force the market-opening pressure!''
</TEXT>
