<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-88 1914EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel-PLO     11-17 0643</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-PLO,0668</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Peres Spearheads Israeli Damage Control Over Palestinian Meeting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Minister Shimon Peres, spearheading an
Israeli damage control drive, accused the PLO on Thursday of
deceiving the world by claiming it moderated its positions at the
Palestine National Council meeting.
   ``We feel very strongly that under the headline of moderation,
what really happened is a more extreme position taken by the PNC,''
he told foreign reporters at a news conference.
   The council, which acts as the legislature of Yasser Arafat's
Palestine Liberation Organization, declared an independent
Palestinian state Tuesday at the end of a four-day session in
Algiers, capital of Algeria.
   As of Thursday, 25 nations had recognized the Palestinian state.
President Corazon Aquino said in Manila that the Philippines was
considering recognition.
   Delegates at Algiers also implictly recognized Israel and said
the council would limit guerrilla operations to military targets in
Israeli-occupied territories.
   Peres, head of the left-leaning Labor Party, said the council's
declaration of a Palestinian state further sabotaged the Middle East
peace process.
   ``I see an attempt to throw a stone into a structure of glass
(the peace process), so delicate, so breakable,'' Peres said. He
said the final status of the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip must
be negotiated in peace talks.
   Israeli ambassadors sought meetings with foreign ministers in
various host countries to explain Israel's position and prevent
recognition of the new state.
   ``We are trying to have some damage control,'' he said.
   Israel is also working out a joint strategy with the United
States to keep the Palestinian state from being accredited as an
observer nation in the United Nations, Peres said.
   He said the outgoing Israeli government, deeply divided on peace
issues, stood united in its rejection of the PLO positions. ``Isn't
it your impression that we have the same position for a change?''
Peres said when asked if he was stating government policy.
   He argued that the Palestinians at Algiers rejected the three
conditions posed by America for talks with the PLO: recognition of
Israel, renunciation of terror and acceptance of U.N. Security
Council resolutions 242 and 338.
   Resolution 338, in one major provision, calls for negotiations
between the parties for ``a just and durable peace in the Middle
East.''
   Resolution 242, adopted earlier after the 1967 Mideast war, asks
Israel to withdraw from captured territory and declares the right of
all states in the region to exist within secure borders.
   In accepting 242, the Algiers meeting coupled it with the right
of the Palestinian people to self-determination.
   Peres argued that by adding phrases, the council perverted the
meaning of the resolution.
   He also discounted interpretations that the PLO implicitly
recognized Israel by declaring a Palestinian state based on the 1947
U.N. partition plan which calls for a Jewish and an Arab state side
by side in Palestine.
   ``Israel is not an implicit state. You either recognize it, or
you don't,'' Peres said.
   State Department spokesman Charles Redman had said in Washington
Wednesday that implicit recognition was insufficient. ``Recognition
must be clear and unambiguous,'' he said.
   Peres also claimed the PLO had not renounced terrorism.
   In a statement in reply to written questions submitted by
reporters, Mrs. Aquino hailed a political declaration by the council
on the U.N. resolutions as ``a positive development not only for the
Philippines but for the whole world.''
   The Philippines depends on the Middle East for most of its oil
needs and sends thousands of workers to Arab countries each year.
   Nations which recognized the Palestinian state are: Afghanistan,
Algeria, Bahrain, Bangladesh, India, Indonesia, Iraq, Jordan,
Kuwait, Libya, Madagascar, Malaysia, Mauritania, Morocco, Nicaragua,
North Yemen, South Yemen, Qatar, Pakistan, Saudi Arabia, Sudan,
Tunisia, Turkey, the United Arab Emirates and Yugoslavia.
   The Egyptian daily Al-Ahram said Cuba, Zambia and Somalia also
recognized the Palestinian state, but cited no source.
</TEXT>
