<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-Falklands     11-17 0257</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Falklands,0263</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>General Assembly Urges Negotiations on Falklands</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The General Assembly passed its annual
resolution Thursday urging Britain and Argentina to open
negotiations on the sovereignty of the Falkland Islands, over which
they fought a 74-day war in 1982.
   The vote in the 159-member assembly was 109-5 with 37
abstentions. Last year it was 114-5 with 36 abstentions.
   Britain, which won the war by driving an Argentine invasion force
out of the South Atlantic archipelago, cast its customary vote
against the resolution but the United States voted in favor.
   Sir Crispen Tickell, the British ambassador, declared during
debate: ``We are not ready to enter into negotiations on all aspects
of the future of the Falkland Islands. That would mean the beginning
of negotiations which would represent the method by which Argentina
would recover sovereignty.''
   ``The British government will continue to uphold the right of the
Falkland Islanders to self determination,'' he said, but ``that does
not mean there is nothing else to talk about.''
   Tickell cited fishing as a possible area of agreement with
Argentina, which calls the islands the Malvinas and claims to have
inherited the archipelago from Spain in 1810. Britain has ruled the
islands since 1833.
   About 1,000 men were lost on both sides in the war, most of them
when the British sank the Argentine cruise General Belgrano.
Argentina has not yet declared a formal end to hostilities and
diplomatic relations have not been restored.
   About 2,000 people live on the islands. Most are fishermen or
raise sheep.
</TEXT>
