<1ST_LINE>u i AM-OAS-HumanRights     11-17 0533</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-OAS-Human Rights,0556</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chile Rejects Criticism in Human Rights Report</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGIO CARRASCO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Chilean envoy on Thursday
attacked a human rights report that accuses his country's military
of burning two civilians with gasoline and questions Chile's
progress toward democracy.
   The report by the Inter-American Human Rights Commission focuses
on human rights abuses in Latin America and also singles out Cuba,
El Salvador, Guatemala, Nicaragua and Paraguay.
   Delegates of 31 nations in the Organization of American States
received the report during their meeting Wednesday in San Salvador.
   The commission declared the Chilean government of Gen. Augusto
Pinochet ``responsible for the death of Rodrigo Rojas and grave
injuries of Carmen Gloria Quintana when they were burned by a
military patrol in July 1986.''
   According to the report, the soldiers doused the pair with
gasoline, set them on fire, and left them at the roadside.
   The military said the two were throwing firebombs. But human
rights groups and relatives of Ms. Quintana and Rojas said they were
innocent bystanders. The case has attracted international attention.
   The report also said Pinochet's defeat in a yes-or-no
presidential referendum on Oct. 5 represented ``a positive fact.''
However, it said the loss ``does not imply the installment of an
authentic democratic system.''
   Pinochet, who came to power in a September 1973 coup, lost his
bid to extend his presidency until 1997. The opposition is calling
for early elections to end military rule.
   Chile's OAS Ambassador, Javier Illanes, said the commission had
not given Chile credit for trying to end abuses.
   ``It seems to us the commission was only interested in negative
aspects and didn't give importance to the progress of democracy,''
he said.
   The report also criticized communist-ruled Cuba, where it said
political prisoners received long sentences under harsh prison
conditions. There was no immediate reaction from Cuban officials.
   In El Salvador, the report found ``an increase in the activities
of the so-called death squads'' that stalk victims for political
ends.
   However, Benjamin Cestoni, president of the Salvadoran
government's human rights commission, said Thursday the report was
unfair because it failed to reflect ``the damage from terrorist
groups.''
   El Salvador has been using U.S. support to fight a nine-year
civil war against leftist guerrillas.
   In Nicaragua, the commission reported ``advances, although
precarious'' stemming from a March cease-fire pact between the
leftist Sandinista government and U.S.-backed rebels who fought for
seven years.
   But the commission criticized the Sandinistas for repression of
an opposition demonstration in July and ``serious violations of the
rights'' of several opposition activists.
   Deputy Foreign Minister Victor Hugo Tinoco of Nicaragua said his
government was satisfied because the report reflected the
difficulties imposed by the civil war.
   The OAS General Assembly will vote Saturday on whether to accept
the report.
   Sonia Sgambatti, president of the group's Inter-American
Commission for the Control of Drug Abuse, also told delegates to the
conference Thursday that drugs are the biggest criminal problem in
the history of the Western Hemisphere.
   She credited several nations, including the United States,
Colombia, Bolivia and Mexico, for their anti-drug efforts during the
past year.
   Sgambatti also called for quicker extradition of drug suspects
among member nations.
</TEXT>
