<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Canada 1stLd-Writethru a0664 11-17 0801</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Canada, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0664,0826</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mulroney Campaigning Hard in Home Province</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 14 grafs, quote from Reagan speech and Broadbent
comment; PICKS up 11th pvs `But in'</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Brian Mulroney desperately needs
to sweep his native province of Quebec to win a majority government
Monday and preserve the free trade agreement he signed with
President Reagan.
   Pressed hard by opposition allegations that he sold Canada out,
Mulroney has promoted the deal as the ``passport to prosperity,'' an
``instrument of economic expansion.''
   He tells crowds the choice is a simple one between ``John the
Ripper'' _ Liberal Party leader John Turner _ and ``Brian the
Builder.''
   Mulroney strives to portray Turner as an anti-American who
opposes progress, and points to the prosperity of his four years in
office.
   ``The cause of my life is to build a nation,'' he says.
   Ed Broadbent, leader of the socialist New Democratic Party, said
Reagan's remarks Thursday about the free trade agreement will hurt
Mulroney.
   ``It will remind every Canadian how close Brian Mulroney is to
Ronald Reagan,'' said Broadbent, whose party is expected to finish
third. ``It will remind every Canadian the Americans got virtually
everything they wanted in this deal.''
   Reagan said in a speech to the U.S. Chamber of Commerce in
Washington: ``As far as the United States is concerned, the Free
Trade Agreement is an example of cooperation at its best. It is a
testament to the commitment of our two governments to the principles
of the open market and to economic cooperation.''
   Opponents of the agreement had said the Reagan speech could be
interpreted as interference in Canadian affairs.
   Mulroney's Progressive Conservative Party must win 148 of the 295
seats to ensure the agreement takes effect Jan. 1, eliminating
tariffs between the world's two largest trading partners over a
10-year period.
   It has been approved by Congress but has yet to be considered by
Parliament.
   Quebec has 75 seats in the House of Commons, second only as a
bloc to the 99 seats of Ontario, where opposition is stronger.
   The free trade debate has dominated the campaign since Mulroney
dissolved Parliament on Oct. 1.
   At the time, he appeared headed for an easy victory. The
Liberals, long a dominant force in Canadian politics, had sagged to
what seemed to be a battle with the New Democrats for runner-up
status.
   But in a matter of weeks, Turner's persistent attacks on the free
trade agreement as a threat to Canadian sovereignty and identity
have revived his chances. Polls indicate that more Canadians oppose
the agreement than support it.
   The polls also put the Liberals and Progressive Conservatives in
a dead heat.
   Support for free trade has been strongest in French-speaking
Quebec, secure in its cultural identity, but Turner has by no means
conceded the province.
   The opposition leader was in Montreal on Wednesday night and
charged the prime minister is willing to sacrifice textile workers,
garment workers, food workers and farmers ``on the altar of free
trade.''
   At Mulroney's major campaign rally Wednesday night in a working
class district of East Montreal, protesters' signs read: ``Mulroney
for Governor of the 51st State'' and ``Canada for the Canadians.''
   The prime minister responded with the shout that the pact ``is
good for Quebec, and it is good for Canada!''
   Mulroney is expected to do well throughout rural Quebec. Because
of its strong cultural identity, there is little reason to fear the
pact could bring in an overwhelming U.S. presence.
   The province also has a strong entrepreneurial bent that has
helped fuel prosperity in the 1980s. Quebec's prime minister, Robert
Bourassa, is a leading supporter of the free trade agreement even
though he is a Liberal.
   But polls indicate Montreal will be more hotly contested that the
rest of the province.
   During his campaign, Mulroney has spoken of the 175,000 new jobs
in Montreal since his landslide victory in 1984, 345,000 new jobs in
the province, and 1.3 million new jobs across Canada.
   Mulroney comes from a working class background in Baie-Comeau on
Quebec's north shore. He is the first French-speaking Quebecer to
lead the Conservative Party and is greeted here with shouts of
``Brian, Brian!''
   Turner scored points in the French-language debate with his
unexpectedly strong attack on the free trade agreement, but Mulroney
speaks French with a fluency his rivals can't match.
   He jokes with the crowds and moves about with ease, and he
dismisses as ``scare mongering'' anti-free trade people who say the
agreement will cost Canada too much.
   Mulroney and other supporters maintain Canada is mature enough to
compete efficiently with its powerful southern neighbor.
   The prime minister will spend the weekend on a final campaign
swing through Quebec, ending up in Baie-Comeaue for election day.
</TEXT>
