<1ST_LINE>r w AM-AnimalDrugs     11-17 0399</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Animal Drugs,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Accuses 12 Of Illegal Animal Drug Importing and
Distributing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department announced Thursday that
two people have been indicted and 10 others accused of illegally
importing and distributing unapproved drugs for animals.
   As part of the investigation, which began in 1984, the government
also seized more than 30 tons of allegedly adulterated and
misbranded animal drugs valued at more than $600,000. The seizures
occurred in Rushville, Ill., and Omaha, Neb.
   The drugs were for distribution to veterinarians, farm supply
outlets and farmers throughout the country.
   A 25-count indictment against Heinz G. Dall of Ossining, N.Y.,
and Robert M. Clack of Pittsfield, Ill., accuses them of illegally
importing and distributing animal drugs and drug products in
violation of the animal drug provisions of the federal Food, Drug
and Cosmetic Act. A federal grand jury in Cedar Rapids, Iowa,
returned the indictment Wednesday.
   The indictment alleges that from May 1983 to October 1988, Dall,
Clack and others conspired to illegally import drugs intended for
animal use into the United States from Canada in violation of
customs laws and the Food, Drug and Cosmetic Act.
   The indictment alleges that neither Clack nor Dall were
authorized to receive or to distribute the drugs because neither
they nor wholesalers who bought their drugs held government-approved
new animal drug applications as required by federal law.
   The Food, Drug and Cosmetic Act requires that all drugs intended
for use in animals have an approved new animal drug application
prior to U.S. marketing.
   On Thursday, the government filed a three-count felony
information against Jeffrey A. Engel of Omaha, Neb., the former
president and general manager of the now-defunct Custom Feed
Blenders of Fort Dodge, Iowa.
   Engel is charged with conspiring to violate customs laws and the
Food, Drug and Cosmetic Act, using false statements and practices to
import merchandise and failing to register a drug manufacturing
facility.
   The government this week also filed misdemeanor informations in
Omaha, Neb., against Dana Wolf, Timothy Hoffman and International
Manufacturing and Sales, all of Omaha; ZetaPharm Corp. of New York,
N.Y.; Ronald Nissen and Rex Blunk, both of Fort Dodge, Iowa; and Wes
Thoreson of Jewel, Iowa. In Cedar Rapids, Iowa, the government filed
charges against Lawrence Tipton and James Rhodes, both of Fort
Dodge, Iowa, and against Gregory and Bradley Langmo, both of
Litchfield, Minn.
</TEXT>
