<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Diabetics-Blindness 1stLd-Writethru a077erofWallStreetJournal
11-17 0492</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Diabetics-Blindness, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0777,0501</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Diabetics With Good Blood-Sugar Control Much More Likely To Keep
Eyesight</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: RECASTS 6th graf, `Insulin, usually...' to DELETE incorrect
reference to intravenous injections; picks up 7th graf,
`Older-onset...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA C. COLEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Diabetics who are able to control their
blood-sugar levels well are much more likely to keep their eyesight
than those whose levels are poorly controlled, a study to be
published Friday suggests.
   Thousands of people with diabetes go blind each year because of a
condition linked to the disease called retinopathy, in which tiny
blood vessels at the back of the eye break and bleed, usually
painlessly and over a period of years.
   The condition afflicts both people who get diabetes as adults and
those who get it at younger ages, say researchers at the University
of Wisconsin, who studied both groups over a four-year interval.
More than 1,800 diabetics participated in the study.
   The researchers used blood sugar-levels to divide subjects into
four categories and found that those in the highest-level category
developed signs of retinopathy almost twice as often as subjects in
the lowest category.
   This was true of all subjects taking insulin, whether they got
the disease before or after age 30, the researchers reported in
Friday's Journal of the American Medical Association.
   Insulin, usually administered by injection, helps the body use
sugar and other carbohydrates.
   Older-onset diabetics _ those developing the disease at or over
age 30 _ who were not taking insulin showed an even greater
disparity, with retinopathy appearing four times as often among the
highest blood-sugar category compared with the lowest, the
researchers found.
   Dr. Barbara E.K. Klein, professor of ophthalmology and a
co-author of the study, said Thursday, ``It suggests that ...
(non-hospitalized) people with higher levels are at higher risk.''
   But the study is too preliminary to use as a basis for changing
the way people manage blood-sugar levels, because tighter controls
can lead to serious medical complications, she said.
   Still, the findings suggest that even a modest improvement of
blood sugar control ``may reduce the incidence of proliferative
(advancing) retinopathy signficantly,'' they said.
   For example, the four-year risk of developing advancing
retinopathy among people with an 11 percent reading for glycosylated
hemoglobin, a blood-sugar test, was estimated to be roughly double
that of people with a reading of 9 percent, they said.
   Regardless of blood-sugar levels, 59 percent of the younger-onset
diabetics developed some signs of retinopathy over the four-year
period, the researchers said. In the older-onset group taking
insulin, the rate was 47.4 percent. In the older-onset group not
taking insulin, the rate was 34.4 percent, the researchers said.
   In an editorial accompanying the study, Drs. Michael P. Stern and
Steven M. Haffner of the University of Texas Health Science Center
at San Antonio, said the new findings provide persuasive evidence
that blood-sugar control is positively associated with the risk of
developing initial or advancing retinopathy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
