<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     11-17 0424</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0435</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Utah Hit By Snow Storm</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Snow hit Utah hard Thursday as another in a series of storms to
cross the western United States dumped up to 9 inches in some
regions.
   Snow warnings and advisories were in effect in portions of
Wyoming, Colorado, Idaho, Montana, Nevada and Oregon.
   The storm that brought heavy snow to parts of the West earlier in
the week was producing rain along the Atlantic Coast on Thursday.
Showers and isolated thunderstorms extended from New England to
coastal North Carolina.
   There were numerous reports of small tornadoes and waterspouts
over the northern beaches and Currituck Sound of North Carolina. A
small tornado was reported at Point Harbor. A trailer was blown over
and several buildings were unroofed.
   Sunny skies prevailed across much of the rest of the nation east
of the Mississippi River.
   Low pressure centered over southern James Bay in Canada continued
to produce strong and gusty winds in the Great Lakes region. Gale
warnings were in effect in the afternoon for Lakes Huron, Erie and
Ontario.
   Unseasonably warm weather prevailed ahead of the cold front
crossing the Atlantic Coast region. Temperatures were in the 80s
over the Florida peninsula and in the 70s from northeast Florida to
coastal North Carolina.
   Unseasonably cold temperatures extended across the north central
United States with readings in the teens from northern Montana to
western Minnesota.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 11
degrees at Williston, N.D., to 90 degrees in Fort Myers, Fla.
   The nation's low Thursday morning was -7 at Glasgow, Mont.
   Friday's forecast called for a storm system crossing the central
United States to spread snow from the plateau region across the
northern and central high Plains into Minnesota with heavy snow
expected in the mountains. Rain showers and thunderstorms were to
scatter from the Gulf Coast region to the middle Mississippi Valley
and the central Plains. Fair to partly sunny skies were forecast for
the rest of the nation. Windy conditions were expected over the
southern Rockies.
   Temperatures were expected to remain below 40 degrees from
northern Arizona and the northern and central plateau region to
Upper Michigan and across northern Maine with subfreezing
temperatures over Montana, Wyoming and North Dakota. Warmer
temperatures were expected into the 60s in Southern California and
into the 60s and 70s from the Rio Grande Valley of Texas through the
lower Mississippi Valley to the southern Atlantic Coast with highs
in the 80s over extreme southern Texas and the Florida peninsula.
</TEXT>
