<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Britain-Iraq     11-17 0274</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Iraq,0280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Britain Expels Three Iraqi Embassy Personnel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Foreign Office spokesman said Thursday night that
Britain expelled three members of the Iraqi Embassy in London for
activities incompatible with their status, a diplomatic expression
for spying.
   Iraq retaliated by expelling three member of the British Embassy
in Baghdad and the three Britons have returned home, he said.
   The spokesman, who in accordance with British practice refused to
let his name be used, said the Iraqis were told on Oct. 18 they must
leave and were given two weeks to do so. ``I believe they have
left,'' he said.
   No immediate explanation was offered as to why the announcement
of the expulsions was delayed until Thursday night, 16 days after
the Nov. 1 expiration of the time limit set for the departure of the
three Iraqis.
   The spokesman identified the three expelled Iraqis as Abdul
Hassain S. Jbara, an assistant press counselor; Ghassan Mohammed
Shagir, a third secretary; and Samir Karim Hussain Mahdi, the
chauffeur of Ambassador Mohammed Sadiq Al-Mashat.
   He identified the three Britons expelled from Iraq as Charles
Hollis, a second secretary; Simon Elvy, a visa officer; and John
Barton, a security officer. He said all three had been exactly what
they purported to be, namely diplomats.
   There was no immediate reaction from Iraqi authorities to the
Foreign Office announcement.
   Relations between the two governments have been unmarked by any
recent upsets. Earlier this year, Iraqi President Saddam Hussein
thanked Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher for Britain's support for a
plan sponsored by the United Nations that resulted in the present
cease-fire in the war between Iraq and Iran.
</TEXT>
