<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Bush-Geographic     11-17 0284</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-Geographic,270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Pledges To Use Leadership to Leave Earth a Better Place</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush pledged Thursday
night that his new administration will seek to leave a planet Earth
``in better shape than we found it.''
   The president-elect, in a toast at the centennial banquet of the
National Geographic Society, said, ``The only path to a cleaner,
safer planet is global cooperation on the environment.''
   ``The plain fact is many of the problems we face in the
environment _ global warming, ocean pollution, acid rain _ are
international in nature,'' Bush told 1500 people at the black tie
banquet.
   ``I plan to use America's leadership in the world as a force for
leaving the planet in better shape than we found it.''
   The society, publisher of National Geographic magazine, producer
of television specials and sponsor of far-flung explorations,
presented centennial awards to 15 famous honorees, including
astronaut and senator John Glenn of Ohio, mountain climber Sir
Edmund Hilliary, underwater explorer Jacques-Yves Cousteau and
anthropologists Mary and Richard Leakey. Each honoree also received
$10,000.
   The award winners issued a joint plea to do more to ``save this
fragile Earth.''
   Bush said he shares the society's concerns about education and
the environment.
   ``Other cultures don't always see the world as we do and their
needs and their attitudes are differnt...,'' he said.
   ``I support wholeheartedly the National Geographic's efforts to
teach America about the world around us.''
   He said the society has brought ``to armchair explorers the
wonders of distant discoveries, exotic customs, breathtaking natural
sights.''
   ``The Geographic's love of the planet Earth just leaps from every
page. That little yellow-bordered magazine is truly a window on our
world.''
</TEXT>
