<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Yugoslavia 1stLd-Writethru a0761 11-17 0599</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yugoslavia, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0761,0617</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>10,000 March in Protest As Communist Feuds Rock Yugoslavia</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout, UPDATING with resignations accepted, protest
dispersed, details. Adds byline. No pickup</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto KOS1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SLOBODAN LEKIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 10,000 people marched in
sub-freezing weather to protest the resignations Thursday of the
Kosovo Communist Party president and another top official in this
restive province.
   It was believed to be the biggest protest in Kosovo since bloody
riots in 1981.
   Some estimates put the crowd at 20,000.
   Kacusa Jasari, president of the Kosovo Communist party, and Azem
Vlasi, her predecessor and a member of the powerful party presidium,
announced their resignations at a meeting of the provincial
Communist leadership Thursday.
   The presidium approved both resignations, the state Tanjug news
agency reported. It said Remzi Koljgeci, also an ethnic Albanian,
would act as president until the next session. No date was given.
   The two ethnic Albanian leaders were the main target of
resignation demands by Slobodan Milosevic, Communist Party chief of
the Serbian republic, in his drive to bring Kosovo under tighter
Serbian control.
   Protesters marched through Pristina, Kosovo's capital, chanting
support for Jasari and Vlasi and bearing portraits of the late
President Jozip Broz Tito.
   They chanted ``Unity! Fraternity!,'' ``Long live Kacusa
Jasari!,'' ``We shall not yield Azem Vlasi!'' and slogans against
Milosevic.
   Jasari and Vlasi addressed protesters packed into a sports hall,
reassuring them the two would stay in the top leadership and
appealing for peace.
   Jasari said she would step down as head of the 13-member Kosovo
presidium, but would remain a member of the body, Tanjug reported.
   Vlasi announced his resignation from the Kosovo presidium in
compliance with a recent decision of the federal party presidium
prohibiting its Central Committee members from simultaneously
holding membership in local party bodies, Tanjug said. Vlasi is on
the national party Central Committee.
   The resignations brought to seven the number of top Kosovo party
leaders who said they were stepping down after Serbian and
provincial Communist leaders clashed at a meeting this month over
Serbian demands for a purge of Kosovo's ruling elite.
   Milosevic has been backed by rallies attended by hundreds of
thousands of Serbs in recent months.
   Slavs in Kosovo claim they are being harassed and forced to
emigrate by the ethnic Albanian majority.
   Although administratively part of Serbia, Kosovo enjoys wide
autonomy under Yugoslavia's 1974 constitution, which was adopted
under Tito and created a loose confederation of six republics and
two provinces.
   The constitution is seen by many as a main cause of Yugoslavia's
present ethnic and economic woes, since it leaves central power weak.
   The march and a demonstration Thursday by about 4,000 miners
indicated the Kosovo party leadership enjoys wide support among
ethnic Albanians who make up about 90 percent of Kosovo's
population. The miners marched to Pristina from the Titova Mitrovica
lead mines, 31 miles away, to protest the resignations.
   Milosevic's supporters have repeatedly claimed the Kosovo party
leadership lacks majority support.
   They said the provincial leadership could not cope with Albanian
nationalism left simmering since 1981, when ethnic clashes left at
least nine people dead.
   According to Tanjug, windows were shattered at the offices of the
Belgrade-based daily Vecernje Novosti, but no other incidents were
reported.
   By about 10 p.m., most of the crowd had dispersed.
   In another development Thursday, workers of the country's major
cotton yarn manufacturer Djuro Salaj of Mostar, in western
Yugoslavia, walked out demanding a 60 percent pay increase, Tanjug
reported.
   The plant employs about 6,000 workers. Average monthly salary for
a worker is about $61.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
