<1ST_LINE>u a AM-PosingPrince     11-17 0771</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Posing Prince,0797</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Deputies Dethrone High School `Prince'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES HANNAH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DAYTON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Students at Meadowdale High School thought a
classmate was the Crown Prince of Morocco until police learned that
the sporty red car he drove was stolen and he didn't have his royal
father's telephone number to call for help.
   Michael W. Taylor, 28, of Louisville, Ky., was in
Dayton-Montgomery County Jail after being charged Wednesday in Ohio
with receiving stolen property. A Kentucky grand jury on Thursday
indicted him on two counts of theft by deception.
   Students say the flashy foreign-exchange student they knew as
17-year-old Prince Sparkle Shannon dressed in the latest fashions
and wore gold jewelry around his neck and a diamond ring. He spurned
school buses in favor of a red 1988 Dodge Daytona car and reportedly
once rented a chauffeured limousine to take him to a Meadowdale
football game.
   ``I can't believe it,'' said freshman Shamika Bohanon. ``He could
dress. It seemed like he had on a different pair of shoes every
day.''
   Taylor was the subject of an article in the school newspaper, and
during a recent lecture for the student leadership club told
students he would inherit the Moroccan throne when King Hassan II
died. He also told students he had studied with the KGB in the
Soviet Union last year, school officials said.
   But the royal act began to unravel Monday when Madison Township
police detective Rick Wright spotted Taylor's car, which was bearing
Kentucky license plates, in the school parking lot. He ran a check
and learned it had been stolen.
   Wright said he and other police officers waited until Taylor got
into the car with a female companion and then stopped the vehicle.
   ``Do you know who that is?'' Wright said the girl told the
officers. ``That's the prince of Morocco.''
   Wright said at that point school officials and security guards
confronted them.
   ``That kid is the prince of Morocco,'' Wright quoted one school
official as saying. ``What are you going to do to him? You're going
to start an international incident right here in our parking lot.''
   Wright said he took Taylor into the school and found that he knew
the capital of Morocco, the name of the prime minister and even the
date of the country's independence day. But the officer said Taylor
had no passport or immigration card.
   ``He was talking in a very Middle Eastern accent,'' Wright
recalled. He quoted Taylor as telling school officials: ``You mean
to tell me you let murderers go free in this country, and you're
going to let them lock me up for this?''
   Wright said he then asked Taylor to call his father on the
telephone.
   ``The king?'' Taylor asked.
   Wright said he took Taylor into custody after he said he left his
father's phone number at home.
   Montgomery County sheriff's detective Bob Weaver said Taylor, who
stands about 5 feet, 6 inches and weighs about 110 pounds, told
police his name was Monlay Rashid.
   But Weaver said everything changed when Taylor discovered police
knew his real identity.
   ``He was confronted with that, and basically he finally admitted
to being Michael Taylor,'' Weaver said. ``When we said, more or
less, `the game's over,' that's when he finally lost his Moroccan
accent.''
   Meadowdale Principal Ben Kirby said Taylor asked to enroll at the
high school in September, just days after classes had started.
Taylor told school officials his father wanted him to go to school
in Ohio and that he liked Dayton. He was enrolled as a senior.
   Kirby said he became suspicious when the student's high school
transcripts never arrived. The principal said Taylor had said he had
been staying with a host family by the name of Flagg, but he had no
additional information.
   Louisville police detective Ron Schultz said he arrested Taylor
last May on charges of obtaining a car under false pretenses.
Schultz said at that time Taylor gave his name as Nakita Vandiest
Shepard.
   ``He's nothing but a con artist; all indication is that he is,''
Schultz said. He expects Taylor to face numerous additional charges
in Kentucky.
   The charges Taylor faces in Dayton stem from the theft of a Dodge
Daytona from a Louisville car dealership last spring.
   Taylor could be sentenced to one to two years in prison and fined
up to $5,000 if convicted in Vandalia Municipal Court on the charge
of receiving stolen property. He was being held in the Dayton jail
in lieu of $7,500 cash bond.
   He also could be sentenced to one to five years on each count of
theft by deception.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
