<DOCNO> AP881117-0225 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-88 2144EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-Namibia     11-17 0459</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Namibia,0470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>General Assembly Calls For Namibia's Independence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The General Assembly on Thursday
overwhelmingly demanded that South Africa grant independence to
South-West Africa regardless of the presence of 50,000 Cuban troops
in neighboring Angola.
   The demand was part of a package of five resolutions that ask for
sanctions to punish South Africa for ruling South-West Africa, also
known as Namibia, and a program to implement the sanctions and press
for independence.
   A procession of 71 speakers came to the podium in debate that ran
from Monday through Thursday to castigate South Africa for occupying
South-West Africa in defiance of U.N. resolutions.
   Not one nation voted against any of the proposals, although the
United States, Western Europe, Japan, Israel, Australia and New
Zealand abstained on some. South Africa was stripped of its voting
rights in the United Nations in 1974.
   U.S. Ambassador Vernon A. Walters said the United States
abstained to maintain its neutrality while mediating peace talks
among South Africa, Cuba and Angola.
   South African, Cuban and Angolan negotiators tentatively agreed
this week during talks in Geneva that the Cubans will leave Angola
and South Africa will allow the United Nations to begin a one-year
independence plan for South-West Africa.
   If their governments ratify the accord, the Namibian idependence
process could begin early in 1989.
   Cuban troops have been in Angola since 1975 to defend that
country's Marxist government from raids by the UNITA rebel movement
_ the National Union for the Total Independence of Angola _ and its
ally, South Africa.
   South Africa has ruled Namibia for 73 years since Germany lost
the former colony during World War I. The League of Nations, the
United Nations' predecessor, subsequently granted South Africa a
mandate to administer Namibia.
   In 1966, the United Nations revoked the mandate. In 1978, the
Security Council passed Resolution 435, a one-year plan to set up a
constituent assembly to adopt a constitution and organize an
independent goverment.
   The resolutions passed Thursday call South Africa's occupation an
``act of aggression'' and demand prisoner-of-war treatment for
captured members of the South-West African People's Organization
(SWAPO), the guerrilla group fighting for independence.
   SWAPO is designated in the resolutions as the ``sole and
authentic representative of the Namibian people.'' For years SWAPO
has held non-voting observer status in the United Nations.
   Walters told the assembly that America objects to that
characterization, and said ``only free and democratic elections .. .
will provide the Namibian people themselves the opportunity to
choose whom they want as their representative.''
   The resolutions also call for mandantory economic sanctions
against South Africa, a step that Britain and the United States have
blocked before in the Security Council by using their veto power.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881117-0226 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-88 2154EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-NATO-Kohl     11-17 0392</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NATO-Kohl,0406</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Anti-NATO Protesters Fight West German Police</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HAMBURG, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chancellor Helmut Kohl said Thursday
that opposition to the North Atlantic Treaty Organization could grow
in Western Europe unless Washington rethinks its plans for
cost-sharing among members.
   Hours after he spoke at Hamburg's City Hall, about 8,000
opponents of NATO marched, fired flares and battled riot police to
bolster their demand that West Germany pull out of the military
alliance.
   Kohl made his comments before an independent 16-nation body of
lawmakers called the North Atlantic Assembly, which has been holding
its annual congress since Sunday. Protesters later fired flares at
the building and clashed with riot police nearby, but the delegates
had already ended the day's session.
   Several people were injured, and at least two demonstrators were
arrested, police said. No reports emerged of fire or damage.
   The marchers, mostly young, carried banners reading ``North
Atlantic Terror Organization,'' ``Get Out of NATO,'' and other
slogans.
   Some demonstrators threw stones at police as they moved in to
make arrests, said a police spokesman, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   Most demonstrators dispersed, but some remained and clashed with
riot police who were carrying shields and truncheons, witnesses
said. The remaining protesters later fled.
   Kohl told the North Atlantic Assembly that West Germany acts as
host to more than 400,000 allied soldiers on its soil and will
continue to fulfill its NATO obligations.
   But he added, ``We should also not overtax one another and
thereby conjure up the danger that acceptance of the alliance could
be damaged.''
   Kohl, a staunch supporter of the United States, has recently been
emphasizing that West Germans hesitate to accept greater financial
burdens within NATO.
   On Thursday, he broadened that message to include other nations
in the Western European alliance.
   His speech came amid growing sentiment in Washington that NATO
allies in Western Europe should shoulder a greater defense burden.
   West Germans, however, argue that other kinds of national
contributions to NATO should be taken into account. They say they
should get credit for putting up with military hardware and soldiers
on their territory.
   The chancellor ruled out removing NATO short-range nuclear
weapons deployed in West Germany. U.S. officials worry pressure to
scrap the weapons could mount among West Germans who view the Soviet
Union as a decreasing military threat.
</TEXT>
