<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Greece-US     11-17 0261</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Greece-US,0270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Anarchists Fight Police Outside American Embassy in Athens</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Riot police swung clubs and fired tear gas
Thursday at hundreds of anarchists who hurled sticks and stones at
them outside the U.S. Embassy, witnesses said.
   Police said they made at least 10 arrests. No injuries were
reported.
   The anarchists arrived at the embassy at the conclusion of a
march by 20,000 demonstrators who were marking the 15th anniversary
of a student uprising against the 1967-74 military dictatorship in
Greece.
   The peaceful march started at Polytechnic University, site of the
Nov. 17, 1973 rebellion which was crushed by troops and tanks. It
ended at the fenced embassy compound on Vasillis Sophias Avenue, a
main boulevard, where protesters shouted, ``Americans, murderers of
the people, get out now!''
   After march participants left the embassy area, the anarchists
began to battle police.
   More than 20 young people were killed in the 1973 student
uprising, which is credited with triggering the military regime's
collapse.
   The annual march to the U.S. Embassy reflects a widely held
belief that U.S. support enabled the colonels to remain in power.
   The demonstrators chanted slogans urging Premier Andreas
Papandreou's socialist government to remove four U.S. military bases
that have operated in Greece since the early 1950s.
   The Polytechnic uprising anniversary is generally treated as a
national holiday, with politicans from all parties laying wreaths
beside a sculpture dedicated to the slain youths.
   But this year leading politicians, including Papandreou and
Constantinos Mitsotakis, leader of the main opposition New Democracy
party, did not attend the commemorations.
</TEXT>
