<HEAD>Former Navy Radioman Charged Under Espionage Statute</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FAYETTEVILLE, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Navy communications specialist
pleaded innocent Thursday to charges he violated federal espionage
laws by possessing classified documents, authorities said.
   Henry Otto Spade, 24, of Mountain Home, likely did not disclose
information from the two classified documents. The documents, if
released, would pose ``a grave danger to United States security,''
U.S. Attorney Mike Fitzhugh said.
   One document is a cryptographic key card, which gives a list of
codes needed to decipher scrambled communications; no information
was released concerning the second document. Spade was arrested
following a tip to police.
   Spade entered his plea before U.S. District Court Judge H.
Franklin Waters and was released on $25,000 bond.
   Spade could be sentenced to up to 10 years in prison and fined up
to $250,000.
   Spade, who is unemployed, had served as a radioman and a
communications specialist in the U.S. Navy. He was honorably
discharged in April after four years and seven months of service.
</TEXT>
