<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MissingTeen-Agers 2ndLd-Writethru a0802 11-17 0595</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Missing Teen-Agers, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0802,0611</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Missing Teens Found Dead in Submerged Car</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 5th, `The car...' to UPDATE with
controversy over whether a barrier was in place; picks up 6th graf
pvs, `A crane...'; ADDS 2 grafs at end to UPDATE with memorial
service Thursday night.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos NWD1; NWD2, HF2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEAN GOLEMBESKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A car containing what authorities
believed were the bodies of four young people missing since last
weekend was found Thursday on the bottom of a murky river, police
said.
   A detour sign on the road incorrectly directs traffic to the dead
end where the accident occurred. A second sign warns of danger ahead.
   The three women and one man, ages 19 and 20, were last seen by
their parents about 7 p.m. Saturday, when they left their hometown
of East Lyme for an evening in New Haven.
   Autopsy reports were pending, but police Lt. James Sorrentino
said it was likely the four victims were the missing young people.
   The car approached an open swing bridge and went into the water
over a barrier blocking the roadway, Sorrentino said. Others said
the bridge, which swings from side to side, had been in an open
position for several years.
   Several news reports, quoting unnamed sources, said no barriers
were in place blocking the road on the night of the accident. A
service station owner said that a wooden barrier normally blocks the
roadway, which was cordoned off by police Thursday.
   ``I have no information either way,'' Sorrentino said. ``I've
been led to believe the barriers were always there.''
   A crane was used to pull the car from the water, while some
family members waited in a police van.
   Police have determined the four spent at least part of Saturday
night drinking illegally at a bar near Yale University, said state
police Detective Andre Trudelle. An employee of the bar told
authorities they left together about 3 a.m. Sunday, Trudelle said.
   The legal drinking age in Connecticut is 21.
   ``They were good kids. I can't picture them being drunk and
driving,'' said Michelle Funaioli, who said she was at a New Haven
bar last Thursday with Michael Gallo, one of the missing.
   The missing women were identified as Jill Sawyer, 19, a student
at the University of Rhode Island; Christy Stevens, 19, a student at
Mohegan Community College in Norwich; and Laura Lagrotteria, 19.
   ``It's horrible. It's the most horrible thing I've ever seen
happen,'' Ms. Funaioli said.
   Police divers found the car submerged in about 15 feet of water
in the Mill River, in a little-traveled, old and industrial part of
the city, just north of the New Haven harbor, police said.
   The bridge has been closed for several years because of roadwork
in the area, business owners said.
   There were no skid marks at the scene, and police said an
investigation would determine if the car was speeding.
   Family and friends described the four former high school buddies
as responsible adults unlikely to take off without telling anyone.
   They were last seen by their parents Saturday evening, when they
left for an evening in New Haven.
   The parents had distributed pictures of the missing and offered a
$25,000 reward.
   Thursday night, about 200 friends and relatives of the victims
packed a Niantic church for a prayer service.
   ``There are no words to take away your pain,'' said Assistant
Pastor Laurie Whinnem Etter. ``The only way to respond is to
celebrate the love and the joy that these friends shared.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
