<DOCNO> AP881117-0231 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-88 2215EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Chile     11-17 0423</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chile,0440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pinochet Rejects Changes Urged For Transition To Democracy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Military President Augusto Pinochet firmly
rejected on Thursday opposition calls for constitutional changes
before Chile's return to elected civilian rule in 1990.
   He said the reforms urged by dissidents would ``undermine the
basic structure'' of the constitution .
   Pinochet's lame-duck government had hinted this week at talks
with the opposition that beat him in an Oct. 5 referendum on
extending his rule until 1997.
   In a speech at a luncheon with supporters in Punta Arenas, 1,550
miles south of Santiago, Pinochet said his right-wing government is
prepared for a ``constructive exchange of ideas'' with the
opposition, ``but within the present legislation.''
   ``The opposition, under the pretext of improving the
constitution, aims at the destruction of the new institutionality,''
Pinochet said, referring to the 1980 military-written constitution.
   The text of the speech was carried by the state-run news agency
Orbe.
   Under the constitution, Pinochet's referendum defeat makes an
open presidential election mandatory in December 1989, with Pinochet
handing power over to the winner in March 1990.
   Pinochet has rejected demands for his earlier departure from
power.
   He has ruled since leading a 1973 military coup toppled the
elected government of Marxist President Salvador Allende, who died
during the overthrow.
   After their referendum victory, opposition parties listed
constitutional changes they said were needed for a fast, smooth
transitition to democracy.
   The list included eliminating one article that bans Marxist
parties; changing another that makes one third of the future
36-member senate appointed instead of elected, and reforming the
composition of a military-dominated National Security Council. The
opposition sees this council as a permanent threat to future
civilian government.
   The opposition also wants easier rules and lower quorums for
changing the constitution in the future.
   Pinochet rejected all the demands, one by one.
   ``Opening a space to Communists in the political system means
giving them the faculty to use democracy to destroy democracy,''
Pinochet said.
   He warned he will be ``adamant'' in rejecting that, ``because the
freedom of Chileans cannot be the subject of negotiations or
compromise.''
   He said he cannot accept easing the procedures for future
constitutional amendments, because ``the fundamental charter, which
is the basis of democracy, cannot be left exposed to occasional
political majorities or temporary electoral pacts.''
   Pinochet said that reducing the military presence in the security
council would mean ``again isolating the armed forces'' from the
rest of society.
   ``The armed forces have a professional role, but within the
national reality, not outside it,'' Pinochet said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
