<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ChopSuey     11-17 0557</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chop Suey,0570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Says Chop Suey's First U.S. Arrival In SF</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHLEEN MACLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge who heard almost as many versions of
the U.S. origins of chop suey as there are characters in the Chinese
alphabet, sampled a a plate piled high with the stuff and on
Thursday issued his ruling.
   San Francisco, of course.
   Municipal Court Judge George T. Choppelas, presiding over a mock
Court of Historical Review and Appeals, ruled the vegetable, meat
and noodle dish described as ``Chinese soul food'' and first made
with ``anything that crawled or moved'' appeared on a Gold Rush-era
San Francisco table about 1850. That was 30 years before it found
its way to New York's Chinatown menus.
   The tongue-in-cheek court has decided other questions such as who
invented spaghetti, where the first martini was mixed and whether
the panic instilled by Orson Welles' 1938 broadcast about a Martian
invasion could happen today.
   Choppelas said his finding was supported by both oral history
handed down through generations of Chinese-American families in
Northern California and a story of its origins with elements of
life-or-death necessity and cunning business wiles.
   The story came from witness Annie Soo, secretary of the San
Francisco-based Chinese Historical Society of America. She testified
that according to family legend, her husband's grandfather was
working at a San Francisco Chinese boardinghouse around 1848 when a
band of drunken, hungry miners unable to find any restaurants open
stormed the rooming house.
   When the house owner said he didn't have any food left, Soo said
one of the miners aimed a gun at his head and threatened him. His
imagination ignited, the owner returned to the kitchen and hastily
assembled a dish of vegetables and discarded meat entrails. Heaped
on a bed of steaming rice, the slap-dash dish was served to an
appreciative group.
   ``That whole group enjoyed it very much,'' Soo said. One of the
miners asked what the dish was called, ``The boardinghouse owner
said, `Oh, chop suey.'''
   Choppelas said the quick-thinking owner not only saved his own
life, but gained some loyal customers.
   Soo's story was supported by Alon Yu of Berkeley, owner and
partner in the China Station restaurant and Imperial Palace and
Tommy Toy's in San Francisco.
   A fourth-generation Californian, Yu said his family came to
Northern California from China during the Gold Rush. Yu said many
frugal Chinese people working in mining towns survived on leftovers
from mine owners and were forced to eat ``whatever crawled or
moved.''
   Chop suey, what Yu called ``Chinese soul food,'' is likely to
have originated from these humble beginnings in California and not
in New York, where large numbers of Chinese later immigrated, he
said.
   Disputing that theory was former New Yorker and publicist Ivan
Cutler, who admitted that he and lawyer Jeff Brown had difficulty
deciding if Cutler was the ``su-or or the suey'' in this culinary
case.
   Chop suey came to New York in the 1850s, Cutler said, when a
visiting Chinese dignitary dined with President Grover Cleveland at
the Waldorf Astoria. Because of a sensitive stomach, the dignitary
declined the American-style feast and instead had his own chefs whip
something up for him _ chop suey.
   Choppelas quipped that New Yorkers like to claim everything good,
but noted, ``They don't call it Waldorf suey.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881117-0234 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-88 2241EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-Afghan     11-17 0631</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Afghan,0648</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Report Says Afghan Human Rights Situation Improves</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   UNITED NATIONS _ A U.N. report said Thursday that the human
rights situation in Afghanstan improved somewhat in
government-controlled areas, but it said acts of terrorism by rebels
increased in the past year.
   The 37-page annual human rights report on Afghanistan said that
while the Geneva Agreements, signed April 14, ``give grounds for
hope, the special rapporteur (the person assigned to prepare the
report) has still not been able to report any improvement in the
human rights situation within the country.
   ``Acts of war are continuing, violations of human rights are at
least as frequent as in the past, affecting particularly the
civilian population and endangering the lives and security of
innocent men, women and children.''
   The rapporteur, Felix Ermacora of Austria, is the special
investigator of the Afghan human rights situation for the U.N. Human
Rights Commission, based in Geneva.
   A similar report last year said the main problem in realizating
human rights there was the presence of more than 100,000 Soviet
troops. Half of them have been withdrawn under U.N.-mediated
agreements signed in Geneva.
   The rest are to be pulled out by Feb. 15, although Moscow has
suspended its withdrawal because of increasing attacks by
U.S.-backed and Pakistan-based rebels.
   The report said, ``In general, there is greater improvement in
the human rights situation in government-controlled areas. However,
allegations of torture and ill-treatment of prisoners on remand
(awaiting trial) and political prisoners are still being received,''
he said. Afghan authorities reject the allegations.
   Ermacora said the number of political prisoners has fallen
sharply as a result of anmnesty decress and other measures under the
Afghan government policy of national reconciliation. Conditions of
detention in Pol-i-Charkhi prison, a major center, have improved, it
said.
   But the investigator also said that after the signing of the
Geneva Agreements, which Afghan rebels rejected, ``acts of terrorism
... have caused many deaths among innocent civilians.''
   ``Terrorism in Afghanistan and Pakistan has multipled,'' since
his report last year, he said.
   The report cited government reports of rebel violence from April
to last August. It said heavy artillery and ground-to-ground
missiles were used against towns and villages, charitable
institutions and mosques. The report cited 4,154 cases of missile
firings and 24 explosions, killing 945 civilians and wounding 1,895,
including 187 children and 98 women.
   It said a rocket attack on Kabul Airport killed nine civilians on
Sept. 1 and wounded 20. On Sept.27, a rocket attack on a Kabul
neighborhood reportedly killed 35 civilians.
   Afghan refugees in Pakistan, it said, still are afraid to return
home, largely because of rebel-planted mines.
   The report said withdrawing Soviet troops had committed human
rights violations and it cited reports of Soviet bombing and
bombardment of civilian areas.
   On March 7, it said, Soviet artillery bombarded residential areas
in the suburbs of Herat, at the end of April migrating nomads were
attacked by Soviet and Afghan troops and houses, schools and mosques
were damaged and destroyed in other Soviet attacks.
   ``Many Afghan villages and houses have been destroyed in the
course of the Soviet troop withdrawal and many civilians have been
killed due to the fighting tactics of the oppostion movements and
acts of retaliation,'' the report said.
   The U.N. report said treatment of prisoners of war violates the
1949 Geneva Conventions. Prisoners are used as a means of barganing
and exchange, it said.
   The whereabouts of at least 313 Soviet soldiers missing in action
is still unknown, it said. The Afghan government considers rebels to
be terrorists and not combatants to be treated in accordance with
international humanitarian law, it said.
   The report said the International Committee of the Red Cross
should be given full access to all prisons and detention centers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881117-0235 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-88 2244EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Smokeout 1stLd-Writethru a0700 11-17 0904</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Smokeout, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0700,0929</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Millions Try To Kick the Habit for Great American Smokeout</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 15 grafs to UPDATE with other events from the day;
picks up 16th graf pvs, `Businesses and...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LARRY RYCKMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Millions of smokers on Thursday swapped their cigarettes for
apples and gum, went cold turkey for free turkey sandwiches and
tossed their tobacco into bonfires as part of the 12th annual Great
American Smokeout.
   Newborns in several hospitals wore ``I'm a Born Non-Smoker'' city
workers in Cedar Rapids, Iowa, sported pins and stickers that said,
``Kiss Me, I Don't Smoke; and non-smokers joined ``adopt-a-smoker''
programs to help smokers through a smokeless day.
   The American Cancer Society estimates nearly 40 percent of the
nation's 50 million smokers tried to quit for the day. About
one-tenth, or 2 million people, will kick the habit permanently,
said Paul Rosenberg, a cancer society spokesman in New York.
   ``My grandkids keep telling me it's time to quit smoking,'' said
Pat Zielke, mayor of La Crosse, Wis., and a pack-a-day smoker for 40
years. He quit smoking for the day and was ``adopted'' by a cancer
society volunteer.
   Actor and former smoker Larry Hagman, star of the television show
``Dallas,'' said the smokeout was the day to just quit lighting up.
   ``The key to quitting for good is just quitting. There's no
tapering off, you just have to go cold-turkey,'' said Hagman, who is
honorary chairman of the observance.
   In New York, the cast and crew of Off-Broadway's ``Steel
Magnolias'' went cold turkey.
   ``It's going to curl some of their hair,'' teased non-smoker
Bobby Grayson, hair designer for the play, which is set in a beauty
parlor.
   Smokers traded their cigarettes for apples in several cities,
including New York, Norwalk, Conn., and Philadelphia. Non-smokers
got apples, too, along with a ``good for you.''
   Some hard-core New Yorkers eyed the apples suspiciously. Others
took them to wives, boyfriend or co-workers who smoke. Some, like
Sino Perratore, threw their cigarettes into a waste basket at
Rockefeller Plaza.
   In Hammond, La., pharmacist Don Fellows Jr. burned four cartons
of cigarettes, four boxes of cigars and several boxes of chewing
tobacco in a hibachi outside his store.
   The burning tobacco was all he had left after deciding several
months ago to stop ordering the products and to burn what was left.
   ``I thought I would make a statement; maybe someone would stop
and think and stop smoking cigarettes before it was too late,''
Fellows said.
   A chain of three pharmacies planned a similar tobacco bonfire in
Austin, Texas.
   In Indianapolis and Fort Wayne, Ind., 10-feet-tall cigarettes
were erected downtown, complete with smoke-generating machines. Fire
crews doused the smoldering cigarettes and chopped them into small
pieces.
   In Little Rock, Ark., a 5-foot-tall smoking cigarette was put out
with fire extinguishers by workers at the Baptist Medical System
building. One employee, Lana Campbell, said this is about the third
time she's used the smokeout to try to quit.
   ``You know what they say, if at first you don't succeed,'' said
Ms. Campbell, 27, of North Little Rock.
   The grandson of tobacco magnate R.J. Reynolds joined with
Pleasanton, Calif.-based publisher SyberVision to launch a $20
million television advertising campaign accusing the tobacco
industry of addicting millions of Americans.
   ``My grandfather, R.J. Reynolds, helped get America hooked on
cigarettes through clever advertising. Now, I'm going to use the
power of advertising to get America unhooked,'' Patrick Reynolds
said.
   Thousands of Californians rode aboard the ``Smokeout Express,'' a
train coach on Amtrak's San Diegan, which took a whistlestop
no-smoking journey through Southern California. A pipeless Mr.
Potato Head, the popular toy spud, joined them.
   One California crusader against smoking tried to stuff 143
cigarettes in his mouth at one time to show that smoking is ugly and
hazardous to your health.
   ``I'm showing how ridiculous it looks. Some people smoke this
much in a day or week,'' said Jim Mouth as he prepared to shove the
more than seven packs in his mouth at John's Pipe Shop in Hollywood.
   Businesses and schools in Concord and Bedford, Mass., received
visits from a 6-foot-tall turkey clad in winter garb.
   ``Our turkey is wearing a scarf and a vest and encouraging people
to quit cold turkey,'' said Deb Beatty, a cancer society spokeswoman.
   They were also talking turkey near the Texas Capitol in Austin,
where a sandwich shop gave free 6-inch turkey sandwiches to people
who turned in a half-pack of cigarettes.
   The anti-smoking demonstrations persauded many to try to kick the
habit. Others finally heeded the warnings that smoking causes lung
cancer, heart disease and respiratory disease. The surgeon general
has warned of the potentially fatal risks of smoking and the
addictive properties of nicotine, the drug in cigarettes.
   Eileen Ham, a smoker for 35 years, got the message.
   ``I've been cutting down slowly. I've gone a whole day without
smoking in the last two weeks, and I've cut down to five or six
cigarettes a night,'' she said in Austin. ``I want to quit because
it will make me feel better and it will give me more energy.''
   Still, there's one in every crowd.
   Alan Farnham, a reporter for Fortune magazine in New York,
gathered 40 ``like-minded people'' for a tongue-in-cheek
``smoke-in'' at a Manhattan restaurant.
   ``By reducing stress, tobacco adds years to life,'' Farnham said.
``Galen, the Greek physician, believed tobacco adds years to life.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881117-0236 </DOCNO>
