<HEAD>Reagan Pays Tribute to USIA Director Wick</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan joined 200 executives and
professionals from the private sector Thursday at a dinner paying
tribute to Charles Z. Wick, director of the U.S. Information Agency
throughout the Reagan administration.
   ``Charlie is the man who brought our international communications
agency into the 20th century,'' Reagan told the audience at the
black tie affair.
   Other officials of the administration as well as diplomats and
members of Congress attended the dinner at the headquarters of the
Organization of American States, along with the president and first
lady Nancy Reagan.
   The dinner was a highlight of the annual meeting of USIA's 10
private sector committees, made up of experts in film, radio and
television broadcasting, sports, publishing, public relations and
medicine.
