<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-88 2255EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Pollard-Interview     11-17 0285</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pollard-Interview,0294</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Convicted Spy Pollard Calls His Life Sentence Unfair</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Convicted spy Jonathan Pollard says he deserved
to be punished for giving U.S. secrets to Israel, but claims in a
television interview that his life sentence is unfair.
   In an interview to be broadcast on CBS' ``60 Minutes'' Sunday,
Pollard said there was ``no excuse'' for his passing classified
information to Israeli agents in 1985 when he was a civilian
intelligence analyst for the Navy.
   But he said there was ``an explanation.''
   Pollard said he acted for ``soft reasons having to do with a
family that was destroyed in the holocaust. Having to do with the
realization that this government in the 40s had abandoned the Jewish
people to its fate in Europe.''
   ``The hard reason why I did what I did ... (was that U.S. policy)
was fundamentally to place Israel in a position where she would be
forced to make an unenviable choice between a ruinous war or
shameful peace,'' he said.
   The interview took place at the U.S. Bureau of Prison's maximum
security penitentiary in Marion, Ill. in the presence of two U.S.
Naval Intelligence officials.
   Pollard was sentenced to life imprisonment in March 1987 after
pleading guilty to conspiracy to commit espionage.
   His wife, Anne Henderson-Pollard, pleaded guilty to conspiracy to
receive embezzled government property and being an accessory after
the fact to the possession of national defense secrets. She was
sentenced to five years in prison.
   Pollard said he considered his sentence unfair because Israel is
an ally and he did not give it information damaging to U.S.
interests.
   ``My sentence did not reflect proportional justice, it reflected
political vengeance, plain and simple,'' Pollard said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
