<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-AfghanRights     11-17 0647</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Afghan Rights,0664</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING to change slug from AM-UN-Afghan, a0817, and avoid
confusion with another story slugged AM-UN-Afghans.</HEAD>
<HEAD>U.N. Report Says Afghan Human Rights Situation Improves</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   UNITED NATIONS _ A U.N. report said Thursday that the human
rights situation in Afghanstan improved somewhat in
government-controlled areas, but it said acts of terrorism by rebels
increased in the past year.
   The 37-page annual human rights report on Afghanistan said that
while the Geneva Agreements, signed April 14, ``give grounds for
hope, the special rapporteur (the person assigned to prepare the
report) has still not been able to report any improvement in the
human rights situation within the country.
   ``Acts of war are continuing, violations of human rights are at
least as frequent as in the past, affecting particularly the
civilian population and endangering the lives and security of
innocent men, women and children.''
   The rapporteur, Felix Ermacora of Austria, is the special
investigator of the Afghan human rights situation for the U.N. Human
Rights Commission, based in Geneva.
   A similar report last year said the main problem in realizating
human rights there was the presence of more than 100,000 Soviet
troops. Half of them have been withdrawn under U.N.-mediated
agreements signed in Geneva.
   The rest are to be pulled out by Feb. 15, although Moscow has
suspended its withdrawal because of increasing attacks by
U.S.-backed and Pakistan-based rebels.
   The report said, ``In general, there is greater improvement in
the human rights situation in government-controlled areas. However,
allegations of torture and ill-treatment of prisoners on remand
(awaiting trial) and political prisoners are still being received,''
he said. Afghan authorities reject the allegations.
   Ermacora said the number of political prisoners has fallen
sharply as a result of anmnesty decress and other measures under the
Afghan government policy of national reconciliation. Conditions of
detention in Pol-i-Charkhi prison, a major center, have improved, it
said.
   But the investigator also said that after the signing of the
Geneva Agreements, which Afghan rebels rejected, ``acts of terrorism
... have caused many deaths among innocent civilians.''
   ``Terrorism in Afghanistan and Pakistan has multipled,'' since
his report last year, he said.
   The report cited government reports of rebel violence from April
to last August. It said heavy artillery and ground-to-ground
missiles were used against towns and villages, charitable
institutions and mosques. The report cited 4,154 cases of missile
firings and 24 explosions, killing 945 civilians and wounding 1,895,
including 187 children and 98 women.
   It said a rocket attack on Kabul Airport killed nine civilians on
Sept. 1 and wounded 20. On Sept.27, a rocket attack on a Kabul
neighborhood reportedly killed 35 civilians.
   Afghan refugees in Pakistan, it said, still are afraid to return
home, largely because of rebel-planted mines.
   The report said withdrawing Soviet troops had committed human
rights violations and it cited reports of Soviet bombing and
bombardment of civilian areas.
   On March 7, it said, Soviet artillery bombarded residential areas
in the suburbs of Herat, at the end of April migrating nomads were
attacked by Soviet and Afghan troops and houses, schools and mosques
were damaged and destroyed in other Soviet attacks.
   ``Many Afghan villages and houses have been destroyed in the
course of the Soviet troop withdrawal and many civilians have been
killed due to the fighting tactics of the oppostion movements and
acts of retaliation,'' the report said.
   The U.N. report said treatment of prisoners of war violates the
1949 Geneva Conventions. Prisoners are used as a means of barganing
and exchange, it said.
   The whereabouts of at least 313 Soviet soldiers missing in action
is still unknown, it said. The Afghan government considers rebels to
be terrorists and not combatants to be treated in accordance with
international humanitarian law, it said.
   The report said the International Committee of the Red Cross
should be given full access to all prisons and detention centers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
