<HEAD>American Camerawoman Dies of Hepatitis While Covering War</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American TV news camerawoman has
died of hepatitis while traveling in Afghanistan to cover the war,
the U.S. Embassy said Thursday.
   Her name was being withheld pending notification of her family,
said a duty officer.
   In New York, CBS spokesman Tom Goodman said the woman was a
free-lancer on assignment for CBS News.
   He said it was not determined immediately whether she worked as a
camera operator, sound person or in some other capacity, ``but she
was obviously a member of a news crew.''
   Afghan guerrilla sources, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said the woman died Tuesday near Jalalabad in eastern Afghanistan as
the rebels tried to get her to Pakistan for medical treatment. Her
body was delivered to the Americans on Thursday in Peshawar,
Pakistan, for shipment home.
   Official Radio Kabul reported that a foreign journalist was
robbed and killed by guerrillas near the same city and on the same
day as the woman.
   There was no confirmation of that report. It was unclear whether
it was the Marxist government's version of the same death.
   Radio Kabul has reported several Americans and other foreigners
killed recently in Afghanistan, allegedly while helping the rebels.
   U.S. officials have described the claims as fabrications. They
deny that any non-embassy U.S. personnel are in Afghanistan.
   The United States and Pakistan support the insurgents in their
struggle to oust the Kabul government and drive out the Soviet
forces who bolster it.
   Moscow has pledged to remove all its troops from Afghanistan by
Feb. 15.
</TEXT>
