<1ST_LINE>r a AM-McNamaraProbe     11-17 0562</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-McNamara Probe,0583</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Attorney Being Investigated Over Marijuana Allegations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department is investigating whether
U.S. Attorney Frank L. McNamara Jr. made false statements about his
predecessor when he accused him of smoking marijuana, sources said
Thursday.
   The allegations were rejected by a federal inquiry.
   McNamara had told investigators he saw his predecessor, William
F. Weld, smoking marijuana at a 1982 party in Virginia. But the
report of a 1987 Justice Department probe released Wednesday found
``no evidence whatsoever'' to support the claim.
   Weld later headed the Justice Department's criminal division.
   McNamara issued a two-sentence statement responding to the
report, which was filed in federal appeals court in Washington by
Attorney General Richard Thornburgh.
   ``Upon receiving the report released by the court, I immediately
requested that the Department of Justice conduct a prompt and
thorough investigation to resolve any suggestion of impropriety by
me raised in the report,'' McNamara said.
   ``I will continue to cooperate with the Department of Justice in
every way in order to resolve this matter as quickly as possible,''
he said.
   McNamara's secretary said he was out of his office and
unavailable for comment.
   Justice Department spokesman John Russell declined to comment on
whether McNamara was under investigation.
   But federal law enforcement sources in Washington, speaking on
condition of anonymity, said the Justice Department's Office of
Professional Responsibility was investigating whether McNamara made
false statements about Weld.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney John Markham, who was appointed by Weld
in Boston in April 1985, said McNamara's allegation about Weld was
``just not possible.''
   ``Everybody who has worked with him knows him to be completely
apolitical as a prosecutor and a straight-arrow,'' Markham said in
an interview Thursday.
   President Reagan nominated McNamara to succeed Weld in April
1987, a few months after Weld was appointed to head the Justice
Department's criminal division in Washington.
   An internal Justice Department memo on which Thornburgh's court
filing was based said that after he went to Washington, conflict
developed between Weld and the office of then-Deputy Attorney
General Arnold Burns.
   James Byrnes, a deputy assistant attorney general who was helping
to shepherd McNamara's nomination as U.S. attorney in Boston through
the Senate, told investigators that Burns requested him to call
McNamara to ``dig up some dirt'' on Weld.
   McNamara, who told investigators Weld opposed his nomination and
believed Weld was trying to scuttle it, then told Byrnes that he had
seen Weld drunk on a couple of occasions and had seen him smoking a
``joint'' at a party after a wedding in Virginia in 1982.
   The memo said it is unclear whether Byrnes, who said he had no
specific recollection of briefing Burns, reported back what McNamara
had said.
   Burns and Weld resigned from the Justice Department on March 29
to protest former Attorney General Edwin Meese III's continued
tenure.
   Asked whether he believed Burns had requested officials to ``dig
up dirt,'' Weld said Thursday: ``I've spoken to Arnie and there's no
misunderstanding between us as to the events at the Justice
Department.''
   Weld said his relations with Burns are good. He declined further
comment.
   Burns on Wednesday labeled as ``categorically untrue'' the
allegation that he told Byrnes to call McNamara about Weld.
   The Justice Department memo also said McNamara told the FBI that
he had smoked marijuana as recently as four years ago.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881117-0242 </DOCNO>
