<HEAD>Sandinistas Charge 11 Government Officials Kidnapped by Rebels</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said Thursday that
U.S.-backed rebels kidnapped 11 government officials who were
inspecting hurricane damage in an eastern province.
   A statement from the president's office said rebels abducted the
health, agriculture and finance officials Saturday near Rio Coco
town, about 220 miles northeast of Managua.
   It said the officials were evaluating damage caused by Hurricane
Joan, which struck Nicaragua on Oct. 22.
   The leftist Sandinista government appealed to Honduras for the
safety of the captives. Neighboring Honduras is used as a base by
rebel troops.
   The rebels, known as Contras, made no immediate response to the
government claim.
   The government and rebels signed a cease-fire agreement in March,
but talks on ending the 7-year-old civil war collapsed in September.
Each side accuses the other of truce violations.
</TEXT>
