<1ST_LINE>a i PM-Thailand-Indochina Adv25   11-17 0734</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Thailand-Indochina, Adv 25,0751</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv25</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri PMs Nov. 25 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Thailand Seeks Business Links with Indochina</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY MOLLY YONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thailand has begun looking to its
communist-governed neighbors as trading partners after shunning them
since the Indochina war years.
   Calling for increased commerce with Vietnam, Laos and Cambodia,
Thai businessmen voice fear they are being outdone by counterparts
from Japan and Singapore, which are drawing $200 million to $300
million a year in a low profile but brisk trade.
   As Vietnam liberalizes its underdeveloped economy, Thai
businessmen and some legislators worry that if they act too slowly
Japan and Singapore along with Hong Kong, Taiwan or France will
corner a market that Thailand is in a favorable geographic position
to penetrate.
   Prime Minister Chatichai Choonhavan, himself a businessman,
started talking about improving general relations with Indochina as
well as exploring economic opportunities shortly after taking office
in August.
   Already Thai businessmen are angling for fishing licenses in
bountiful Vietnamese waters and sending agricultural experts to Laos
to supervise an experimental farm while importing Laotian timber.
   Laotians shop at a Thai-run department store in Vientiane, the
Laotian capital, and a Thai company recently entered into the first
major joint venture project in Laos, the construction of a garment
factory.
   But officially Thailand has thus far had no
government-to-government economic transactions with Vietnam since
its troops invaded neighboring Cambodia, and Thai policy has been
one of putting pressure on the Vietnamese in all fields. The Thai
government also offers no help to private entrepreneurs doing
business with Indochina, but it generally turns a blind eye to the
vast black market trade across its borders with Cambodia and Laos as
well as Burma.
   ``We have lost time and lost out to countries that actively
traded with Indochina regardless of their government's strong
opposition to Vietnamese troops in Cambodia,'' said Wongse
Polnikorn, a former deputy foreign minister and currently chairman
of a Thai company that will import timber from Laos and set up a
cash-crop farm in Vientiane.
   Prime Minister Chatichai has instructed that the number of goods
officially banned for export to Laos be halved to 30, according to
government spokesman Suvit Yodmani.
   Since the 1975 communist victories in Indochina, periodic
skirmishes _ as well as two major confrontations _ have erupted
along the Thai-Laotian border. Similar clashes have occurred between
Thais and Vietnamese along the Thai-Cambodian frontier.
   Last year, two-way trade between Laos and Thailand topped $48
million, although the black market, or ``unofficial,'' trade is
known to be far higher. Two-way trade with Vietnam rose to $7.5
million last year from $4.8 million in 1986 while Thai exports to
Cambodia were $400,000 in 1986.
   But some in Thailand, which has traditionally been suspicious of
Vietnam's longterm intentions in the region, view a prosperous
Vietnam as potentially dangerous and expansionist.
   ``If we can make Vietnam prosperous, ourselves prosperous, that's
great, but what is there to guarantee that Vietnam won't move into
Thailand's northeast,'' spokesman Suvit said in an interview. ``Once
it's prosperous, then it can afford to keep troops in Cambodia.''
   Surin Pitsuwan, a leading member of Parliament, suggested that
Thailand at first proceed cautiously in trading with Laos, a country
with which it shares ethnic and cultural bonds and which poses no
major security threat. He also suggested more economic dealings with
Burma, with which official, two-way trade totaled $544 million in
1987.
   ``There are a lot of trade opportunities and untapped resources
next door,'' Surin said. ``If we don't hurry now, the degree of
their dependence on us will be reduced.''
   Although Thailand will be hard pressed to compete with Japanese
technology and funding, businessmen say the Thais could carve out a
profitable Indochina niche in such areas as agro-industry, fishing,
forestry and smaller-scale construction.
   Thailand, where the economy is booming and consumer spending on
an upward curve, could also serve as a market for Indochinese goods.
While war has largely wrecked economic infrastructure in Indochina,
the three countries possess large untapped natural resources and an
abundance of cheap labor.
   ``We must go and explore ways we can do more and benefit from one
another,'' said Kangwan Tantiponganant, a businessmen involved in
Laos. Given the political sensitivities, other Thai businessmen
prefer to make low-keyed trips to Vietnam and Laos, emphasizing that
their interests are in ``long-term business planning.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Fri PMs Nov. 25</NOTE>
