<1ST_LINE>a a PM-GovernmentBargains ADV22   11-17 0859</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Government Bargains, ADV 22,0887</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv22</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Tuesday PMs, Nov. 22, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Surplus-Agency Chief Deals in Federal Bargains, From Bolts To
Bulldozers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARLENE LEVINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAUNTON, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In his pursuit of a bargain for taxpayers,
Edward Aleixo has flown into the mountains of Virginia to retrieve
an old pickup truck with bad tires and no rear lights, driving it
home to Massachusetts.
   He has wangled his way into government vaults and come out with
an Oriental rug Henry Kissinger couldn't use, and procured shelving
and two office cubicles discarded by the White House.
   Aleixo, a retired Air Force colonel, former narcotics agent and
one-time school superintendent, makes big deals, too.
   As director of the Massachusetts State Agency for Surplus
Property, Aleixo is trying at the moment to get his hands on 12 used
helicopters no longer wanted by the Army in Fort Rucker, Ala., so he
can give them to state police and a flight school in Boston.
   Note the word ``give.''
   Alexio insists he doesn't sell a thing he brokers. But for a
relatively small price that covers the cost of his operation, Aleixo
obtains surplus federal property and passes it on to state and
municipal governments, schools and non-profit organizations such as
nursing homes and halfway houses.
   A relatively small price?
   How does $150 sound for a $1,840.56 medical centrifuge (like new)?
   Or $2,500 for a used $200,000 road grader?
   The 9-by-12-foot Kissinger rug was a gift from Algeria that the
then-secretary of state couldn't accept. It now warms the toes of
some Massachusetts government official, a bargain at $150.
   Every state has a surplus agency, under a law Congress enacted
after World War II to make sure the states shared in the federal
leftovers. Customers are restricted to government entities,
educational institutions and non-profit health agencies. There are
1,800 certified customers around the country.
   In Massachusetts, there's a twice-yearly junkyard sale, but
otherwise Aleixo's warehouses are closed to the public. His
customers say access to the surplus stuff helps.
   ``It's tremendous,'' said Brian Broderick, who for 15 years has
been buying surplus goods for the Metropolitan District Commission,
an agency that oversees highways, sewers and other projects that
cross juridictions in the Boston area.
   Government surplus kept the commission rolling a decade ago while
waiting for a bond issue to buy new vehicles. For instance,
tractor-trailers were supplied for a song: $5,000 apiece for a set
of four that would have cost $65,000 each new.
   The Metro Police command bus, a headquarters on wheels, was once
a NASA mobile tracking station. ``We paid no more than $1,000 for
it. A nice piece of equipment that would have cost us $55,000 to
$60,000.''
   ``This is the cheapest way the government has of getting rid of
its property,'' Aleixo said. ``Most of the money goes back to the
taxpayer.''
   Customers pay about 3 cents on the original dollar cost to the
government. Even so, Aleixo's self-supporting operation is in the
red trying to cover its $450,000 annual operating costs, including a
staff of 12. Since the late 1970s, federal agencies have become more
economy minded.
   ``That is good, but there's a point where it's more
cost-effective to buy something new,'' rather than fix the old,
Aleixo said.
   He reckons the state government saves $1 million a year picking
through his warehouse. The assorted other customers save $5 million
to $6 million.
   Rotund and low to the ground, Aleixo is an intense man with a
sense of purpose and a one-liner to describe his work: ``We get all
the bang that's left in the buck.''
   Even the warehouses storing the goods are hand-me-downs. A pair
of long gray metal-clad buildings at the back of an industrial park,
they were erected in 1942 as an assembly point for soldiers shipping
off to fight World War II.
   Inside, every truck, electron microscope and box of bolts, gets a
number.
   Items that cost the government more than $5,000 when new must be
used by the receiver within a year. If not, the new owner doesn't
get title to the object and it is considered stolen property. Items
costing more than $10,000 must be used within 36 months.
   What's in the inventory?
   Dental file cabinets, an oboe and half a piccolo, tons of bolts
for building bridges, metal and wood desks in various stages of
decrepitude from the Internal Revenue Service, a brass bedstead once
belonging to a naval computer testing equipment, computer circuit
boards, air conditioner filters.
   Also: leftover pipe from a submarine, ice skates, map file
drawers, machine tool drills, typewriters and calculators, chairs,
an aircraft camera, tool boxes, an offset press, and Army-green gas
tanks among the takings when a government supplier came under
criminal scrutiny and the relationship ended.
   So what can agencies or schools do with, say, a jet engine
container or 2,000 feet of 2-inch plastic tubing?
   ``I advise them to send a creative person, a person with a spirit
of innovation who can see a new way to use something,'' Aleixo said.
   ``The kids from MIT. They're probably our biggest customers.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Tues PMs, Nov 22</NOTE>
</DOC>
