<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0540</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. trade deficit narrowed by 17 percent
to $10.5 billion in September, the government has reported.
   Exports rose by $700 million to a record high $28.2 billion, the
Commerce Department said Wednesday. Imports declined by 2.5 percent
or $1.1 billion to $38.7 billion from a record high in August.
   The $10.5 billion trade gap for September was down by $1.8
billion from the revised August trade deficit figure of $12.3
billion.
   But the government said the improvement was not enough to stem
inflation worries.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The operating rate at U.S. factories, mines and
utilities rose in October to the highest level in 8{ years,
according to the Federal Reserve.
   The Fed said Wednesday that American industry used 84.0 percent
of its capacity last month, up from 83.8 percent in September. It
was the largest increase since July and the highest level since
February 1980.
   Capacity use has grown or held steady for eight consecutive
months, creeping ever closer to the 85 percent threshold that
economists believe signals a pickup in inflation.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Business inventories rose sharply relative to
sales in September, the government reports.
   But analysts discounted the economic significance of Wednesday's
government report, noting that sales have picked up since then.
   The Commerce Department said inventories held on shelves and
backlots rose 0.7 percent to a seasonally adjusted $749.4 billion,
while sales remained virtually unchanged at $495.4 billion.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United and Northwest airlines have decided to
follow Continental Airlines' move to boost most discount MaxSaver
fares.
   But spokesmen for American Airlines and Delta Air Lines said
those carriers still were studying Continental's move.
   United said Wednesday it was matching Continental's action
throughout its route system with the average increase on the
MaxSavers to be around $15 each way. Northwest only partially
followed the action, changing around 30,000 MaxSaver fares between
different cities.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Economic Commission has opened its
post-election attempt to break a seven-year deadlock on the budget
deficit with repeated warnings that the deficit represents the
nation's greatest economic threat.
   Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan, one of the leadoff
witnesses before the bipartisan panel, said Wednesday ``The deficit
already has begun to eat away at the foundations of our economic
strength, and the need to deal with it is becoming ever more
urgent.''
   Greenspan joined other witnesses in saying that Congress and
President-elect George Bush must reach agreement quickly on ways to
slash the deficit or run the risk that foreigners will stop
financing America's borrowing needs.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The buyout firm Forstmann Little & Co. and its
partners have withdrawn from the bidding for RJR Nabisco Inc.,
muddling the battle for the food and tobacco giant.
   Forstmann Little stated Wednesday the investor group it led had
decided that ``consistent with its investment criteria, it will not
submit a proposal.''
   The group's decision left an unknown number of suitors for RJR
Nabisco, which is accepting sealed bids from prospective buyers
until Friday.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
