<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A British securities fraud probe that suggests
Ivan Boesky duped Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. could give the
troubled firm a potent new attack on the credibility of the
imprisoned insider trader.
   Boesky has implicated Drexel in illegal acts and is expected to
be a star witness against the investment house.
   Legal experts said Wednesday that the British investigation also
may mean new trouble for Boesky if he did not disclose the alleged
fraud against Drexel when he negotiated a plea-bargain agreement two
years ago.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michigan's request for federal protection from
Canadian automotive trade practices has been rejected by the U.S.
trade representative.
   Trade Representative Clayton Yeutter said Wednesday state
officials had no right to file such a petition.
   He also said the state's request had been superceded by a
free-trade agreement negotiated between the United States and
Canada. Under the program, Canada gives duty rebates on autos to
foreign manufacturers in return for the use of Canadian parts in
their cars.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Treasury Department task force studying the
savings and loan crisis has concluded that taxpayer money must be
spent to rescue the ailing system.
   An administration official said Wednesday that the department
also is looking at a proposal to form a presidential board headed by
the Treasury secretary to oversee the bailout.
   The official confirmed reports that the administration was
considering a plan to raise $20 billion to $30 billion a year for
three years.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A draft proposal to impose stricter
requirements for appealing government decisions to deny Social
Security, Medicare and welfare benefits has provoked a furor among
members of Congress and lobbyists for the elderly and disabled.
   Chuck Kline, a spokesman for Dr. Otis R. Bowen, secretary of
health and human services, said Wednesday the proposed new rules
were still under review within the Social Security Administration
and had not reached Bowen.
   Several critics said the rules, if adopted, would violate the
1935 Social Security Act and a 1971 Supreme Court ruling which
supported an informal and liberal appeals process easily accessible
to the elderly, poor and disabled who frequently lack legal counsel.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than $70 million worth of Douglas and
noble firs are being cut and bundled as Oregon growers ready
themselves for the Christmas season.
   With an expected harvest of 7.2 million trees this year, Oregon
remains the nation's single largest supplier of Christmas trees.
   Prices remain about the same as last year for premium trees, with
6-foot to 7-foot Douglas firs bringing growers around $11, said
Bryan Ostlund, spokesman for the Northwest Christmas Tree
Association in Salem. Slower-growing noble firs bring a higher
price, he said, while retail prices are at least double what growers
receive.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar plunged Wednesday as bearish sentiment overwhelmed the
government's report of a narrowing of the U.S. merchandise trade
deficit.
   Bond prices declined sharply in response to the falling dollar.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials dropped 38.59 to
2,038.58, its lowest close since it stood at 2,002.31 on Sept. 1.
   Crude futures prices fell; cocoa futures prices surged; silver
futures sagged while gold futures were little changed; copper
futures retreated; grains were lower; soybeans were higher; and
livestock and meat futures were mixed.
</TEXT>
