<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     11-17 0248</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0259</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices have turned mixed as traders
keep their attention on the OPEC meetings scheduled for this week.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the December contract for
West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude oil, fell
23 cents Wednesday to settle at $13.67 a barrel, after falling 37
cents on Tuesday. Other contract months also lost ground.
   Among refined petroleum products traded on the exchange
Wednesday, the December contract for unleaded gasoline settled at
46.50 cents a gallon, down 0.46 cent. The contract had fallen 1.20
cents Tuesday.
   The December contract for wholesale home heating oil, which fell
0.23 cent in the previous session, rose 0.07 cent to settle at 44.47
cents a gallon.
   Ministers from eight OPEC nations were gathering today for
pricing and strategy committee meetings in Vienna, Austria, wich
were to be followed by a full meeting of all 13 ministers on Monday.
   Analysts said reports that daily OPEC crude production has
reached 22.5 million barrels depressed some prices Wednesday, but
they said traders were optimistic cartel members would work at
upcoming meetings toward eliminating the worldwide oil glut.
   The Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries has a
self-imposed daily production limit of about 15 million barrels.
However, a number of members are believed to be ignoring their
individual limits.
   Overproduction has added to an already glutted world market and
pushed crude prices well below OPEC's benchmark of $18 a barrel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881117-0256 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-88 0051EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OPEC Bjt   11-17 0672</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-OPEC, Bjt,0696</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>OPEC Ministers Face Issue Of Output Levels, Oil Price Slump</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Will be led with early oil prices, further lead prospects
uncertain; meeting begins late afternoon or early evening local
time.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Facing the prospect of fresh declines in
world oil prices, OPEC chiefs gathering today in Vienna are under
pressure to fashion a new agreement that will control the cartel's
surging production and help bolster crude prices.
   Ministers from eight of the 13 nations that make up the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries were meeting for talks
on bringing order to the chaotic oil market.
   ``There is a feeling they have to come up with a new (production)
agreement,'' said one OPEC official, who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   ``They will work very hard at it because of the consequence of
failure...a collapse in prices,'' he said.
   The eight ministers are meeting in a joint session of two OPEC
committees, in talks that could run into the weekend. On Monday, all
13 ministers are to meet for the cartel's winter meeting.
   At issue is the thorny problem of how to address the cartel's
recently skyrocketing output, which has added to an already glutted
world market. Analysts say most OPEC members have exceeded their
production quotas, partly to press for position in advance of the
Vienna meetings.
   As a result, prices have slipped $4 or more below OPEC's
benchmark price of $18 a barrel. A barrel is equivalent to 42
gallons.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the December contract for
West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude oil, fell
23 cents Wednesday to settle at $13.67 a barrel, after falling 37
cents on Tuesday.
   The recent declines reflect how dramatically OPEC production has
risen.
   The International Energy Agency estimated in its Monthly Oil
Market Report that OPEC production was nearly 21.1 million barrels a
day in October, the highest monthly output in more than five years.
   OPEC's official total production quota under a December 1986
arrangement is about 15 million barrels a day. That excludes Iraq,
which has ignored its limit.
   Nick Antill, oil analyst at the London brokerage County NatWest,
estimated next year's demand for OPEC oil at 18.7 million barrels a
day.
   Joseph Stanislaw, managing director of Cambridge Energy Research
Associates in Paris, speculated that a new accord might set total
output at 19 million to 19.5 million barrels a day.
   A key to a new quota agreement is bringing Iraq back into the
system.
   Saudi Arabia _ the world's largest oil exporter and OPEC's most
influential member _ and Kuwait have insisted that a fresh accord
must include all members.
   Saudi Arabia recently increased its production to more than 6
million barrels a day, well above its ceiling of 4.3 million
barrels, in an attempt to pressure other cartel members to obey
their quotas.
   Iraq has refused to obey its daily ceiling of 1.5 million barrels
because it wanted parity with war rival Iran, which has a quota of
2.4 million barrels.
   The two countries agreed to an August cease-fire in their
8-year-old war, and both want to earn more oil revenue to pay for
rebuilding their war-ravaged economies.
   Analysts estimated Iraq has been producing at least 2.6 million
barrels a day, and could boost production to 3.7 million barrels
next year with completion of a new pipeline through Saudi Arabia to
the Red Sea.
   Under a new system, Iran and Iraq might each get a quota of 2.6
million barrels, analysts predicted.
   OPEC ministers also must deal with the United Arab Emirates'
refusal to stick to its quota of 948,000 million barrels a day. It
independently has boosted its limit to 1.5 million barrels.
   OPEC's price evolution committee, meeting Thursday with the
long-term strategy panel, is made up of Algeria, Saudi Arabia,
Nigeria, Indonesia and Venezuela. The strategy committee's members
are Iraq, Iran, Kuwait, Saudi Arabia, Algeria and Venezuela.
   Other OPEC members are Ecuador, Gabon, Libya, Qatar and the
United Arab Emirates.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881117-0257 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-88 0059EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Pillsbury Bjt   11-17 0501</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pillsbury, Bjt,0517</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grand Met Seeking To Block Burger King Spinoff; Pillsbury Won't
Meet</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grand Metropolitan PLC says it is going to
court to try and block Pillsbury Co.'s plan to spin off its Burger
King fast-food chain, the key element in Pillsbury's attempt to
thwart Grand Met's hostile $5.23 billion takeover bid.
   The spinoff, set for Dec. 2, is part of a defensive restructuring
the food and restaurant company announced after rejecting Grand
Met's $60 a share tender offer as inadequate on Oct. 17.
   Pillsbury contends its shareholders would be better off with the
restructuring, in which they would receive a special dividend and
stock in the newly separate Burger King, which accounts for a huge
chunk of Pillsbury's revenues but is slumping.
   But Grand Met claims it would have to lower its buyout offer
should the spinoff occur, because the restructured company would
present a huge tax liability for Grand Met.
   Grand Met said Wednesday it planned to ask for a temporary
restraining order in Delaware Chancery Court, where Chancellor
William Allen has said he would hold a hearing Nov. 28.
   According to Grand Met, Allen also said he would set a hearing
for Dec. 12 on Grand Met's renewed motion to invalidate Pillsbury's
``poison pill'' takeover defense. The tender offer, which has been
extended three times, is conditioned on the removal of the pill,
which would make a takeover prohibitively expensive.
   Dissident shareholders also have sued to have the pill
invalidated, but courts in Delaware and Minnesota have left it
intact.
   Pillsbury stock closed at $56 Wednesday, down $2 a share in
composite New York Stock Exchange trading.
   In another matter, documents from both companies filed with the
Securities and Exchange Commission indicate Pillsbury Chairman
Philip Smith on Tuesday rejected a telephone request from Grand Met
Chairman Allen Sheppard to meet in New York to discuss the tender
offer.
   Sheppard on Wednesday renewed his criticism of Pillsbury's stance.
   ``We are amazed at the negative response to our overture, given
that almost 80 percent of the Pillsbury shares had been tendered to
Grand Met as of Nov. 14,'' Sheppard said in a statement.
   Pillsbury had no comment. In its SEC filing, Pillsbury said Smith
told Sheppard in their phone discussion that he saw no purpose in
meeting.
   ``Mr. Smith noted...that if Mr. Sheppard had anything additional
for the board to consider, he would report it to the board,''
Pillsbury's SEC document said.
   In Grand Met's account of the telephone conversation, Smith said
he was led to believe from media reports and company statements that
Grand Met was firm on the price of its tender offer.
   ``Mr. Sheppard indicated that while he presently saw no reason to
increase the offer price, he had heard that Mr. Smith was a very
good salesman and was prepared to listen to any argument that Mr.
Smith might have regarding why Grand Met ought to pay more than $60
a share,'' Grand Met stated.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
