<1ST_LINE>r f PM-PrimeComputer     11-17 0379</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Prime Computer,0392</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prime Asks Stockholders To Wait On Takeover Bid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Computer Inc. is asking its stockholders to
wait two weeks before deciding whether to sell their shares under a
$970 million takeover offer made by a small California computer
maker.
   On Wednesday, one day after the unsolicited offer by MAI Basic
Four Inc., which is controlled by New York investor Bennett S.
LeBow, Prime also announced that its president, Joe M. Henson, was
stepping down six weeks earlier than planned.
   Henson said in a statement that the takeover bid ``makes it
desirable to complete the transition now so Prime can be represented
by the man who will have responsibility for leading it in the
future.''
   Anthony Craig was named on Oct. 3 to succeed Henson but was not
due to take over until the end of the year.
   MAI Basic, which already owns 4.1 percent of Prime's 48.5 million
shares outstanding, is offering $20 a share for the remaining stock.
   Prime closed Wednesday at $17 a share, down 75 cents in
consolidated New York Stock Exchange trading. MAI Basic fell 37{
cents to $11 a share.
   Natick-based Prime in February acquired Computervision Inc. for
$435 million to become the second-leading supplier behind
International Business Machines Corp. in the field of computer-aided
design and manufacturing systems.
   Prime last month bolstered its position by acquiring General
Electric Corp.'s Calma business, which also makes CAD-CAM systems.
MAI Basic, which is about one-quarter the size of Prime, makes
business computers and information processing systems.
   In a statement Wednesday, Prime said its board of directors would
meet ``in due course'' to discuss the MAI Basic bid, which is being
made by a wholly owned subsidiary set up specifically for the
takeover, Choice Corp.
   The company said it will notify shareholders of its decision by
Nov. 29.
   Choice Corp. has conditioned the bid on at least 67 percent of
shares being tendered by the offer's Dec. 13 expiration.
   MAI Basic said it filed suit in Delaware Chancery Court seeking
to block Prime's new poison-pill takeover defense from taking
effect. The company also has begun litigation against Prime in U.S.
District Court in Boston seeking to overturn a Massachusetts law
that limits takeover attempts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
