<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0414</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Plummets, Gold Also Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell in European trading today, reaching
its lowest level against major foreign currencies in more than five
months. Gold prices also fell.
   The slight improvement in the U.S. trade deficit in September,
announced on Wednesday, was not enough to reverse the downward
pressure on the dollar, foreign currency dealers said.
   The U.S. trade deficit narrowed to $10.46 billion from $12.18
billion in August.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell to a 15-year low against the Japanese yen, closing
at 121.52 yen, despite reported central bank intervention.
   Later, in London, it was quoted at 122.00 yen.
   The Bank of Japan reportedly intervened in the market on a
``pretty big'' scale to prevent the dollar's further decline, said
one dealer in Tokyo.
   The bank refused to comment on its activities. But Japanese
Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa called for joint action by monetary
authorities to prop up the sagging dollar, a Finance Ministry
official said on condition of anonymity.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Wednesday's
prices, included: 1.7190 West German marks, down from 1.7230; 1.4425
Swiss francs, down from 1.4465; 5.8745 French francs, down from
5.8975; 1.9399 Dutch guilders, down from 1.9575; 1,280.10 Italian
lire, down from 1,291.00; and 1.2323 Canadian dollars, up from
1.2305.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.8325, 1 cent more expensive
for buyers than late Wednesday's $1.8225, and the pound's highest
level against the dollar since May 31.
   London's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price for
gold of $423.30 a troy ounce at midmorning today, unchanged from the
opening bid, but down from $425.50 bid late Wednesday.
   In Zurich, the bid price was also $423.30, down from $425.40 bid
late Wednesday.
   Bullion dealers in London said gold is languishing in narrow
ranges despite the dollar's weakness, because the precious metal
didn't have enough momentum to break through a strong resistance
level at $426 on Wednesday.
   ``People just became frustrated and took some profits on long
positions Wednesday, and there's not enough business in the European
market today to warrant a good move in either direction,'' one
dealer said.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose 65 cents to close at a bid
$424.34.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $6.32 a troy ounce,
down from Wednesday's $6.39.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
