<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-88 0742EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Japan-Markets     11-17 0462</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Dollar Plummets to 15-Year Low Against Yen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar plummeted to a 15-year low against the
Japanese yen today, despite the Bank of Japan's reported
intervention. But share prices rose on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   The dollar closed at 121.52 yen, down 2.02 yen from Wednesday's
close of 123.54 yen. Opening at 122.40 yen, the currency ranged
between 121.30 and 122.40 yen.
   Today's close was the lowest since the Tokyo market began
floating the exchange rate when the Bretton-Woods system was
abandoned in February 1973. Before then, one dollar was fixed at 360
yen.
   The Bretton-Woods agreement at the end of World War II
established the international currency exchange system in which the
dollar's value was fixed at that of one ounce of gold, and all other
currency rates were pegged to the dollar.
   Dealers attributed the dollar's dive today largely to investors'
pessimism over Washington's ability to reduce its trade deficit and
the central bank's failure to prop up the currency.
   Market sources said the central bank bought dollars
intermittently throughout the day but failed to reverse the
currency's decline because it bought ``only a small amount of dollar
compared to the amount (of) money in the market,'' said Mitsuhiko
Kinugasa of Daiwa Bank.
   The Bank of Japan does not comment on its activities.
   On Wednesday, the U.S. Commerce Department said the nation's
September trade deficit was $10.5 billion, down from $12.27 billion
in August.
   ``But the dollar will keep falling as long as the market
sentiment for the weaker dollar continues,'' said Sumio Fukushima of
Sumitomo Bank.
   Despite the improved U.S. trade deficit, ``it is still large, and
the United States has not shown any signs to attempting to reduce
its deficit further,'' Fukushima said.
   A dealer with the Bank of Tokyo said neither central bank
intervention nor dollar-buying by speculators could stop the
currency's decline.
   ``There are still so many people who want to get rid of the
currency,'' he said, adding he doubted if the dollar ever could
return to the 122-yen level. He also spoke anonymously.
   Meanwhile, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, which closed
Wednesday at 28,996.12, added 80.69 points, or 0.28 percent, to
close above the 29,000 level for the first time. Its finish at
29,076.81 was its fifth straight record high.
   Share prices opened lower in Tokyo following declines in overseas
markets and the dollar's plunge in New York, but gradually rose
toward the end of trading as dealers became interested in a wide
varieties of issues, said Nikko Securities' Yoshio Shimoyama.
   ``But many investors, especially speculative ones, were sitting
on the sidelines to see what happens to the currency market,'' he
said.
   In moderate trading with 850 shares traded on the first section,
electrical issues attracted participants.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
