<HEAD>Rales Brothers Abandon Effort To Buy Interco</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An investment group seeking to buy Interco Inc.
for $2.7 billion has abandoned its tender offer after the St.
Louis-based retailer and manufacturer failed to meet the group's
deadline to begin takeover negotiations.
   Cardinal Acquisition Corp., the Washington-based group controlled
by Mitchell and Steven Rales, had said it would drop its
$74-per-share cash offer at midnight Wednesday and return all
tendered shares if Interco did not agree to give Cardinal
confidential corporate information or enter into buyout talks.
   The Raleses' offer had attracted tenders for 92 percent of
Interco's 35.56 million outstanding shares.
   Interco's stock price fell $1.87{ a share to $63.37{ in composite
New York Stock Exchange trading on Wednesday as traders anticipated
an end to the Raleses' bid.
   An Interco spokesman said the company would proceed with its
plans for a $2.8 billion restructuring that was valued at $76 a
share, including a $30.80, one-time cash and securities dividend to
shareholders.
   However, the legal maneuvering resulting from the bid was not
over.
   The Delaware Supreme Court is scheduled to consider on Nov. 30 an
appeal of a lower court ruling that declared Interco's ``poison
pill'' takeover defense illegal.
   Interco shareholders also have filed suits against the company
charging they were denied the full value of their stock by
management's refusal to accept the Raleses' bid.
   A spokesman for the Raleses declined comment on their future
plans.
   However, the Wall Street Journal reported today there were
indications the brothers might increase their holdings in Interco.
Lawyers for Interco told the Journal they had been notified the
Raleses were seeking federal clearance to acquire more shares in the
company.
   The Raleses currently own 3.2 million _ or 8.7 percent _ of
Interco's stock.
   Interco has rebuffed the brothers' overtures since their initial
$64-a-share offer in July.
   The restructuring plan, which would put Interco deeply into debt,
would result in the sale of its Ethan Allen furniture division and
other assets.
   Other Interco lines include Florsheim shoes, Converse sneakers
and London Fog outerwear.
   Interco employs about 54,000 people nationwide and had sales of
$3.34 billion last year.
</TEXT>
