<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market rallied today, attracting some
buyers at its lowest level since late summer.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which had fallen nearly
89 points over the previous six sessions, rose 11.56 to 2,050.14 in
the first half hour today.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by about 5 to 3 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 618 up, 370 down and
461 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 20.97 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   Analysts said buying was encouraged by word that many central
banks around the world were moving to support the dollar in foreign
exchange.
   The dollar, which has fallen sharply in recent days, hovered
early today near post-World War II lows against the Japanese yen.
   Brokers also said some traders were ``bargain hunting'' among
stocks whose prices have fallen from their 1988 highs reached last
month.
   However, they added, enthusiasm for stocks continued to be
restrained by high yields available on short-term interest-bearing
investments such as Treasury bills.
   Gainers among the blue chips included General Electric, up { at
43; General Motors, up } at 80; American Express, up | at 26~, and
International Business Machines, up ] at 115~.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
.63 to 149.59. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was down .07 at 286.23.
   On Wednesday the Dow Jones industrial average dropped 38.59 to
2,038.58, its lowest close since it stood at 2,002.31 on Sept. 1.
   Declining issues outnumbered advances by more than 4 to 1 on the
NYSE, with 296 up, 1,216 down and 443 unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 161.71 million shares, against 115.17
million in the previous session.
