<HEAD>Pernod Apparently Wins Battle For Irish Distillers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pernod Ricard SA apparently won Thursday a
months-long takeover battle for Irish Distillers Group PLC,
Ireland's biggest whiskey maker, when Britain's Panel on Takeovers
and Mergers said the bidder had not breached any takeover rules.
   That means Pernod's offer of 285 million Irish punts, or 450
Irish pence a share, apparently prevails over Grand Metropolitan
PLC's higher offer of 322 million punts, or 525 Irish pence a share.
   Pernod's bid is the equivalent of $442 million.
   Irish Distillers shares fell 46 British pence to 378 pence on
London's Stock Exchange following the announcement.
   Pernod ``is obviously pleased that the ruling has gone its way
and looks forward to completing the offer,'' said a Pernod spokesman
in London, adding that the French liquor company currently holds
more than 53 percent of Irish Distillers' shares.
   The spokesman, who was not identified in accordance with British
practice, said he was confident Pernod would obtain clearance from
the Irish Ministry of Industry and Commerce, which is investigating
the offer on competitive, public interest, regional employment and
other grounds.
   The British takeover panel was ruling on whether Pernod
improperly obtained binding agreements from some Irish Distillers'
shareholders.
   Pernod has previously said it would release shareholders from
these commitments if the panel ruled against the French company. But
the panel, in a lengthy statement, said Pernod wouldn't be obliged
to do so.
   Grand Met spokesman Tim Halford said the British company had no
intention of disposing of its 25.1 percent holding in Irish
Distillers.
   ``We're actively buying shares at the moment to reaffirm our
interest in Irish Distillers,'' Halford said.
   Analysts said Grand Met's next move as a minority shareholder
likely would be an attempt to negotiate the purchase of one of Irish
Distillers' whiskey brands, or even a joint venture agreement with
Pernod.
   Irish Distillers' brands include Jameson's and Paddy whiskeys.
   ``Grand Met have said all along that they were interested in an
internationally known whiskey brand,'' said Ron Littleboy, an
analyst with Nomura Research Institute in London.
</TEXT>
