<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-88 1140EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-HollyFarms 1stLd-Writethru   11-17 0494</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Holly Farms, 1st Ld-Writethru,0515</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Holly Agrees To Be Acquired by ConAgra</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Rewrites thruout to fix style on ConAgra, update with
late-morning trading, further comment from Holly Farms and ConAgra,
no comment from Tyson.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Holly Farms Corp., which has been fending off a
hostile takeover bid by a rival poultry producer, said today it
agreed to be acquired by agriculture conglomerate ConAgra Inc. in a
stock-swap deal worth around $1 billion.
   The merger was unanimously approved by the boards of directors of
both companies and is now subject to stockholders' agreement.
   Under the definitive pact, each of Holly Farm's 18.1 million
common shares outstanding would be exchanged for between 1.875
shares and 2 shares of ConAgra shares, depending on market
fluctuations, Lee Taylor, president of Memphis, Tenn.-based Holly
Farms, said in a brief interview.
   Based on ConAgra's close of $28.87{ a share on the New York Stock
Exchange on Wednesday, the deal would be valued at around $1.04
billion. By late morning the stock had fallen to $28.
   Holly Farms slipped 12{ cents a share to $52.62{ in early trading.
   Earlier this month, Holly Farms rejected as inadequate a hostile
$940 million bid, or $52 a share, from rival Tyson Foods Inc., the
nation's largest poultry producer.
   Springdale, Ark.-based Tyson has been trying since mid-October to
take over Holly Farms, but directors of the Memphis-based company
have spurned those advances.
   A secretary at Tyson's headquarters said no executvies were
available for immediate comment.
   Executives of Holly Farms and Tyson had met earlier this week,
but there was no comment from either side on what was discussed.
   In a statement, Taylor said the ConAgra deal ``provides our
stockholders with significantly higher value than any other
available alternative.''
   ``Our stockholders will not only receive a significant premium
for their stock but will continue to participate in Holly Farms'
future economic success as ConAgra stockholders,'' Taylor said.
   ConAgra, based in Omaha, Neb., said it expected to issue between
33.9 million and 36.2 million shares in the merger transaction. It
currently has 80.1 million common shares outstanding.
   The company said it expected shareholders of both companies to
vote on the agreement before the end of January.
   The terms of the agreement also gave ConAgra an option to
purchase certain Holly Farm assets. In addition, Holly Farms agreed
to pay a fee and expenses if the merger was not completed under
certain conditions.
   Two Holy Farms directors would join ConAgra's board.
   ConAgra Chairman Charles M. Harper said the deal was ``an
excellent strategic fit in terms of our businesses and our people.''
   Holly Farms is a diversified foods company with about half of its
sales in chicken. The company had total sales of $1.6 billion last
year. Tyson's 1987 sales totaled $1.8 billion.
   ConAgra operates in many segments of the food industry. Its
products include crop protection chemicals, animal health care
products as well as flour and grains and seafood and poultry
products.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
