<1ST_LINE>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   11-17 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Open Lower On Slack Demand</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened lower today on
the Chicago Board of Trade in continued selling that analysts said
was linked to disappointment over the slow pace of grain sales for
export.
   Prices of grain and soybean futures have been in a downtrend
since last Thursday, one day after the Agriculture Department
revised upward its 1988 production estimates for corn and soybeans.
   The USDA report signaled that prices would have to drop to
encourage more foreign buying, said Cathy Leow, assistant vice
president of grain futures trading with Thomson McKinnon Securities
Inc. in New York.
   ``It basically told anyone still friendly to the market: `No way,
buddy, at least not in the short term. Demand has got to get a lot
larger.'
   ``I think people are just basically giving up on a lot of
positions they've held for quite a while,'' she said.
   In early trading, wheat was 2{ cents lower to { cent higher with
the contract for delivery in December at $4.08\ a bushel; corn was
1{ cents to 2{ cents lower with December at $2.61} a bushel; oats
were 1 cent to 2{ cents lower with December at $2.03 a bushel;
soybeans were 4\ cents to 6 cents lower with November at $7.39 a
bushel.
   Livestock futures were lower in early trading on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange but pork-belly futures were mostly higher.
   Live cattle were .03 ent to .37 cent lower with December at 73.22
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .02 cent to .37 cent lower with
November at 81.67 cents a pound; hogs were .15 cent to .45 cent
lower with December at 40.90 cents a pound; and frozen pork bellies
were .02 cent lower to .28 cent higher with February at 44.60 cents
a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mostly lower on Wednesday.
</TEXT>
