<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Britain-Plessey     11-17 0310</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Plessey,0324</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Takeover Target Plessey Posts 6 Percent Profit Gain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Plessey Co. PLC, a giant electronics company which
became the target of a hostile takeover bid on Wednesday, reported
Thursday its first-half earnings rose 6 percent, constrained by
recent acquisitions of its own.
   General Electric Co. PLC and Siemens AG launched a joint 1.7
billion-pound, or $3.1 billion, bid Wednesday for Plessey, which
``emphatically rejected'' the offer.
   Separately, in Brussels Thursday, the European Commission said
European Economic Community antitrust officials would look into the
proposed merger between the three European electronics giants.
   A commission spokesman said the combination would be ``an
operation of a European dimension'' and therefore of interest to the
EEC antitrust officials. Under the EEC treaty, the commission is
empowered to probe whether mergers satisfy competition rules.
   In its earnings statement, which made no mention of the bid,
Plessey said its earnings for the six months ended Sept. 30 came to
47.3 million pounds, compared with 44.6 million pounds in the same
period a year earlier.
   Revenue climbed 14.8 percent to 692.6 million pounds from 603.4
million pounds.
   The results were at the bottom end of a range of analysts'
forecasts.
   ``The important steps of the period under review give me
encouragement to confirm my belief that we are back on the growth
path,'' said Plessey Chairman Sir John Clark.
   ``I must emphasize, however, that much remains to be done in
integrating our acquisitions,'' he said.
   ``A priority within the company is to accelerate the benefits of
the acquisition program while at the same time reducing debt service
cost.''
   Recent Plessey acquisitions have included U.S.-based Electronic
Systems Division, purchased from Singer Co. for $310 million, and
Hoskyns Group PLC, a British computer services concern, bought for
164 million pounds.
   These purchases have raised Plessey's interest payments, cutting
into the company's profit, it said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
