<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street Noon,0316</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market was mixed today in a session
marked by some spotty buying of blue chips.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 big-name industrials, which had
fallen nearly 89 points over the previous six sessions, rose 7.47 to
2,046.05 by noontime on Wall Street.
   But losers outnumbered gainers by about 8 to 7 in nationwide
trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 586 up, 662
down and 564 unchanged.
   Analysts said buying was encouraged by word that many central
banks around the world were moving to support the dollar in foreign
exchange.
   The dollar, which has fallen sharply in recent days, hovered
early today near post-World War II lows against the Japanese yen.
   Brokers also said some traders were ``bargain hunting'' among
stocks whose prices have fallen from their 1988 highs reached last
month.
   However, they added, enthusiasm for stocks continued to be
restrained by high yields available on short-term interest-bearing
investments such as Treasury bills.
   Gainers among the blue chips included General Electric, up ] at
42~; General Motors, up { at 79}, and Sears Roebuck, up { at 40{.
International Business Machines was steady at 115{ and American
Telephone & Telegraph was unchanged at 27|.
   Japanese stocks were strong as the Tokyo market hit new peaks.
Matsushita Electric, which projected a 28 percent increase in
consolidated net income for its current fiscal year, climbed 7{ to
192}.
   Honda Motor gained 4} to 156} and Kyocera 4\ to 79.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
.30 to 149.26. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was down .70 at 285.60.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 66.51 million shares at noontime,
down from 73.33 million at the same point Wednesday.
</TEXT>
