<1ST_LINE>u f PM-EconomyRdp 2ndLd-Writethru   11-17 0696</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Housing Construction Up Sharply In October</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: ADDS new grafs 1-3 to UPDATE with dollar, stocks recovering;
picks up 2nd graf pvs bg'ng, The Commerce ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The battered dollar rebounded in early trading today, bolstered
by a wave of coordinated dollar purchases by central banks, while
the stock market struggled to its feet after a sharp drop on
Wednesday.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which has fallen nearly
89 points over the previous six sessions, was up 7.47 points at
2,046.05 at noon on Wall Street.
   The dollar was quoted at around 122.68 Japanese yen in New York
trading, up from 122.24 yen late Wednesday. That had been the U.S.
currency's lowest close against the yen in New York trading since
modern exchange rates were established in the late 1940s.
   The government reported today that housing construction jumped
7.2 percent in October, the biggest increase in eight months.
   The Commerce Department said new homes and apartments were built
at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 1.55 million units last
month, up from a 1.45 million rate in September. All regions of the
nation, except the Northeast, had posted gains, it said.
   The huge increase followed a revised 0.8 percent decline in
September and a 1.1 percent drop in August. Previously, the
department said housing starts increased 1.5 percent in September
and fell 3.1 percent in August.
   The October jump was the biggest since a 9.9 percent increase in
February. Analysts had been expecting a decline of about 1 percent.
   In another report Wednesday, the Commerce Department said the
U.S. trade deficit narrowed by 17 percent in September, to $10.5
billion. But the figures refused to calm jittery financial markets.
   The dollar plunged Wednesday, bond prices slid and the stock
market tumbled to a 2{-month low in response to the report, which
indicated a smaller decline in the deficit than was expected by many
market participants and analysts.
   The dollar registered its lowest close against the Japanese yen
in New York trading since modern exchange rates were established in
the late 1940s, falling nearly 1 percent to 122.24 yen.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks dropped 38.59
points to 2,038.58, its lowest close since it stood at 2,002.31 on
Sept. 1.
   Overall exports rose in September by $700 million to a record
high $28.2 billion, the Commerce Department said. Imports declined
by 2.5 percent or $1.1 billion to $38.7 billion from a record high
in August.
   The $10.5 billion trade gap for September was down by $1.8
billion from the revised August trade deficit figure of $12.3
billion.
   But neither change was big enough to stem a new selling wave of
dollars by traders who were worried about inflation from an
overheating economy and skeptical of President-elect George Bush's
promise to reduce the federal budget deficit without any tax
increases.
   Many analysts had expected the trade deficit to drop below $10
billion in September, as it did in May and July.
   When it did not, ``more general concerns'' over the federal
budget deficit and the willingness of foreigners to keep financing
U.S. consumer habits triggered Wednesday's selling spree on
financial markets, said David Wyss, chief financial economist for
Data Resources Inc. of Lexington, Mass.
   ``Exports were up, imports were down. The reaction should have
been positive,'' Wyss said. ``Although the trade deficit has
improved, the improvement seems to have stalled out at about $11
billion (deficit) a month. Add to that figures on growth that we've
seen in the past couple of weeks and the market has good reason to
be pessimistic.''
   In other economic developments Wednesday:
   _The Federal Reserve Board reported that the operating rate at
U.S. factories, mines and utilities in October rose to the highest
level in 8{ years.
   _The Commerce Department said business inventories rose sharply
relative to sales in September, a sign of economic weakness.
Analysts discounted the significance of the report, noting that
sales have picked up since then.
   _The value of U.S. agricultural exports jumped 26 percent to a
four-year high of $35.2 billion in the fiscal year that ended Sept.
30, the Agriculture Department reported.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
