<1ST_LINE>r f BC-MillerAds     11-17 0206</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Miller Ads,0214</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Miller Changes Ad Agency For Sagging High Life</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Miller Brewing Co. is changing advertising
agencies for its flagship Miller High Life brand, whose sales have
been falling since the early part of the decade.
   Charles Schmid, senior vice president of marketing for Miller,
said Wednesday that Leo Burnett USA in Chicago would take over the
advertising of High Life from J. Walter Thompson, which has had the
account since 1985.
   Thompson has been given an undisclosed new product assignment and
will continue working on the Lowenbrau and Matilda Bay Cooler
accounts, Miller officials said.
   Schmid said Thompson's advertising campaign featuring the slogan,
``Stop and Taste the High Life,'' has done a good job strengthening
the product.
   ``It will now be Leo Burnett's challenge to create advertising
that builds strong sales momentum for the brand,'' he said.
   High Life's sales peaked in the early 1980s above 20 million
barrels, but fell below 10 million last year.
   Beer Marketer's Insights, an industry newsletter, said Miller
spent $15.7 million on the advertising account for the first six
months of this year. For all of 1987, Miller spent $25.3 million on
High Life, less than half the $67.7 million spent in 1986.
</TEXT>
