<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-88 1439EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     11-17 0411</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Dollar-Gold,0428</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Ends Higher In Europe After Reported Intervention</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: An AMs version planned by 5:30 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar ended slightly higher in hectic
European trading Thursday, pushed up by reported intervention by
U.S. and European central banks.
   Gold prices fell.
   The Bank of Japan intervened heavily during the Tokyo trading
day, but the intervention was largely shrugged off by the market,
dealers said.
   The U.S. Federal Reserve began to buy dollars for yen in the New
York morning, and the dollar-buying spree was quickly bolstered by
the entry of the Deutsche Bundesbank, and then the British, Swiss,
French, Italian, Austrian and other central banks, dealers said.
   The Bundesbank's participation added a lot of weight to the round
of intervention, since this is the first time the West German
central bank has intervened in the dollar's latest downward move,
dealers said.
   The intervention appeared to be moderate, but was spread widely
among banks in order to have the biggest impact possible for the
amount of money spent, they said.
   Dealers said they had expected concerted intervention to
materialize, especially after so many warnings in recent days by top
monetary officials, who either reiterated their desire for exchange
rate stability, or said they weren't in favor of a lower dollar.
   But although the intervention was expected to keep the dollar
steady for a while, dealers say they will soon be looking for a
chance to sell dollars again.
   In London, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost
$1.8227 to buy one pound, lower than late Wednesday's $1.8225.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Wednesday:
1.7298 West German marks, up from 1.7230; 1.4518 Swiss francs, up
from 1.4465; 5.9075 French francs, up from 5.8975; 1.9560 Dutch
guilders, down from 1.9575; 1,291.75 Italian lire, up from 1,291.00;
and 1.2335 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2305.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell to 121.52 yen. Later, in London, it was quoted at
122.65 yen.
   Gold fell in London to a late bid price of $422.00 a troy ounce,
from $425.50 bid late Wednesday.
   In Zurich, gold fell to close at a bid $421.00 an ounce, compared
with $425.40 bid late Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose 65 cents to close at a bid
$424.34 an ounce.
   Silver bullion prices fell in London to a late bid price of $6.29
a troy ounce, compared with Wednesday's $6.39.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881117-0282 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-88 1517EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-LACounty-Japan     11-17 0255</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-LA County-Japan,0264</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>County Borrowing $100 Million From Japan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a unique 10-year deal, Los Angeles County
is borrowing $100 million from two Japanese lenders in what
officials described as a first between a foreign nation and a local
government entity.
   The county will borrow $100 million in yen under the arrangement
with the Nippon Life Insurance Co. and the Long Term Credit Bank of
Japan Ltd.
   ``This is our first borrowing in a foreign market and the first
state or local government borrowing of this nature,'' county Chief
Administrative Officer Richard B. Dixon said from Tokyo on Wednesday.
   ``We have been shopping for opportunities in the taxable market,
and this is the first and best opportunity we have found,'' said
Dixon.
   The county will invest the funds in ``high-grade debt
securities'' and use the profits to help reduce the unfunded
liability in the employees' retirement system, Dixon said.
   Dixon said a currency swap agreement will also allow the county
to repay the loan in dollars rather than yen as a hedge against any
risks if the foreign currency fluctuates.
   Because of the 1986 Tax Reform Act, the county has been seeking
alternatives to the domestic market. The law eliminated local
government's ability to issue tax-exempt pension bonds.
   Additionally, interest rates are lower. Dixon said the loan will
be repaid in dollars at the 10-year U.S. Treasury note rate, now
9.01 percent, plus .58 percent. At today's rates, these percentages
are lower than the U.S. prime rate of 10 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
