<1ST_LINE>u f PM-AirFares 2ndLd-Writethru   11-17 0609</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Air Fares, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Airlines Follow Continental Move on MaxSavers; Others Mull
Action</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: RECASTS grafs 1-7 to UPDATE with Delta, American following,
edit to conform; picks up 8th graf pvs bg'ng, Northwest Airlines ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The decision by Continental Airlines and other
U.S. carriers to boost most of their lowest discount fares reflects
current strength in passenger traffic, analysts say.
   Several major airlines said Wednesday and today that they were
following Continental's revamping of the popular fares, used by most
vacation travelers. United Airlines, the nation's largest carrier,
is matching Continental's action throughout its route system, said
spokeswoman Sara Dornacker in Chicago. She said the average increase
on the so-called MaxSavers to be hiked would be around $15 each way.
   Other airlines matching the MaxSaver changes through their entire
systems include American Airlines, Delta Air Lines and Trans World
Airlines Inc.
   Northwest Airlines partially followed the action, changing around
30,000 MaxSaver fares between different cities, said Northwest
spokesman Red Tyler in Eagan, Minn. He said the Continental changes
involve more than 100,000 such fares.
   ``We continue to review the others,'' Tyler said. ``There is
still indecision in the industry.''
   Houston-based Continental notified travel agents on Tuesday night
and Wednesday that it would revamp its MaxSaver program to base
fares on the length of a flight. Competition on individual routes,
not mileage, had determined the fares in the past.
   Under the new formula, due to take effect next Wednesday,
MaxSaver fares for longer flights generally would be raised while
those for shorter hauls would mostly be reduced.
   The changes apparently raised about roughly two-thirds of
Continental's MaxSaver fares and cut the remaining MaxSavers.
   They followed by a few days plans initiated by Continental and
matched by other big airlines to drop another category of discount
air fares, the ``junk fares'' available four to seven days before a
flight and used mainly by business travelers.
   Like Continental, most of Northwest's fare changes were
increases, Tyler said. He said Northwest so far has only matched
Continental in the markets where the two airlines compete directly.
In other markets, Northwest will wait to see whether the other
carriers follow Continental's lead, Tyler said.
   The hikes in both advance-purchase MaxSavers and last-minute junk
fares reflect the recent trend toward higher air fares propelled by
increasing passenger traffic.
   ``Consumers definitely are paying higher prices,'' said Andrew
Geller, an airline analyst at Provident National Bank in
Philadelphia.
   Airline fares are up an average 8 percent from a year ago, he
said.
   Continental, which customarily has been a pacesetter in cutting
fares, has started to enjoy stronger traffic _ allowing it to switch
directions.
   The airline used to slash fares to attract more passengers, and
its moves quickly were mimicked by the other big carriers in an
effort to remain competitive. Now, Continental's improving traffic
has made it a leader in fare hikes rather than cuts, at least for
the moment.
   That has allowed Continental to switch its emphasis from filling
seats with cheap fares to offering better service, said Ned Walker,
a spokesman for the airline.
   ``Service has the utmost attention at Continental,'' he said.
``After safety, the focus is on service.''
   Walker cited monthly statistics compiled by the Department of
Transportation showing recent improvements in Continental's on-time
performance and other aspects of its service.
   Continental may be ``trying to position itself in the
price-service array'' by getting closer to full fares, suggested
John Pincavage, who follows the industry for PaineWebber Inc.
   He said the big test of the airlines' strength will come in
January and February, when passenger traffic is seasonally weak.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
