<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0202</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soybeans Futures Plunge To 6-Month Low; Grains Follow</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures plunged to their lowest prices in
more than six months Thursday after cracking an important technical
resistance point.
   The grain markets followed soybeans lower with corn futures also
posting steep losses.
   Soybean prices had opened modestly lower in a continuation of the
downward trend that had characterized the market since late last
week. Analysts linked the early selling to heavy showers overnight
in soybean-producing areas of South America and to the relatively
slow pace of soybean sales for export.
   But analysts said selling accelerated as soybeans for delivery in
November approached $7.40 a bushel, the low of the market's last
significant bottom on July 28, and speculators pushed the price
through that important barrier.
   At the close, wheat was 1\ cents to 6{ cents lower with December
at $4.09 a bushel; corn was 2{ cents to 4} cents lower with December
at $2.59{ a bushel; oats were 2\ cents lower to 1{ cents higher with
December at $2.03 a bushel; and soybeans were 17\ cents to 25\ cents
lower with November at $7.19 a bushel.
</TEXT>
