<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Earns-Campbell     11-17 0283</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Campbell,0295</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Posts Earnings Decline for 1st Qtr</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Campbell Soup. Co. said Thursday its
first-quarter earnings fell 26.9 percent from results a year ago
which were swelled by a one-time accounting adjustment.
   The food company said excluding the accounting change, its
results were up 11.1 percent compared with a year ago.
   Net earnings for the three months ended Oct. 30 fell to $69.4
million, or 54 cents per share, compared with $94.9 million, or 73
cents a share, a year ago. The 1987 results included an accounting
change for income taxes that added $32.5 million, or 25 cents a
share, to net income for the quarter.
   Without the change, the company would have reported a profit of
$62.4 million, or 48 cents a share, in the first three months of
1987.
   Revenue for the quarter rose 13 percent to $1.33 billion from
$1.18 billion a year earlier.
   The company said operating earninbgs rose 21 percent at Campbell
U.S.A., the Camden-based firm's largest division.
   It said its V8 vegetable juice had a 50 percent increase in
volume, while Prego spaghetti sauce increased 27 percent and
Franco-American pasta 12 percent.
   ``Increased soup marketing efforts to consumers are expected to
increase per capita consumption this year, although first-quarter
soup sales were flat because of promotional timing differences,''
Campbell President R. Gordon McGovern said.
   McGovern said several acquisitions last year helped boost sales.
Marie's salad dressing sparked a 39 percent in the company's fresh
product unit, while the volume of Vlasic Foods increased by 36
percent.
   Reflecting the acquisition of Freshbake, a United Kingdom-based
frozen foods business, Campbell International had a 30 percent
increase in sales and operating earnings increased 13 percent.
</TEXT>
