<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-88 1646EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Eastern     11-17 0470</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Eastern,0485</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Payment To Continental Angers Eastern Labor Leader</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A union leader was angered to learn that Eastern
Airlines, which must request rescheduling of $300 million in loans,
has made multimillion-dollar payments to its non-union sister
carrier, Continental Airlines.
   ``We're talking about $50 million more that is being upstreamed,
and yet they continue going out and telling the world this horror
story about their financial problems,'' Charles E. Bryan told a
meeting of labor leaders Wednesday.
   Bryan is president of the Machinists local at Eastern, the
airline's largest union. Eastern and Continental are both
subsidiaries of Texas Air Corp., the nation's biggest airline
company.
   Eastern's latest quarterly filing with the Securities and
Exchange Commission showed it paid Continental $17.5 million in
September for frequent flier redemptions. It also paid $19 million
to Houston-based Continental for strike contingency services.
   Bryan also was critical of a $21.1 million loan from Eastern to
Bar Harbour Airlines, a commuter carrier that is another Texas Air
subsidiary.
   Eastern spokesman Robin Matell called the $17.5 million frequent
flier payment to Continental ``a perfectly legitimate transaction''
under the two airlines' joint frequent flier program, because more
Eastern frequent fliers were redeeming their award certificates with
Continental than the other way around.
   Texas Air announced recently that the strike contingency program
is being discontinued because management doesn't consider an Eastern
strike likely. Eastern's Machinists and management have been in
federal mediation over the union's contract since January.
   Bryan and other union leaders at Eastern say Texas Air Chairman
Frank Lorenzo has been bleeding away Eastern's assets since he took
control two years ago. Eastern has paid Texas Air tens of millions
of dollars in management fees, along with fees for use of the
computerized reservations system that formerly belonged to Eastern
and is a separate Texas Air subsidiary.
   Bryan has urged Lorenzo to sell Eastern to an employee-backed
group. Financier Carl Icahn, the owner and chairman of Trans World
Airlines Inc., recently expressed interest in buying Eastern and met
with representatives of the Machinists and other Eastern unions.
   Eastern's SEC report also said Texas Air paid $16 million in
expenses to Eastern left over from its 1986 takeover.
   Eastern, awaiting government approval of a $365 million sale of
its northeastern shuttle to New York developer Donald Trump, said it
must make such asset sales to stay alive, unless it can reduce labor
costs. Eastern has reported $233 million in net losses in the first
three quarters of this year.
   Eastern officials plan to meet Friday with French, British and
West German lenders to renegotiate the airline's debt payments to
avoid a technical default that could result in lenders demanding
quicker payments of the loans.
   ``This situation has happened in the past,'' said Eastern
spokeswoman Karen Ceremsak. ``We don't expect it to be a problem.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
