<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Visnews-NBC     11-17 0337</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Visnews-NBC,0350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reuters To Sell Visnews Stake to NBC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reuters Holdings PLC, the British news and
information services company, is selling a 37.75 percent stake in
its Visnews television news agency to the National Broadcasting Co.
for about $10 million, the companies said Thursday.
   Reuters will issue new Visnews shares to NBC, which is owned by
General Electric Co. of Fairfield, Conn., and operates the NBC
television network, the companies said.
   That will reduce Reuters' stake in Visnews from 88.75 percent to
51 percent while British Broadcasting Co. will continue to hold the
remaining 11.25 percent, they said.
   Under the agreement, NBC will supply Visnews with all its news
programming for broadcasting worldwide for a 10-year period, they
said.
   At the same time, Visnews will supply its news programming to NBC
for broadcasting in the United States, they said.
   NBC and Visnews camera crews are to work closely together
throughout the world, they said.
   Michael Nelson, chairman of Visnews and general manager of
Reuters, said in a statement, ``This alliance of NBC, the leading
U.S. TV network, the BBC and Reuters, the world's largest electronic
publisher, is a major new force in international TV news.''
   Robert C. Wright, president of NBC, said, ``We look forward to
working with our partners, Reuters and the BBC, in what will clearly
be the world's premier global news gathering agency.'
   In New York, NBC spokesman Joe Rutledge said the deal would allow
NBC to cut back on its hiring of free-lancers for foreign news
coverage and give it more flexibility in deploying its own crews. He
said it could ultimately affect fewer than 20 NBC news jobs overseas.
   Separately, Visnews said it has signed a five-year contract with
Rupert Murdoch's Sky Television to provide news programming for its
24-hour Sky News channel in Britain. The contract is valued at about
$55 million.
   Visnews, which was formed in 1957, provides over 400 broadcasting
organizations in 84 countries a daily service seen on an estimated
470 million television sets.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
