<HEAD>Presidential Airways to Buy 16 Boeing Planes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Presidential Airways announced Thursday that it
is buying 16 turboprop aircraft from Boeing Co.'s Canada deHavilland
Division for $180 million.
   The first of the 50-seat Boeing deHavilland Dash 8-300 planes is
scheduled to be delivered to the commuter airline next summer and
the remainder in l990 and l991, Presidential said.
   Presidential Chairman Harold ``Hap'' Pareti said the new aircraft
will allow it to carry more passengers on some of Presidential's
current flights, where it now flies a 19-seat aircraft, and allow it
to open new markets.
   The airline announced earlier this week a profit for the second
consecutive quarter after losing $88 million since l985 when it
began operating.
   Presidential's operations are concentrated through its hub at
Dulles International Airport outside of Washington, where it serves
as a feeder for United Airlines, which also has its major East Coast
hub at Dulles. Presidential flies under the name United Express.
   The addition of the Dash 8-300 aircraft will give Presidential
added flexibility in matching its aircraft with market size. It
already owns eight 90-seat British Aerospace BAe-146s as well as 14
smaller planes capable of carrying l9 passengers.
   Pareti said the new Dash 8-300s will be used on flights within
300 miles of Dulles airport, probably into North and South Carolina,
the Ohio Valley and Connecticut.
</TEXT>
