<FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-88 1712EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-WallStreet 1stLd-Writethru   11-17 0488</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0509</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Blue-chip stocks staged a modest rally Thursday,
but the rest of the market remained in a slump.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which had fallen nearly
89 points over the past six sessions, recovered 13.87 to 2,052.45.
   In contrast, declining issues outnumbered advances by about 4 to
3 in nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks,
with 635 up, 844 down and 496 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 141.28 million
shares, down from 161.71 million in the previous session.
Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including
trades in those stocks on regional exchanges and in the
over-the-counter market, totaled 164.67 million shares.
   Analysts said buying of blue chips was encouraged by word that
central banks around the world were moving to support the dollar in
foreign exchange.
   The dollar, which has fallen sharply in recent days, hovered
early Thursday near post-World War II lows against the Japanese yen.
   Brokers also said some traders were ``bargain hunting'' among
issues whose prices have fallen lately from their 1988 highs reached
last month.
   However, they added, many market participants remained skeptical
that the dollar was ready to launch a sustained turnaround.
   In addition, enthusiasm for stocks continued to be restrained by
high yields available on short-term interest-bearing investments
such as Treasury bills.
