<HEAD>Money Funds Rose $4.53 Billion in Latest Week</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf pvs bgng The rise...CORRECT total to $279.22
billion sted $299.22 billion as sent. Picks up 3rd graf, The
funds'...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assets of the nation's 454 money market mutual
funds rose $4.53 billion to a near-record level in the latest week,
the Investment Company Institute said Thursday.
   The rise, to $279.22 billion in the seven-day period ended
Wednesday, followed a revised $2.67 billion increase in the funds'
assets the previous week, according to the Washington-based mutual
fund trade group.
   The funds' assets hit a record high $280.02 billion in the week
ended Feb. 24.
   The Investment Company Institute said that in the latest week,
assets of 223 general purpose funds rose $1.82 billion to $89.04
billion, assets of 100 broker-dealer funds increased $1.2 billion to
$117.31 billion, and assets of 131 institutional funds rose $1.5
billion to $72.87 billion.
   The seven-day average yield on money market mutual funds rose in
the week ended Tuesday to 7.60 percent from 7.56 percent the
previous week, according to Donoghue's Money Fund Report, a trade
journal based in Holliston, Mass.
   The 30-day average yield rose to 7.57 percent from 7.53 percent,
Donoghue's said.
   The average maturity of the portfolios held by money funds was 37
days, down from 38 days, Donoghue's said.
   Separately, the newsletter Bank Rate Monitor said its survey of
100 leading commercial banks, savings and loan assocations and
savings banks in the nation's 10 largest markets showed the
effective annual yield available on money market accounts was
unchanged for the second week at 6.08 percent as of Wednesday.
   The North Palm Beach, Fla.-based newsletter said the effective
annual yield available on special savings accounts, called Super NOW
accounts, also was unchanged from a week earlier at 5.12 percent.
   Bank Rate Monitor said the effective annual yield was 7.88
percent on six-month certificates of deposit, up from 7.84 the
previous week. Yields were 8.17 percent on 1-year CDs, up from 8.14
percent; 8.35 percent on 2{-year CDs, up from 8.32 percent; and 8.55
percent on 5-year CDs, unchanged from the previous week.
