<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0679</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Troubled Dollar Gets Slight Boost From Intervention</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES M. KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of the most pronounced rounds of central bank
intervention since spring helped stem the dollar's slide Thursday,
but some analysts said the currency would need more help before it
stabilizes.
   Gold prices dipped. Republic National Bank of New York said gold
bullion was bid at $419.75 an ounce at 4 p.m. EST, down from $423.60
late Wednesday.
   Traders said the central banks stepped into the foreign exchange
markets in force to buy up dollars a day after the U.S. currency had
sunk to near historic lows.
   In Tokyo, where the trading day begins, the dollar fell to 121.52
yen, nearly a 40-year low, despite heavy intervention by the Bank of
Japan.
   Later, in London, the dollar moved to 122.65 yen, and then in New
York it settled at 122.155 yen, off slightly from late Wednesday's
122.24.
   The dollar's lack of response against the yen was attributed to
the frequency of the Bank of Japan's recent intervention in the
market. Buying by European central banks, which intensified through
the day, was more unusual and helped the U.S. currency move higher
against most other major currencies in late New York trading.
   The participation of the Bundesbank was particularly important
since it was the first time West Germany's central bank had
intervened in the dollar's recent decline, traders noted.
   It was the most widespread intervention in the market since a big
sell-off of dollars last April in reaction to a bad monthly trade
report.
   Although the trade deficit showed modest improvement in the
latest report issued Wednesday, the dollar sustained heavy losses
nonetheless. Wednesday's slide convinced some traders that
intervention by the central banks was inevitable.
   ``The market had been expecting it for some time,'' said Stephen
Leach, currency analyst for Chemical Bank in New York. ``The
question was when.''
   Leach noted the timing of the intervention also coincided with
the Treasury's auction of $9 billion in new 30-year bonds Thursday.
Some analysts who follow the credit markets had feared that the
dollar's recent weakness would scare foreign investors away from the
auction.
   But analysts said more intervention would be necessary to
stabilize the dollar. The market is also looking for clear policy
statements from President-elect George Bush on what his
administration will do to cut the trade and budget deficits.
   Worries about the twin deficits have kept pressure on the dollar
since the election was decided last week.
   The dollar fell against the British pound in London, where it
cost $1.8227 to buy one pound, more than late Wednesday's $1.8225.
But the pound fetched $1.82875 in late New York trading, less than
$1.83375 late Wednesday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Wednesday
were 1.7230 West German marks, up from 1.7164; 1.4470 Swiss francs,
up from 1.4422; 1.23075 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2296; 5.8915
French francs, up from 5.8770; and 1,283.75 Italian lire, up from
1,277.75.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Wednesday:
1.7298 West German marks, up from 1.7230; 1.4518 Swiss francs, up
from 1.4465; 5.9075 French francs, up from 5.8975; 1.9560 Dutch
guilders, down from 1.9575; 1,291.75 Italian lire, up from 1,291.00;
and 1.2335 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2305.
   Among precious metals prices on the New York Commodity Exchange,
gold bullion for current delivery slipped to $420.10 an ounce,
compared with $424.50 late Wednesday.
   Gold fell in London to a late bid price of $422.00 a troy ounce,
from $425.50 bid late Wednesday. In Zurich, gold fell to $421.00 an
ounce, compared with $425.40 bid late Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose 65 cents to $424.34 an ounce.
   Silver bullion for current delivery was quoted at the Comex at
$6.170 an ounce, down from $6.277 late Wednesday. Silver prices fell
in London to a late bid price of $6.29 a troy ounce, compared with
Wednesday's $6.39.
</TEXT>
