<HEAD>Soybean Market Collapses To 6-Month Low</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices plunged to their lowest levels in more
than six months Thursday after cracking an important resistance
point.
   On other markets, grain, cotton, precious metals, energy,
livestock, meat and stock-index futures all were lower while copper
futures advanced.
   Soybeans for delivery in November settled at $7.19{ a bushel on
the Chicago Board of Trade, a loss of 25} cents from Wednesday's
final price. It was the lowest settlement price for a near-month
soybean contract since May 13, when the May contract finished at
$7.19{.
   Soybean prices had opened modestly lower in a continuation of the
downward trend that has characterized the market since late last
week. Analysts linked the early selling to heavy showers overnight
in soybean-producing areas of South America and to the relatively
slow pace of soybean sales for export.
   But selling accelerated as November soybeans approached $7.40 a
bushel, a price not seen since July 28, and speculators pushed the
price through that important barrier.
   ``When you hit that level, you started seeing a lot of
liquidation in the market,'' said Cathy Leow, an assistant vice
president of Thomson McKinnon Securities Inc. in New York.
   Wheat settled 1{ cents to 6{ cents lower with the contract for
delivery in December at $4.09\ a bushel; corn was 3\ cents to 5
cents lower with December at $2.59\ a bushel; oats were } cents to
1\ cents lower with December at $2.04 a bushel; and soybeans were
17} cents to 25} cents lower with November at $7.19{ a bushel.
   Cotton futures finished sharply lower on the New York Cotton
Exchange in a technically inspired sell-off.
   Analyst Ernest Simon of Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. said the
cotton market was due for a correction.
   ``The fundamentals have been bearish for a long time,'' he said.
``We've got large crops throughout the world and we have a slower
offtake (from existing stocks) than we had last season. In spite of
that, the market has gone up and stayed up. Now it's finally coming
down,'' he said.
   Cotton settled 1.5 cents to 1.75 cents lower with December at
53.20 cents a pound.
   Copper futures rebounded strongly on New York's Commodity
Exchange after falling for four of the five previous sessions.
   Analysts attributed the rise to renewed supply concerns prompted
by reports of production problems at a state-owned mine in Chile and
the terrorist bombing of the Peruvian Mine Owners Association
offices in Lima, Peru.
   Copper settled 1.5 cents to 5.3 cents higher with December at
$1.333 a pound.
   Silver futures prices fell sharply for the third straight day on
New York's Commodity Exchange as the market adjusted to recent
losses in the gold market and to its own bearish fundamentals, said
James Steel, an analyst with Refco Inc. in New York.
   Silver settled 11 cents to 11.8 cents lower with December at
$6.19 a troy ounce; gold was $4 to $4.50 lower with December at
$421.10 a troy ounce.
   Energy futures weakened substantially on growing pessimism about
OPEC's ability to reach an agreement to limit crude-oil output and
force prices higher, analysts said.
   Oil ministers of the 13 members of the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries gathered Thursday in Vienna to start a series of
meetings on capping their runaway production.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 38 cents to 91 cents
lower with December at $13.29 a barrel; heating oil was 1.50 cents
to 1.86 cents lower with December at 42.97 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .85 cent to 1.99 cents lower with December at 45.65
cents a gallon.
   Cattle futures fell sharply late in the session on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange, pressured by aggressive speculative selling on
bearish technical signals, analysts said.
   Expectations of a seasonal decline in demand for beef also
contributed to the sell-off.
   A surge of last-minute selling drove hog futures to a sharply
lower close while weakening cash markets weighed on both the hogs
and the pork bellies, analysts said.
   Live cattle settled .50 cent to 1.17 cents lower with December at
72.67 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .02 cent to .75 cent lower
with November at 81.67 cents a pound; live hogs were .38 cent to
1.10 cents lower with December at 40.70 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .78 cent to .90 cent lower with February at 43.65 cents
a pound.
   Stock-index futures retreated slightly on the Chicago Merc, where
the contract for December delivery of the Standard & Poor's 500
settled .40 point lower at 264.65.
</TEXT>
