<HEAD>MCI Going After Pay Phone Market</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   MCI Communications Corp. said Thursday it is
launching a major campaign to claim a piece of the $2 billion-a-year
market in long-distance calls from pay telephones.
   The marketing drive is an effort to capitalize on a recent
federal court ruling that ordered the local Bell operating companies
to stop discriminating in favor of American Telephone & Telegraph
Co. on collect, third-party and coin-paid long-distance calls placed
from public phones and calls charged to Bell company credit cards.
   The court ordered the Bell companies by Jan. 1 to let owners and
managers of public pay phones choose a long-distance carrier.
   MCI, the nation's second-largest long-distance company after
AT&T, said it will offer a full range of basic operator services to
pay phone users beginning next year. Also, non-MCI customers using
pay phones pre-subscribed to MCI would be able to use Bell calling
cards.
   The company said it will target its campaign at owners and
managers of pay phones at airports, hotels, universities, government
agencies, convention centers and other facilities with large amounts
of pay phone use.
</TEXT>
