<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Amfac     11-17 0296</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Amfac,0307</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Amfac Shareholders Approve Acquisition By Chicago's JMB Realty</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACK SCHREIBMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shareholders of Amfac Inc., Hawaii's largest
private landowner, on Thursday approved a $49 a share cash buyout
valued at $920 million by Chicago-based JMB Realty.
   The acquistion by JMB, America's largest real estate syndicator
and a manager of $20 billion in U.S. and Canadian properties, will
be consummated Friday in Hawaii, Amfac announced.
   Amfac common stock trading on the New York and Pacific Stock
exchanges will be suspended as of the opening of business Monday.
   The acquisition was approved by 86.6 percent of shareholders.
   Amfac chief officer and president Richard L. Griffith said, ``We
are delighted with the outcome of (Thursday's) meeting, which
demonstrates the support of our shareholders for our efforts to
maximize their investment in Amfac. We now look forward to a new,
rewarding association with JMB.''
   Neil G. Bluhm, president of JMB, said, ``...We're delighted to
become associated with a premier Hawaii-based land, retail and
resort company. Amfac has a long and proud history...this
acquisition marks JMB's first venture in Hawaii, the hub of
burgeoning Pacific rim economy.''
   The Hawaiian conglomerate owns or leases 151,000 acres, much of
it used to grow sugar cane, and also has interests in retailing,
resorts, agriculture, property management and electrical
distribution. Amfac's Hawaii-based Liberty House department store
alone has been valued at around $250 million.
   JMB has invested nearly $4.5 billion for several major real
estate businesses in recent years. With the acquisition of Amfac,
JMB now handles 2,000 acres of land for development in Hawaii.
   Amfac began as a Hawaiian sugar company more than a century ago.
Deals leading to Thursday's acquisition by JMB included an
unsuccessful management-led proposal for an $800 million leveraged
buy-out.
</TEXT>
